column12: One of my all time favorite place to go with a group.  I don't care for the show and the atmosphere but the teppanyaki style is delicious.  They have the BEST dipping sauces for the meat and veggies!  I wouldn't recommend this place as a great place for Japanese food nor for sushi but I do give it props for their grilled items.

column12:
Just did review of Gyu Kaku and made me think of this place.
Many years ago this used to be a good place to get decent quality
hibachi and cheap rolls/nigiri.
Over the years and quality disapeared and the only Japanese working there were the waitresses.
I ended back in there earlier in the summer and yes..
still the same O~some O
They have a prime location, if you go to SB to shop you will walk by this place. To bad the food doesnt speak for its self anymore.

column12:
To be fair, the place is an extraordinary visual dream.  The counterperson was very accommodating when asked if I would like to order breakfast at 5 to 11.  I did and he asked the chefs not to put the breakfast acudaments away.  Very kind and great service.

 I was terribly excited to meet my husband for brunch during the work week but was slightly disappointed with my order.  Being vegetarian I thought I might try the biscuit egg dish without the egg and enjoy the tomato jam.  It was over cooked, could hardly bite into the biscuit and the jam far too sweet.  

Oh well, perhaps I will just have coffee next time because that was delicious.

column12:
This place is awesome!!! I was a bit apprehensive as this place is a no frills kinda restaurant. I am so glad my husband insisted!

We ordered the shrimp ceviche and clam chowder as appetizers. Both were delicious! They did not skimp on the shrimp and the chowder was filled with buttery goodness. For the main course, my husband ordered the dungeness crab, our son the shrimp tacos and I had the crab sandwich. All dishes were tasty!

The best part about this restaurant is the price! All of this food and drinks for less than $70...can't beat that!!!

column12: Loved this place! I was warned that the wait is very long, but I went on a Thursday right at opening 11am. The service was great and so was the food. We Had the lobster pasta, crab sandwich, clam chowder, & fried calamari and oysters. All we're very delicious! My favorite though was the lobster pasta. Price was not too bad at all! About 60 bucks for all of that plus a beer and Bloody Mary! Definitely going back!

column12:
Great place to eat! My wife had the cioppino with pasta and I had the lobster roll with onion rings.

The cioppino comes in a bread bowl but they substituted the bread with pasta. It was served hot and was delicious! The bowl was crammed with mussels, shrimp, sea scallops and a king crab leg. Loved it!

My lobster roll was nothing to write home about. Bland on flavor and very salty. The meat was minced and unrecognizable as lobster. However, the onion rings were crazy good! Fresh onion wrapped in a light and flakey batter. 

The service was great and our server, Sam, was very nice. We'll be back!

column12: Only 4 tables for outside seating so had to wait for quite awhile. The atmosphere of eating right by the ocean is lovely, however, the few items we tried were just ok. Lobster pasta's lobster is very dry and does not taste like lobster. The sauce is ok. A tad bland. 6 pieces of uni was $21.95 with small slices of raw scallops were also kind of bland together; uni was better on its own. I would the uni at seafood marker instead for half the price. Onion rings were crispy. 3 items costed us $60. Ouch!

column12:
Looking forward to coming back! 
Stopped here for lunch on our way up the central coast based on the reviews. There were a fair number of people waiting in front of us but it only took 10-15min to be seated. Our server was appropriately nice and service overall was good. We chose 1/2 dozen oysters (excellent), a bowl of the clam chowder (excellent), and a lobster roll. As I used to work for a Boston based company, I have had many lobster rolls up and down New England.... the lobster roll at Santa Barbara Shell Fish is one of the best I have ever had. Period. 
I am really looking forward to getting back here soon!

column12:
Pretty pricey for the quality, but you can't beat the vibe and atmosphere.

We've been here a few times and the staff kind of make you feel like a nuisance. 

We got AWFUL food poisoning the first time we came, but gave it another shot and haven't had an issue.

The crab cakes are delish, and definitely a good sized portion. Oysters have been tasty each time we had them, and the tacos are just ok.

column12:
Was taking a day trip to Santa Barbara and saw this cute little seafood shack on the wharf. There was a decent amount of people waiting outside and a clipboard to add your name in the front. Once we got seated service and food was friendly and fast. I got the steamed clams in white wine sauce which were super fresh and delicious. Served with warm and a little charred bread. The broth is light but also a little creamy, loved it. The clams themselves were super pretty too. My boyfriend got the steamed crab with slaw and onion rings, the meat was insanely fluffy and just fell apart once you got it out of the shell. 

We happened to be there while Man vs. Food was filming and got invited to join the show! They brought out the uni on scallop and lime and chapino for us to try on camera. While being on the show was super cool, the food was unfortunately left out for a while waiting for the shoot and got a little cold. I love uni and the uni was sooo fresh, super rich and creamy. Unfortunately not a huge scallop fan so wasn't sure how I felt about the pairing. The chapino is essentially this seafood stew served in a bread bowl. While it looked awesome, I felt the sauce was too heavy for the delicate seafood, almost like a pasta sauce. However, my boyfriends mom had ordered it for lunch and seemed to really enjoy it so perhaps it would have been a lot better if it hadn't been cold. 

Prices are affordable, especially for such a great location. Put your name down, wander the wharf a little, and maybe you'll get to see some seals like we did!

column12: The pizza was okay (nothing extraordinary), the salad bar was misleading (more about it later), but the service was pretty poor. Everyone looked annoyed, the lady working the front was not pleasant or helpful, and they ignored me several times when I needed something. The salad bar looked decent - there was a good variety of greens - but the soups weren't part of the AYCE salad bar deal! I came up to ask for a bowl to access the two soups at the salad bar, and the lady said that it would cost extra! Strangely, there's no soup option in the menu. Anyway, the place is subpar - too pricey for Pizza Hut quality and non-existent customer service.

column12:
Husband and I walk by this place frequently on our evening walks about town. Decided to try it last Friday night for dinner. Read the Yelp reviews; hit or miss it seems. Menu was easy to find on the Yelp page (thank you!) and the food was exactly what we were craving. Burgers, pasta, salads. What really intrigued me and have to admit is the main reason we went, was the pic of the artichoke app on the site.  I LOVE artichokes! I really love artichokes done well and that pic won me over.
Place is very large with outdoor seating on two patios and large indoor seating. This does not include the bar area attached. We sat outside on the top patio.  Greeter was friendly, sat right away. Waitress came over right away. Friendly greeting. Mentioned it was our first time and open to suggestions. She offered a couple (don't recall them) and I shared my excitement for the artichoke app and how it was the reason for us being there.  Ordered the artichoke along with the pappardelle pasta, side of black bean soup, side of mashed potatoes. My husband wasn't super hungry so the side orders were his.  Great way to try a variety of items that all sounded soooo good!
Artichoke app arrived and it was GREAT! Garlic, onion, tomato, yes, yes, yes. Cooked perfectly. Easy to eat the meat off the leaves, leaves pulled off easy from the heart. So happy this was as good as hoped.
Black bean soup tasted ok.  Really thick which was fine but it hardened up pretty quickly and reminded us of chocolate pudding. Mashed potatoes were ok, nothing amazing but liked the skins included and not a lot of butter.  
Pappardelle pasta was very flavorful! Garlic, onion, tomato, olives. Noodles a bit al dente (sp?) which made me very happy. Love big wide noodles. Very large portion, should have shared it but good news, took half home and ate it for lunch the next day! Love pasta that holds up to being as flavorful as the next day. We will be back & try out the bar next time. 
We had an iced tea and water on top of our food, total was $48sh.  Seemed a bit expensive but the overall experience was A-OK!

column12:
Where else can you hit up a winery, or even do a wine tasting on a pier??? Well, I don't know of any in the midwest so this was certainly quite the treat for me!!!  I'm from the midwest and I've done a number of wine tastings...this one was super-cool because you can hang out right on the water on the pier.  I was undecided between ordering a glass or doing a tasting but I opted for a tasting (free taste of chardonnay with your yelp check in!)  They have some very nice, light summery white wines there to try or order a glass of.  Awesome atmosphere at this place! 
The service was super friendly as well!

column12:
What an interesting experience! Drove up here on a Sunday morning to try the tri-tip sandwich and it was well worth the drive! The meat was tender and there's sauce on the side if you like yours a little saucier. I also got the onion rings which were pretty crunchy. 
There are plenty of seatings outside and I kinda enjoyed sitting out in the sun and admiring the scenery with my sandwich. The drive up was a bit scary because it's just one narrow road up the mountain and there's no parking lots or anything, just find a spot along the road and park! Overall, I'd definitely come back again next time I'm in the area!

column12:
I am so glad we had our wedding here!!! I cannot say enough what a pleasure it was to work with Breanna, the venue manager and Eli, the food and beverage director. Our wedding here was a destination wedding, so we were very concerned about making sure all of our family and friends that travelled a long way to get to our wedding had a good time. Being a couple straight out of grad school, we were also very concerned with keeping the cost manageable. Everything worked out on all accounts! 

We first picked the venue for two reasons: the price was right and the venue is GORGEOUS. The pricing was very straightforward, which we really appreciated, and when looking at other options in the Santa Barbara area, the Riviera mansion was pretty comparable with other venues which are not all inclusive (ones where you have to find your own caterer, rent linens, etc etc). Planning a wedding without a coordinator and from across the country, it was also definitely worth it for us to go with a venue that minimized the amount of details we would have to think about.

The looks and layout of the place are what sold us though. With people coming from the east coast and middle of the country, we wanted something that would really showcase Santa Barbara's cool architecture and vibe. The mansion is exactly that.  The layout is also pretty perfect for a multigenerational wedding. We were able to enjoy the California weather for our ceremony and cocktail hour outside, then go inside for dinner, avoiding the cooler night air. Later, we could turn up the party in the bar/dance floor area, while the older folks talked and relaxed on the couches in the living room. It really has something for everyone.

What I didn't realize when we picked it was how absolutely awesome all the staff would be to work with. Breanna was super helpful, answering all my questions promptly and pleasantly, and accommodating my sometimes short notice visits to the area. When we did our walkthrough a couple of days before the wedding, Breanna and Eli paid attention to every detail and made sure we were taken care of, as they did the day of the wedding too. Eli was incredibly attentive and easy to work with! My dad is in the restaurant industry and was in charge of setting up desserts (we had family make some traditional desserts, as well as got some cupcakes from Enjoy Cupcakes- also a great idea!). Eli worked with him to get whatever he needed, risers, tablecloths, etc and was really sweet about it. 

The attention to bartending at the Riviera Mansion deserves a paragraph of its own. Breanna worked with me and the bartender (who's name I forget but has worked there for 20 years and is also incredibly awesome) to create a peach moscow mule as our signature drink (our colors were peach and green) and get it to taste just right. She even arranged it so we had fresh peaches! At the wedding, everyone raved about them, even guests who usually prefer something more manly sounding. The staff had all drinks ready to go for our cocktail hour, and also passed trays of drinks, so there was never a line at the bar (something guests also specifically mentioned that they appreciated). Hell, Eli even followed me with my drink for a couple of minutes around dinner since my hands were full of other things! Really spectacular and attentive service.

Five stars all around. It was absolutely a joy to have our wedding here.

column12:
For fast food, this place is consistently putting out pretty decent food.  Good burgers.  The Mexican food is good too.  My wife and daughter always like the steak fajitas or chicken fajitas.  I like their tacos, usually beef or carnitas pork.   Salsas are tasty.  

The price is low, making this place our go to when we decide not to cook and instead want something easy to grab and go.

column12: The food here is delicious but the manager is horrible shes disrespectful and very rude. I used to come in and have lunch at least once a week but now I just can't make myself go into the place. I've never felt so uncomfortable to order in a restaurant. Really wish they would get rid of the rude women so I could come back in to enjoy the wonderful food. I'm giving this place a 5 stars for the food but for customer service I have to give a -1 star. I've walked into the restaurant and have witnessed the women yelling at the cooks degrading them, when you try to order food she rushes you and gets your order wrong and blames you for it.  This little burger joint can be the best pearl in goleta but she just runs the people away. Very sad.

column12:
Pretty decent food, yummy tacos, pretty tasty tuna melt- a classic burger, beer & fries joint. Their greatest jewels are their excellent ocean views, gigantic sandbox for the kids to play in while the adults get to relax amongst other adults, and great live music (beach music)! Had a great time and fun in the sun, you will too!

In contrast to the very poor food at other beach front food shacks in the Shoreline beach area, the food here is pretty good and beer selection good too.
Enjoy!

column12:
Every Sunday, my family drives to Santa Barbara for the beach, the sun, and the surf. But one of the best parts about our beach day is ordering food from Padaro Beach Grill. I can't say enough how this restaurant brings me and my family pure joy. The food is fantastic, of the best quality, yet not overpriced. My kids love the burgers, my wife is a huge fan of the veggie burger, and the fried Baja fish tacos topped with the smoked tarter sauce are MY favorite. We always order online and the order is ready when they say it will be. They always offer condiments at pick-up, which is a nice touch, and there's always a smile to go along with the food. 

Some people say it's the little things in life that make life worthwhile- when it comes to this phenomenal little restaurant tucked next to the ocean, I'd say that's an observation proven true.

column12:
Padaro's has been a favorite for quite some time. They have a menu that doesn't disappoint. Good appetizers, a solid variety of burgers and sandwiches, and some seafood options. Even a great variety of vegan options. Their margaritas are good, they have a variety of beers, and great outdoor seating. 

Hopefully they open up the sandbox again soon so the kids could entertain themselves. But still a fun time for all.

column12:
That's probably the cheapest Japanese food you can find in Santa Barbara that serves decent food.

I often eat there whenever I need to grab something to eat while shopping in paseo. Their rolls tastes good, as well as their chicken curry bowl, my favorite.

The lady at the counter is very nice and always smiling, even though she doesn't speak English that well she'll do everything to get your order right. However, once served, there is no "waiter" present, since the restaurant is very small, it's more of a to-go / take out kind of place vibe so don't expect a refill on your water!

Side note: Don't drink the tap water they have, I believe they just pour unfiltered tap water into the water fountain.

column12: First time eating here for dinner and the dining room is beautiful, but it is very loud. It's difficult to have conversation. The pasta dish i had was amazing. It was a daily special orecchiette. My 9 year old loved it too. The service was great. The dessert pizza wasn't good. The crust tasted stale, and although the chocolate and marscapone topping was tasty, it couldn't compensate for the dry, tasteless crust. My daughter thought the gelato was too sweet. She like things more sweet than I do, so I didn't want to try it. The creme brulee was okay, but there was half a container left at the end and that's a sure sign that the taste wasn't fantastic.

column12:
We stopped here for breakfast which we normally do each time we are here in Santa Barbara and have always had  a decent breakfast both from the tasty standpoint of it and the service has always been good.
This time, something was a miss, because we were seated right away and had our order taken, our coffee arrived and they the wait began.

We waited, and waited, meanwhile the other table next to us that ordered after us was served. 

The server came by and refilled our coffees and said our order would be right up.  Well ok it was after another 10 minutes. Mind you the place only had about 5 tables full and it was after the morning rush.
 The food did arrive and it was hot, and it tasted ok.  This was the time I wish I had my phone with me with the camera because I would have loved to have taken a picture of my egg dish. I ordered a couple of sunnyside up eggs and sausage.  What I saw on the plate instantly made the whole plate unappetizing. 

Usually I remember getting sausage links in several links.  What I got this time was a piece of sausage about 1/2 and inch  in diameter, about 6 or 7 inches long, that was curled up around it's self.
 Unless I had know it was a breakfast sausage of some kind, I could have mistaken it for something else, especially if it was placed on the sidewalk outside.....

Next time I will bring my camera, you had to have seen this to imagine what it looked like.   I almost sent the whole thing back, but after waiting for such a long time,  I opted to eat.

Aside from the lost order or whatever, either the cook has changed or something else because what use to be a nice hearty breakfast , eggs,  some great potatoes was now a couple of eggs with about 4 or 5 small pieces of potatoes.  Come on, potatoes are cheap, you could at least load the plate so it looked like you were getting something for the 15 bucks to put down in front of the customer.  Denny's for 8 bucks can do it all day, you would think they could make a better effort. My only thought was that they must of run out of potatoes,  and the usual garnish of a sliced orange or fruit, and just decided to plop down the eggs and half handful of potatoes and so be it.
Bring back the old Tre Lune, we'll try it one more time, before we totally write it off.

column12:
RUN do not walk to Yoichi's. But seriously, please go experience this amazing, beautiful place and give it the attention it deserves. Every course was exceptional, both in presentation and in taste. From the homemade sesame tofu to the grilled, whole sweet fish to the mochi crepe at the end, I loved every bite. Service was spot on too. 

My husband and I both agree that it is the best meal we've ever had. Don't go there if you want a spicy tuna roll or fish smothered in sweet sauce. Yoichi's uses the freshest ingredients and lets them shine. There is a delicacy and grace to all the food. There is such attention to detail and precision to all the courses - they even have a local artist make new (gorgeous) dishes for each new monthly menu. 

Liquor license is pending and I'm looking forward to going back and trying the dishes with sake. The only bad part was that very few other people were there with us! Given the quality, this place should have a line out the door.

column12:
I went to this restaurant twice, but only ended up eating the second time. 

The first run with Meun Fan was a complete disaster. My party was lazily motioned over to an empty table, where we sat at and went unattended to for the next 10 minutes. My party wasn't given a waiter and even when we tried to initiate some kind of reaction from the staff ourselves, we remained ignored. This was perplexing to us, especially since the place was not very busy, so we simply got up and left the restaurant. 

My second time with the same group of people was a far better experience. This time we prepared a little more by calling in a reservation. Upon arrival we were seated in an already set up table and promptly received a waitress. The waitress was just fine and from the last experience it was almost just a relief to be talked to at all by the staff. The food turned out to be excellent. All of my party was happy with a mixture of dishes ordered; curries, noodle plates, chow mien. The Thai iced tea was also refreshing and slightly above average portion sizes of the food were provided. The prices were competitive, if not some of the cheaper Thai food you'll find in the area. 

I would be happy to give this restaurant higher than 3 stars had it not been for the very poor service that we received on our first trip to Meun Fan.

column12: This place is unbelievably delicious! The owner was so kind and helpful in putting together a birthday celebration for my grandmother's 95th birthday. My grandmother grew up eating home cooked German food, so it was a special treat for her and the food was everything she (and we) could have hoped for! The atmosphere inside the restaurant is intimate and accented with German heritage. My boyfriend, who had never before tried authentic German food and was dubious about it, keeps telling me how he can't stop thinking about the brockwurst and the homemade pretzels with mustard. He insists that we must return soon... and I have absolutely no arguments. Very good restaurant. Excellent service, food, atmosphere, and overall experience. Thank you!

column12: I love the outdoor space at this brewery. We stop here once in a while just to sit in that great outdoor space and enjoy Santa Barbara sunshine. I have not been the biggest fan of their beer however. I was so happy that we stopped here again this week, they have greatly improved their beer list. They have now added a couple IPAs which are my go to for beer and I really enjoyed them. Third window is connected with a small kitchen area that will serve a limited menu of food. I have been here before when they have had an outstanding soft pretzel but right now they are not making those. I do wish they would bring them back along with this great IPA it is a win-win. But do come by and visit and enjoy the great open air feeling of the area and the great outdoor space to sit.

column12: Note: This review is based strictly on service. Rude rude rude. This place needs a major AA (Attitude Adjustment). I wish the staff members had nametags so I could single out the two people that were so rude to me and my new fiancé the day after we were engaged. As we arrived we were greeted with an expression and comment that made me sick. The waitress looked up at me and questioned us sitting down to wait for my parents.. She gave me a rude look and sharply told me that if I wanted breakfast it wasn't available. Then my fiancé attempted to order from the cashier inside and the man behind the counter without any words spoken through his arm with his thumb out pointing to the other register. I had enough and we walked out (wasting $4 in parking). We are now at another place and loving it.. Note to the owner/manager. If you're trying to save money by hiring cheap labor you're making a mistake. Sometimes cheap wages can make an employee unhappy and in turn they treat customers poorly in turn driving away business. I hope you get that point.

column12: Wow..where do I get started: horrible service, bad food, rude staff. So I came in on the weekend at 8 pm, a whole hour before their closing time. At first I thought, this seems to be a decent place, and I was proved very,very wrong. So first of all, when it was time to order, I ordered several things, including naan, samosa chaat, tomato  soup and chana bhatoora. The waiter said they didn't serve naan and samosa chaat at the time..what the heck! The main thing on their menus that people come for, they don't serve that! So angrily I said fine, I'm just here for dinner I can get through..ugh. So then I talked to my family and friends and my nephew started crying because he was thirsty. It's normal to bring water to your customers isn't it? Well we never even got our water after asking. Finaally after a long wait, I got my chana bhatoora, and man was I happy. And as soon as I took a bite...disgusting! I couldn't even finish the meal! And I never leave wastes. So to make the meal better I asked for onions. I waited 10 mins, then asked again. Once again the waiter ignored me. The third Time I asked, he finally listened to me with a grouchy attitude :( soon as I finished eating, he brought the onions..woow. Then I asked for the bill. It was half an hour before he even brought the check. That was unbelievable considering besides us there was one family of two, so why would it take so long to give me my check? Well so I decided to talk to the owner, who was outside. And it was unbelievably rude! He was on the phone outside, and as soon as he saw me walking towards him, he turned his back and pretended not to see me. I said excuse me in my most patient voice, and he said no I cannot talk shoo away :/ i can't explain how much u should not come here. They are lucky I gave them one star, they should deserve 0 stars!!Don't ever go there. Horrible I tell u

column12: Very nice location, i'd get a reservation or opt to sit at the bar.  Everything here is fresh, just don't be caught off guard by the prices, paying for what you get, which is excellent food, but you are also across the street from the ocean (so pretty much every spot has a ocean view) and everyone knows that Santa Barbara isn't the cheapest place either.  They do have a happy hour which if you are looking for a quick and small bite with a beer, what we did, this place is a good choice, won't break the bank and is good.  The service from the hostess to the bartender were quick and professional.  Overall, its a good place to go.  If you are price sensitive hit their happy hour or check out another spot.  It also would be a great place to take a date if you are looking for seafood based meals.  Good luck!

column12:
Visiting Santa Barbara was just about the best thing we needed after being cooped up, quarantine style, for months. 

Santa Barbara was quite busy on a Saturday in August. Apparently other people had the same idea about getting out. The weather was warm, but the cool beach breeze made up for it. We opted for Bluewater Grill due to the reviews and the amount of outdoor seating available. 

We were lucky enough to get the second story terrace spot which gave us beautiful views of the Pacific Ocean and beach. The sun was hot, but the multiple umbrellas provided a nice respite. 

I opted the for Lobster Roll. They asked if I wanted it chilled or warmed, being that it was a hot day a chilled lobster roll hit the spot. It came brimming with succulent lobster on a toasted roll. Paired with a spicy bloody mary it hit the spot!

column12:
Jonny and Pour SB bartended my wedding this past May and I can't praise him and his staff enough. 

Jonny was very communicative throughout the planning process and was always so nice and friendly, which I really appreciated while in the depths of my wedding-related stress. The bartenders that worked at the wedding were so friendly and nice (per my husband, they were also very cool and funny) and were so quick and efficient with their setup and their service throughout the wedding. 

Jonny put together a beautiful and delicious bar service. I am picky when it comes to alcohol, wine and beer especially, and Jonny totally understood my vision and executed everything excellently. For the wine, I told him the types of wine that I wanted (in this case, Rose, Chardonnay, and Pinot Noir) and Jonny found excellent bottles for great prices. He also hooked things up with beer from one of Santa Barbara's breweries, which was very important to me. The signature cocktails were incredible, with everything made from scratch. I had to try everything because it was all so good, and the morning-after headache was totally worth it! My husband (and our guests) also couldn't stop talking about how good everything was.

My "dream vision" for my wedding, more than anything else, was that it would turn into the most rollicking-good-time ever and Jonny and his team were crucial in making that a reality. Everyone had the best time and I know that we have Pour SB to thank!!

column12:
One of the more disappointing dining experiences I've had in a long while. The server dropped my meal and brought it back with 1/2 the amount of fries :/ then we had servers come to us 3 times with other people's food and drinks. Everything seemed very unorganized. However the atmosphere was pleasant and they go for an upscale modern look that's what gets them 2 stars instead of 1. It's just unfortunate the food quality and taste does not meet the appearance.

We waited quite some time for our food and it arcane out at different times. My ahi tuna sandwich came with a Cajun seasoning that was no where to be mentioned on the menu and was way too hot so I had to send it back. The waiter was nice to replace it and the manager himself brought out my dish. Special treatment! So they obviously care about their customers, which I appreciate. The chickens avocado sandwich was ehhh. Not much too it.

I'll maybe this place just isn't my taste buds because it seems like other people like it according to other reviews. Maybe I need to give it another try. But after having 2 items that were both thumbs down, it's hard to want to.

My friend's Cajun sandwich was not that good. She actually said she was suffering through it and my fiancé's burger was a 2/5. The fries were tastey but cold.

My dog loved her chicken and mashed potatoes though!

column12: I'm going to start off with saying with we've been here before multiple times, and i work in the service industry so i am one of the THE MOST understanding people that can ever walk into a restaurant. We came to celebrate our anniversary, because we've had such great past experiences here. I'm sad to say that I'm very upset on the experience this time. We sat at the bar, you could clearly see that they were short handed (no bartender present) we sat for about 5-7 minutes when we were "greeted" by a young Asian girl who said 'we'll be with you.' Short and not so sweet. Who threw dirty menus at us, and continued to cash out and make drinks and chat up the one woman at the bar next to us. She left and was sat there for another 10 minutes when we saw a gentleman server come in clearly late grab keys from the original Asian server and leave, to come back a few minutes later fix himself and proceed to wait on tables. Yet to hear back from the young Asian girl. Now i know this is unlike the typical service, because we have sat a few times at the bar with Derek who's absolutely amazing! To just get disregarded this time around. I don't know what the issue was, however short handed or not, we shouldn't of sat there for 15 minutes plus with dirty menus, to be basically dismissed. We walked out after about 20 minutes and went and spent $200 somewhere else. 20 minutes was more than generous for us to sit there and wait for the young girl or whom ever to get to us and at least give us water to drink right? Needless to say, i won't be coming back here. After such great experiences tonight killed it, and it's unacceptable. Sorry Vincentas.

column12:
Alito's is a colorful New Mexican restaurant on lower state, and one with big competition.

While Alito's lunch prices are a few dollars cheaper than Los Arroyo's a few blocks up, the food is unfortunately a bit bland. 

The chicken in the chicken carbon tacos was under seasoned, which unfortunately wasn't saved by the similarly-uninspired salsa.

The service was lovely, attentive, and prompt.

To be fair, they're new and are likely smoothing out some kinks. I'll definitely give them another chance in a month or so!

3/5

column12: I nicely want to say I was very disappointed on the margarita pitchers. Since Corazon opened in the public market and in the project I have been coming and enjoying their food and drinks. Yesterday I spent 50 dollars for a margarita pitcher that was full of ice filled up to the top that was served with two cups that were full of ice before pouring drink. The pitcher itself only contained about two glasses of the drink, but not even because the glasses were already pre-full of ice so barely 2 full glasses. The pitcher was also served with a wooden spoon to help prevent the ice from falling out when pouring. I understand restaurants are trying to get back on their feet, but it is upsetting for locals and regulars who want to enjoy this fun restaurant setting but are getting gipped for what you are paying for. If you are going to charge customers that amount please be truthful to what you say you are serving. Overall Corazon serves delicious high quality food, but I will not be buying any drinks there soon if they continue not see how this is wrong and unprofessional in the hospitality industry.

column12:
There's a lot to enjoy about this place! They made some mistakes with my order however, and I feel as though the quality could be better.

Food: I like how they have pre-made bowls available but also the variety of choices to create your own. They forgot to put cucumbers and fried garlic in my bowl however, the crabmeat is a little dry, the rice is also quite clumpy and the fish portion was a bit small. In addition, I can't taste any sauce. I did come at the last hour though so could totally be end of the day mishap. The quality of the rest of the ingredients was still pretty good and I like how they have Nori. The matcha kiwi drink is also to die for!

Service: Besides messing up my order, they're really nice and very timely with the orders so this made up for other cons.

Overall, not the best experience but would still come again as the food was still delicious regardless!

column12:
Our party of 8 showed up on a Thursday night and it was packed. Luckily we had a reservation so there was no wait. The water and bread came quickly, and our waitress took our orders shortly afterwards. 

The calamari appetizer was quite delectable. The batter was nice and light, but there were crunchy pieces in there as well. 

I had a small bowl of clam chowder, but it was very hearty. Every spoonful of soup had clams in it. However, the soup was too salty for me. I was not able to taste the clams as much as I would like. 

My entree, however, was very disappointing. As a college student, I don't often spend $26 on just an entree. But when I do, I expect it to be done well, especially when I'm ordering fish and the name of your establishment is Enterprise "Fish" Company. My cut of Salmon was dry and extremely firm. When I went at it with my fork, instead of flaking, the fish came apart more like carnitas. Every bite would get caught in my throat and refuse to go down. 

The rice that came with the salmon was also terrible. Every 2 or 3 bites, I would get a piece of rice that was hard, hard enough to get wedged between my teeth. I regret spending so much on my entree and barely eating half of it.

The service at the restaurant was not bad. Our waitress was very patient with us. My water cup was never empty (I must have went through 4 or 5 glasses of water). Our plates were cleared as soon as we were finished with them. Everyone was polite and friendly. Props to the wait staff! 

I would have given 3 stars, but according to Yelp, that means "A-OK". My experience at this establishment was definitely not OK.

column12: Went there with a group from LA that came up on the Santa Barbara Daylight Vino Train.  I've had the Salmon with a dijon fennel sauce in the past and that's fantastic.  Today I had the the sea bass and it was great.  The clam chowder was a touch salty.  The big problem was the service.  Our drink orders were taken right away but it took forever to get our food order taken.  In the meantime, two of our group not only ordered their food but got it delivered and had dessert!  The wait for our order took a bit too long as well.  When we did get our order is was quite tasty.  When I got the bill for my portion I was charged for the chowder which should have been one of my sides that was included with the meal.  I will say our server was quite nice but I think she was a bit overwhelmed with our large group and her other customers.

column12:

Hats off to you handlebar, that was a great latte matched by a great experience.

column12:
After reading the reviews on yelp for Sandbar I really thought to pass!! Thankfully we went anyways and could not have had a better experience!!!  The patio is perfect for  people watching and spending a long afternoon with good company.  We never  felt rushed!! As visitors we were simply looking for good ambiance and the outside patio  was GREAT!! Firepits and heating lamps!!  

The service was friendly and attentive and would not hesitate to return.  The guacamole was fresh and Fajitas were very good.  We were lucky to be there for happy hour which is actually a real happy hour w 2 for 1 drinks!!  Oh and they have flat screens everywhere with various sports throughout the day!

Many compliments to the manager Art and his staff as I was really expecting far less and felt compelled to ask for him only to to offer my compliments after reading less then desirable reviews.  Great experience at Sandbar and obvious they care about your experience!  Highly recommended for a chillin good time!

column12:
One of the worst dining experiences ever. Absolutely terrible service. 

For starters, as everyone around us was getting their complimentary chips and salsa, we had to ask for ours long after ordering our drinks. The food was only so-so, but we also had to ask for plates, napkins AND utensils to eat our food with! Silly me, thought these things normally came without asking at a restaurant. To top things off, I saw our server dip her hands into the heating drawer, take out a tortilla chip and dip it into the vat of salsa that they serve customers from and eat it. She did this several times! Now I'm no expert, but I'm pretty sure that is a health code violation of some sort. 

I will never go here ever again.

column12: Terrible, just plain terrible. My friends and I went to have some fun and unfortunately had an awful experience. Their alcohol was so disgusting that my friend could not swallow it so she spat it out. A worker thought she was trying to throw up, which she wasn't, and kicked us out. Did not listen to any explanations we had and just kicked us out over an assumption. How is that a way to run a business? We paid for nasty alcohol that we couldn't even swallow and got kicked out over it? If they'd at least had better customer service to combat their terrible alcohol, it would have made sense but how do you expect to stay in business when you treat your customers like trash. There are way better places in downtown Santa Barbara, I wouldn't even come back if they begged me.

column12:
Being new to the area, I've explored different types of places for food, drinks and entertainment.  Somehow, I find myself gravitating back to Eureka.  The Santa Barbara location is as good as it gets in the area for multiple reasons.  The food selection is diverse, yet simple enough to sort through for a quick and casual meal.  Their burgers, of course, being their hallmark; try their fish tacos.  I've yet to grow tired of them-they're fresh, definitely full of flavor, and resonably priced.  But you won't be able to go wrong anywhere on their happy hour menu, so try everything at least once.  If you sign in for a table and there's a short wait, be patient; it will be worth it.

The over 30 beer selections available represent the best of every variety brewed in the western U.S.  Try testing your bartender by letting them know what you like, and I guarantee they can offer you 2 or 3 terrific selections that will make it difficult to decide on just one!  It's not just about being able to brew your own.

One thing that keeps me coming back is the staff from top to bottom.  The bartenders are friendly, respectful, and true beer geeks.  And with their rotation of brews, they really do keep up with the best beers in the area.  The place is managed extremely well;  I've met the management staff and it's evident they truly care about their customers, about service, and about the food quality.  We've all been to places that lack good management, and it shows.  This place is a well-oiled machine.  Every staff member I've been in contact with has demonstrated true hospitality.  Whether an afternoon lunch, or dinner time, I have really felt comfortable here with every visit.

column12: Food is good. Or...was good. Tonight we went in for dinner. We've been to Eureka over 10 times, at least. The food is always good. Until tonight. My husband and I, taking advantage of their happy hour, ordered their nachos. We've had them before and they are yummy. But tonight, instead of cubed moist chicken they gave us soggy, shredded, crock-pot like chicken. Also, the nachos are supposed to come with beans. I counted the beans.......there were 7 total beans (I sent it back asking for more beans and my plate came back with MAYBE 12 beans). Flavor was lacking. My son ordered the corn dog pops. He loves their cheddar-IPA sauce. Our server did not tell us that the restaurant no longer made this sauce (despite us requesting two sides of it), and instead brought two sides of spicy mustard sauce (he's a little kid! What was the thinking there??). I have one other complaint that I have felt for awhile, that being that the service is T.E.R.R.I.B.L.E. Don't go in there expecting to get your drinks in a timely manner. You are lucky if you get them before your meal. And even more lucky if a server comes up to you to take your order at all.

column12: I'm writing this for my boyfriend.  He would give it five stars  He Loves This Place!!  Orders as follows:  #16, 14,19. Sopes (if available), Tacos de bistec.  Usually the same thing.  I'm pretty sure the #19 is the frijoles.  Not your usual refried beans.  This is how we make beans at home.  I don't eat tortillas, so, pretty pointless for me here. (My bf gets all my tortillas.)  But, the #16 is my favorite too.  Also the  roasted chiles pasillas stuffed with cheese.  The chile rellenos are very good too.  The owner has let us try a couple of new dishes to give him feedback.  Good stuff.  Not your usual Mexican food.  If you want the usual go to Del Pueblo or Rose Cafe (yuck) one of those type of places.   Yes the wait is long.  I usually end up talking  to the out of towners, see a lot of the regulars and lots of friends.  One thing I don't like is the table snatchers.  These are the people who send in friends or family to snatch a table way before they are up to order.  That's not cool.  Wait your turn like the rest of us.  Usually works out though.

column12:
This might be my favorite restaurant in the world. You can't beat it for the price point. The fresh-made tortillas are amazing. The #16 is always good: marinated pork, peppers, and cheese. The chorizo quesadillas are fantastic. Some of the best meals though are on the Specials menu. On Mondays they have great chilaquiles. Not sure which days these are, but the fish tamales, veggie tamales, and veggie chile rellenos are incredible. 

It's not a standard taqueria: no chips, no burritos. It's cash only and closed on Tuesdays and Wednesdays. If it's peak hours on a weekend be prepared for a wait. But weekdays before 5:00 or after 8:15 or so it's usually not bad at all. And to all the people who say the food is not flavorful, I'm guessing you ordered the plain steak taco, what did you expect? There are tons of super flavorful choices. And again, the real gems are in the daily specials menu. I'd give it more stars if I could.

column12: Ingredients are fresh and tasty, and there is a yummy bit of extra oregano on every pie. Request thin crust if you want something closer to NY style. Love the grated Mozz. on the salads. Now the not so great news: we used to order from this location every Friday. The staff was efficient, friendly, knew me by name, etc., a few months ago the entire crew seems to have been replaced. Phone orders are difficult, everyone is out of synch, incredibly slow...I take the extra time to order/pick-up from the mesa location now, with the hope that the owners will read this in earnest and do something. This location was a 5 before, but the current service gets it a 3.

column12:
Eh... I wouldn't recommend this place for anything besides breakfast, but if it's a breakfast you're looking for, this place is a definite go to spot.  The service is kind of slow so if you're the impatient type in the mornings, call in your order and then come pick it up.  If you're a slow starter like me, well we're good to go.

All the food they serve here are excellent and while the price is a bit pricey, in return you get a whopping large meal for it.  If there's any downside to it, it would be that the foods aren't really cajun.  They just make use of some cajun recipes.

column12:
I really appreciate the authenticity of this place. There is nothing I love more than authentic Mexican food and this place does not disappoint. They are generous with portions and have something for most dietary needs. 

Today I ordered the veggie burrito and was very satisfied. The veggies consist of zucchini, celery, mushrooms, bell peppers, and onions. It also comes with Mexican rice, beans, cheese, and sour cream. I asked them to hold the cheese and sour cream and it was still very tasty. 

I'm giving this place five stars because I've been to a couple of other Mexican food places around town and their veggie options are not as good as here. The portions and prices are also great!

column12:

column12:
I was a little tentative to try as I thought it was a chain, but i'm really glad I did per a recommendation from a coworker. And I'm super glad I did! I got the carnitas and it was fantastic. It was moist, flavorful and nicely crisped in the cast iron little skillet. Great fresh guacamole that came with it and the really nice addition are the house-made corn tortillas which were perfect to pair. Really loved the grilled green onion and also a nice grilled pepper as well. All paired wonderfully together especially with the great stocked salsa bar.

Friendly staff, good service. Great meal!

column12: My favorite food in Santa Barbara. My friend took me here and everything was spot on. The layout is very casual; you go up to the counter and order what you want, pay there, and sit down with a # where they will bring the food directly to your table. In the interim, you will get house-made fresh chips, which you can eat with any of the salsa from their grab-your-own-condiment station. That in and of itself is already where you know you're going to have a good meal. But then the main courses come and you've treated to dishes that hit all the marks; fast, affordable, delicious. We had ceviche which was fresh and came with a very generous portion of seafood; it is enough to be a dinner in and of itself. But then I had mole enchiladas which were deeply savory and sweet. You're likely to have leftovers, which is a double edged sword. Good because it's delicious, bad because it means it'll take you longer before you're hungry enough to come back and try the rest of the items on their menu.

column12:
FIRST TIME EATING POKE!!

I've always been a little nervous about trying raw seafood, but Choppa Poke helped ease this transition. The chunks of ahi tuna that I got tasted fresh and delicious, and along with the bounty of other toppings, it felt like i was eating a buffet in a bowl. The sauces are amazing, the rice is perfectly cooked, the add-ons had a huge variety of textures and flavors... and in great portion sizes, too!!! You do get what you pay for, which I really appreciate. 

Definitely coming back to this spot; the food is delicious, the place itself is super hygienic and COVID-friendly, and it's just a super great, filling meal to end my day with.

column12: I love the PALMS! Four of us drove up from Camarillo yesterday for my birthday. Overall our experience was similar to previous visits. We are familiar with the menu and the how the do-it-yourself idea works. The food was great. Almost everything went well. So why not 5 stars? THE SERVER WAS A BIG PROBLEM. We sat in a practically empty room staring at our water glasses for about five minutes before another staffer noticed us and reminded our server we were waiting. She did the bare minimum to keep from ignoring us during our entire meal. When two different groups of people she knew arrived it was like old home week - kiss, kiss, hug, hug. Meanwhile I was sitting with an empty glass and she never even asked if I would like another drink. Silly move, since tips are usually calculated on service, and the amount of the bill. I wasn't impressed when she handwrote suggested tip amounts for 15% and 20% on the bill.The "service" was barely worth 10%. If we have the same server the next time we go to The Palms I won't hesitate to ask to be seated in someone else's section.

column12:
Old schoolers rule and this place is a local legend. Basically this is a meat and potatoes place where you choose your protein(different cuts of beef, seasonal fresh fish (halibut or salmon this time), chicken, pork chops, or rack of lamb) and you cook it yourself on a communal grill after spicing it up with a variety of dry spices. All meals come with baked potato and salad bar. Prices are very reasonable. Service was great and helpful. Definitely will be back!

column12:
Excellent service
Delicious, seasonal food

My favorite restaurant in the Santa Barbara area.  Unlike the 5 Points location, the Goleta one has ample, hassle-free parking.   They have tons of seating inside and out.  

The menu has fresh, seasonal ingredients.  They have daily specials in addition to their regular menu.  My husband enjoys their pasta dishes and halibut fish and chips.  I love their quiches, salads and sandwiches.  Their fresh made soups are delicious and flavorful.  My favorite is the corn chowder.

Best dessert - the chocolate mousse "ball".  I forget the actual name of it, but you'll know it when you look in the pastry case.  

Also - a great venue for private parties.  I hosted my mother's birthday there and they did a fabulous job.  We've used them numerous times for catering as well and have always been satisfied.

column12:
Fresco has very good sandwiches, soups, and inventive salads. Today I enjoyed a hot pastrami that was generous with the meat and really yummy. Their soups are house-made and flavorful. They also have pizza, pasta and other specials of the day. You order at the counter and your food is brought to your table. The patio out front is pleasant on a nice day. 

The service is decent usually, but today a young blonde with her hair in a bun was downright unpleasant when serving our food. Her attitude was sour, sullen, and just unacceptable. If you work with the public, leave your bad attitude at home, please.

column12: Great casual spot for breakfast or lunch. The young staff is friendly and helpful and service was timely. I enjoyed sitting on the patio out front. There's ample seating both inside and out and Cafe Int'l can easily accommodate groups. I enjoyed delicious eggs Benedict one morning and an excellent hearty Italian omelet another day. Today I hit the cafe around noon and decided to sample the BLAT s sandwich with a side Caesar salad. It was great! Crispy bacon with lots of avocado and fresh slices of lettuce and tomato were perfect with the salad that had a really tasty Caesar dressing. The menu is so big, I look forward to trying some of the other offerings. Friends have said their soups and potato salad are really good too!

column12: Food was hit or miss - when it hit, it was great, like the salmon, but other dishes were really quite... strange (bad) like the tacos and the grilled avocado (interesting concept, lame execution).  Service from our waiter was really awful, however- slow, uncaring, and got part of the order wrong with no acknowledgement.  My drink sat empty most of the meal.  Food runners seemed nice, so this was probably just one bad guy/bad night, but there seem to be much nicer places in SB.  I'd check them out before coming here.

column12:
This place was pretty disappointing even though it had great service. I wanted to give it one star but because the service was pretty good, I'm giving it two stars. 

I came here with a friend for lunch because my future sister-in-law recommended this place. I ordered the salmon salad and my friend ordered the beet salad. 

I applause the chef for creativity and presentation, but the salmon salad was sooooooo bad. The salmon tasted too fishy and it was a little tough. The chef had also included potatoes and egg crumbles, and with the salmon, just was not a good combination. I also noticed that there was some sort of salad dressing, but it did not go well at all with any of the food. 

I don't know what the chef was thinking when he was preparing my food, but I've never tasted a salad so terrible in my life- and it's pretty hard to mess up salad! Suffice to say, I only picked at my food and didn't even bother to box up the leftovers because I don't think anyone deserves to eat this stuff. I definitely will NOT be coming back here again!

column12:
We heard good things about Sun Sushi, but unfortunately we had a bad experience. The most disappointing was the sushi. Both such rolls (Box and Rainbow) has no flavor. The fish was too cold and very low grade sushi. 

We've been all over the world eating sushi and even lived in Asia (Japan for 2 years) for more than 6 years. This was some of the worst restaurant sushi we've experienced. When we got home we both had to eat something to get the taste out of our mouth. 

We're heading back to Arigato Sushi -- they are consistently great with sushi.

column12:
Anniversary sushi dinner!!! Last year when we were in Santa Barbara, we had sushi on the other end of state street. This was much better then downtown!!! 

We started with seared albacore carpaccio. This was an amazing cut of fish, lightly seared and full of flavor! We then ordered three rolls: Tiger Roll, Mexican Roll and Spider Roll!  Two thumbs up for sure!!! The sushi chefs were amazing, staff very friendly, and service was great!!  Glad to find this little hole in the wall on the upper end of State Street!

column12:
Although I didn't get a chance to actually shop here, I walked inside for a while during Christmas Eve and thought this Spanish colonial revival mall square is definitely a really cool place to check out! Paseo Nuevo is downtown Santa Barbara's biggest shopping square so most festivities will probably happen here. You will also find your typical mall chain stores, although even if you don't shop, a stroll through here is a nice experience as well! 

Its parking garage allows 80-minute free parking, so why not come by and check this shopping center out?

column12:
Came here for dinner tOnight and had a great experience. We got a last minute reservation at 8:45pm seating. Ordered :

1) clam chowder - interesting take on chowder
2) french onion soup - good, great for dipping 
3) giant prawn cocktail - huge size & fresh! 6 pieces
4) aged New York strip - cooked medium, great flavor 
5) abalone pasta - so fresh & delicious, a bit tarty 
6) lobster mac n cheese - good portion size, couldn't finish! 

They had delicious table side breads too. Really like the olive bread. So fluffy, perfect to dip in the soups. 

Very pricey meal, but nice ambiance and friendly staff.

column12:
Solid experience. Outdoor seating is spacious and atmosphere is super nice. I got the Chitarra Pasta which was pretty good. A dish full of shrimp for all the shrimp lovers. 

My husband got the Angel Oak Signature 52 Day USDA Prime which was very good! It did not need any sauce (although you can ask for one for an additional $5). Also got a side of mashed potatoes which were very buttery and creamy. Lastly I got the banana split dessert. If you're looking to finish your meal with a dessert I recommend passing on this one and try a different one. Wasn't my favorite. 

Overall, service was solid. Not as bad as I thought it would be (considering the reviews) and a very nice place to go if you're staying at The Ritz-Carlton and looking for a nice fancy meal with good wine.

column12:
I like it here a lot. The atmosphere is nice and the workers are soooo nice, I even brought the habit in here to eat once because my bf wanted pho but i wanted burgers and they were totally fine with it, no weird or dirty looks haha.  And they're fine with you hanging out too. 

The food is good, my bf is a big Pho fan, so he knows good pho, and over here they have  good pho. Way better than the place near Kmart and the one IV. I'm vegetarian and I ordered the egg foo young, and wow I had a lot of things to eat, a lot. (it came with fried rice, egg rolls, wontons and soup)  lol Which isn't a bad thing, a lot is really cool and for the price. It tasted good, decent. 

Oh and the food comes out SUPER fast, which is very suspicious, but everything is still really good. Great place! Also the hot tea complimentary is awesome!

column12: I visited on a hot Saturday 10/3/20 for lunch with a friend. There was a 20 minute wait and the hostess directed us to a small cart serving a choice of two beverages: spritzer and margarita, we ordered one of each. The cost was $51.00, which I would not mind if it was not in plastic, no where to sit and no shade umbrellas while waiting. We ordered lunch from small menu: a hamburger and bratwurst with pretzel, waitress suggested fried pickles as well as there was no sides. The burger was average, the bratwurst juicy but the pretzel was stale. In both of our opinions the food was over salted and service below average.  The only redeeming elements were the setting with beach views, manicured gardens and smartly dressed staff.

column12: I was not a fan of Tap Thai on upper State street as it seemed like Thai food for people who don't want too much spice and flavors.  I always go to Your Choice if I am in the area.  I still decided to give the new Tap Thai a try after two bad experiences at the Goleta Meun Fan Thai.  I was pleasantly surprised at the fresh flavors and the spice level seemed higher than their State street location.  The portion size was also more generous than the other Thai places in Goleta, especially for the noodle entrees.  I enjoyed the fresh papaya salad, but wish they offer the option of adding salted crab to really kick up the flavor.  I ordered yellow curry, but received Panang curry instead.  I have never been to Thai, so I have no idea what authentic Panang curry taste like.  The Panang curry here is on the sweet side, which suits the American palate.  Pad see ew was standard, fat rice noodles stir fried with eggs, broccoli, fried tofu, and sweet soy.  Garlic fried chicken wing came with an order of 3 whole wings (6 sections of wings).  The wings were very crispy without being too dry, however, it could use more salt before they were fried.

column12:
Just woke up and decided to drop by because this place was right across from where me and my girlfriends were staying at. 

Was seated outside and had a terrific view of the water.  Our waitress was really nice and introduced her favorites on the menu.  Overall the food was standard, not spectacular, just standard. While we waited the seagulls kept us company but we were told not to repay them back in food. 

I'd say it was a nice place to chill with fresh seafood. 

The lasting impression was made by the shrimp shooter. Its like a shot glass with cocktail sauce and a piece of shrimp or oyster depending on what you order. It was A M A Z I N G G G... I think it'll be the closest I'll ever get to knowing how Peter Parker felt when he first transformed into the Spiderman. My friend described the feeling after you take it as, "heightened senses"... I cannot agree more... haha. You literally SEE clearer, HEAR better, BREATH deeper... That shot definitely woke us up. A Must Try! 

I'd definitely come back for the shooters, not so much the seafood. 

check out my pictures :  )

column12:
Upon the recommendation of our hotel, (Milo; who received a negative review) we dined at brophys.  The food, except the salad was sub par at best. The house salad was great, you could tell they made that salad dressing in house. The calamari was well cooked and the fryer oil was clean, no notes of burnt oil at all. The crab cakes, we're terrible. I suppose being from Maryland, an area who's only attribute is its crab produxts, I can be a snob... but these tasted like they came pre made from safeway. The blackened sea bass was burnt, there is a difference between blackened and burned. The mai tai was all clear rum and quite devoid of flavor. Kudos for attempting to get us drunk but we didn't order shots. 

The service was great, the only thing saving the second star. A plethora of attendants made us feel very well taken care of. 

Over all I would say they need to make their food match their menu descriptions and they would have a solid recipe for success.

column12:
I don't know what to say here. The food is amazing, the location is stunning (during the day or at night). It is VERY popular for good reason. 

The service is always friendly even when busy. Camp out at the bar after checking in, the best seats in the house are at the bar. 

Fresh seafood, causal environment, just a great spot and any trip to Santa Barbara is not complete without a meal here. 

If you haven't been here already - don't bother because it's already too crowded. To the haters....if you let them know about a problem they will fix it if they can - or just don't come.

It is not gourmet fine dining (not Michelin ranked - go to the Biltmore for that), but it is just so simply good. 

If you don't like it, you don't like seafood. Order the burger (but why? It is really good too but...)

column12:
Made an overnight trip to Santa Barbara during my west coast visit back in April, located this place based on the good reviews & the fact that it was about a 10 minute walk from our hotel. There was about a 20-30 minutes wait. We got a round of drinks at the bar upstairs & ordered and appetizer but ended up getting a table sooner than estimated, which was fine as we were hungry. The place was packed so we were generally happy with the decision to eat here. The staff was very friendly & the service was efficient. 

We tried the beer boiled shrimp for appetizer, had a good flavor to it, shrimp  have the shell/skin on. We got their house cesar salads which were really fresh & the dressing had a bit of a kick to it. Two of us decide to go with their Seabass dusted with Cajun spices- served with a rice pilaf & coleslaw. I have to say it was one of THE BEST Seabass I've had. The Cajun seasoning added so much flavor. One of my friends ordered the crab cakes (served with fries & coleslaw) and those were really yummy too. 

We thoroughly enjoyed our meal, everything was really fresh & it was very reasonably priced as well.

column12:
Finally got to try Brophy Bros and we didn't haven't to wait in line for hours! This has been one of the most recommended restaurants in town since I moved and it didn't disappoint. 

Food - Some of the best seafood in town. The calamari was so tender and crisp. For the main course we had salmon and sea bass which were cooked perfectly. Portions are generous and the prices are very reasonable.

Ambience - You must sit on the second floor outside patio! The views of the harbor and the Santa Ynez mountains in the background are incredible. The restaurant definitely encapsulates old school Santa Barbara.

Service - Compared to the other reviews on here I think we lucked out, as we only had to wait 15 minutes. Waitresses were friendly and our food was prepared quickly.

column12:
So I came over last night to have dinner, finished eating and paid within 30mins. (the WORST 30 mins meal EVER!)

First of all, food wasn't that great besides the Chili Cheese Fries. I got SMOKED CHICKEN, BACON & SPINACH PIZZA and it tastes like NOTHING! You can't taste the cheese, nor the bacon. I had to add salt and pepper to get some taste. But that's not the worst...

THE WORST PART WAS THEIR SERVICE!!

The server "N", asked us if we needed boxes when we weren't even half way done with our food. Like what is this? Rushing us to leave? WE JUST STARTED OUR FOOD! The restaurant wasn't packed, no one was waiting for a seat, AND! it wasn't even near the time of closing, it wasn't even 8pm yet. And she asked if we need boxes. I was on my second slice of pizza, and my friends still have 3/4 of food in their plate and we were asked if we need boxes. One of my friend said "No, I don't need boxes" and the server brought back boxes and asked her again if she wanted a box. She already said no, she doesn't want a box, just leave her alone. Before we even started boxing our food, the server brought over our checks. 

Yeah, probably not coming back again. Also, we left her some comments on the receipts "thanks for giving us boxes when we weren't even half way done with our food" and more...
So without mentioning her name, she knows who she is. 

If that happens to you in the future, let her know YOU WEREN'T DONE, so she can process it whatever is going on inside her head.

If you wanna sit right on the beach, with your feet in the sand, this is a must stop in Santa Barbara!

column12:
The food here is not what I expected. Everything tasted average not worth what they charge you! 

I read the bad reviews but went here for a birthday dinner so I didn't want to spoil my friends plans and thought we will find out ourselves if the reviews are true. Well sorry to say but I wouldn't recommend this place to anyone! Please save your money and time. 

Service was horrible!!! Waiter was very rude. 

The restaurant was even notified ahead of time of our big party and they reassured us that would be ok. Apparently they were not prepared for our big party at all...

Moral of my review is don't waste your time here!! They don't even deserve one star.

column12: While lines can be intimidating, especially on weekends and holidays, this place runs like a well oiled machine so waits are totally tolerable and once you have a table, service is friendly and efficient. Breakfast served all day, which is great if you are traveling to/from the central coast wine tasting and get a late start! We got the Two by Two by Two, the Susan breakfast burrito, and plenty of treats for our two dogs. That's right... A TRULY dog friendly place! Eggs were light and fluffy, bacon perfectly crisp, and French toast moist and cinnamon-y. Any omelette can be turned into a burrito... Mmmm! Anyone who complains about their water policy (no tap, just $1 bottles of Voss at cost due to phase 2 drought conditions in area) seriously needs to rethink their priorities.

column12: Cute little cafe off the 101 on the way to Santa Barbara. Good selection of sandwiches and a decent kids menu. The Indian Summerland chicken sandwich was decent. The charging for water thing was a bit annoying but understandable due to the drought.

column12:
I have to say I had great expectations when I ate here on my Birthday in October.  I was very disappointed because I was expecting a awesome steak.  Since it was my bday I ordered the Cowboy cut rib eye thinking it would be one of the best steak dinners I had ever had and I was very disappointed.  It just didn't have any grilled flavor, it was kinda grey all over and even though I ordered it medium rare it was well done around the edges and pretty rare in by the bone.  

 Service left something to be desired as well.  Someone at my table had to ask the waiter what the better and oil were for before he noticed we were never served any bread.

I will go to Ruth's Chris next year in search of a top notch steak.

column12: Look, I (once) loved this spot. But they got lazy...they are out of menu items, it's dirty, the food is prepared inconsistently and the menu has been the same since I moved here in 2003. I get they are authentic Mexican, but so is this whole town. Los Agaves, Los Arroyos, Super Cucas...Pastorcito.... You aren't the best (like them) and you are barely average at best. It would be nice if the counter help (the little white college kid who works there now) didn't text (from a table in the dining room) instead of cleaning the tables. Poe training. Average food. Dirty. Pick up your game.

column12:
First off, I only ordered delivery but I feel confident in this review as I have eaten in the restaurant many times over the years . The only reason I'm giving this 2 stars instead of 1 is because they actually delivered the food on time on Christmas Eve. I probably should have known better. My taste for Chinese food has waned over the years.

We ordered beef with broccoli , dry sautéed green beans and vegetable chow mien. The beef sauce was heavy and unappealing. The chow mein was bland and worse of all The green beans tasted like fish! I literally threw over half the food in the trash and wound up eating christmas cookies all night instead. I will not be ordering from them again.

column12: We stopped by this restaurant while on vacation in Santa Barbara, CA.  We found it through Yelp, it had multiple good reviews, close to our hotel, and wanted some good Californian style Mexican food.  Our experience was terrible.  Maybe we caught them on a bad night, but the food tasted like it was right out of the microwave.  My wife got the chicken fajitas and I got the colorado burrito.  The chicken was not fresh for the fajita and they brought her out 2 hard and crusty tortias.  My burito came out on a dinner plate with nothing else on it but one large dry burrito (very visually unpleasing) and the colorado sauce taste like it came right out of bottle and pouring over the meat last minute as opposed to what I'm used to with a good slow cooked and extra tender juicy meat.  I hate writing bad reviews and usually I won't, but I wanted to warn other potential guest like myself so they are not completely disappointed like I was.  I never leave food on my plate and usually eat the rest of my wifes dinner, but we both left with half plates of food and a bad taste in our mouths.  The service wasn't bad and hopefully I just came on a very off day.

We stopped by on a busy Saturday night after being rejected from several other restaurants in the area for not making a reservation (my bad!) but Santo Mezcal was great and found us a table in no time. We got the queso for an appetizer -- a MUST get! I was so full I didn't have a chance to take but a bite of my enchiladas. My husband opted for the salmon tacos and he said they were yummy. The service was amazing...atmosphere great...and the staff were as sweet and accommodating as could be! We will certainly be back. If for nothing else, thank the queso!!!

column12: We had dinner here a couple of nights ago. The place was packed and looked promising. I ordered the combo plate with a chicken taco and chicken enchilada per the servers suggestion. The chicken in both was bland and underwhelming. The hubby got the shrimp and halibut tacos with beans and rice. He said the beans and rice were the best part of the meal. Again the fish was under seasoned and both tasted like a mango salsa taco. The best part of the meal for both of us was the chips and 3 different salsas. It was more of a bar atmosphere and we couldn't even hear each other which added to the disappointment of the evening. If you're looking for a loud bar with average, bland Mexican food this is your spot!

column12:
This place isn't bad, but it's not really worth the price. It's owned by the same folks as Los Agaves, and the food is literally identical to the food served at Los Agaves, just with $5 or so added to the price. I don't know how they can justify that.

On top of being overpriced, the service is far less than what it should be. Our waitress was incredibly pushy, trying to get us to order guacamole and ceviche several different times, selling us large drinks without asking what size we wanted, etc... you get the idea.


Poor service and overpriced. Not worth visiting.

column12: Is it a five star restaurant?  Uhhhh no!  Are the tacos excellent?  Not if you are looking for Taco Bell.  If you are looking for authentic Mexican street tacos that are tasty and cheap, then you have found the right spot.  I had the beef, pork and chicken fajita tacos.  The pork tacos were my favorite, and they were tasty.  I'm glad I trusted Yelp and tried this place.  You could easily be forgiven for passing on this restaurant if you did not know any better.  They take credit cards, and the service was friendly and fast.  I would eat there again if I found myself in downtown Santa Barbara craving some street tacos.   As near as I can tell, they only serve tacos, but you can get tacos made from beef lips or eyes or tripe (see the pic).

column12:
Extremely inexpensive, unpretentious, tasty and fun.

Lilly's tacos does serve many offal meats you won't find everywhere, but it's not just a novelty. It's honest, very well prepared, very simple food, using all kinds of cuts that are unfairly underused. I will admit that the first time I had eye tacos, it was a bit of a dare, but now I order it from time to time, simply because it's good (and, really, not all that different from other cuts of beef).

Next time you go, one of your tacos should be tripe, extra crispy. The texture and the taste are different from the other meats, and it's become my favorite. 

The cart with all the fixings (salsas, herbs, lime, etc.) is always well stocked with quality ingredients which empower you to make each taco truly yours. 

The place is not particularly attractive, but the people are very friendly and the service is very fast. 

HIGHLY RECOMMENDED

The complimentary dish of homemade pickles was 5 stars on its own.

column12: The food was great and the ambiance was perfect to celebrate a special occasion! Our group started with three apptizers: the crabcakes, the artichoke prepared two ways, and the tomato mozzarella salad. They were all delicious but a bit small to share among six people. I ordered the ribeye steak which was cooked to perfection and topped with a tomato jam and blue cheese deliciousness. Some of the other dishes ordered at our table were delicious as well. The Mac n Cheese was amazing! Our only complaint was that we had to ask 3 times for bread from the waitress, while she was more concerned with us ordering more drinks...overall this place is a must visit.

column12:
Saw this place on Diner's Drive-Ins and Dives. We had the lengua tacos, very good, and the carne asada burrito - HUGE and very tasty. I had it with the rice and beans, and got the "hot" green salsa. 

We also ordered pozole to go. While the other food we ordered was good, this was AMAZING! And they serve it every day. 

There are tables to sit down, but NO BATHROOM. Friendly staff, clean. The only negative were the flies.
