column12:
Appalling service (if I could give zero stars I would).

I just came from dinner here. I've had better service drunk at 2am at IHOP.

I've been coming here for birthdays and other special occasions for over 15 years, and tonight, that tradition ended.

We wanted to celebrate our sister's engagement, so we thought the Biltmore would be the perfect place to do that. 

Here's what went right:
-The red wine.

Here's what went wrong:
- seated at kitchen entrance, after calling twice earlier that day requesting we be seated at a quiet table specifically away from the kitchen.
-wine glasses and water glasses were used interchangeable by the waiters - who had no idea that there is a difference between red, white, and water glasses. I enjoyed white wine water when the waiter filled my white wine 'glass' with water.
-we had to ask for the candle on our table to be lit.
-the waiter never greeted us to go over the menu. In fact, I'm pretty sure two bus boys waited on us the whole night.
-the white wine was warm, and although the bus boy brought an ice bucket to put it in, left the white wine on the table.
-after no one waited on us for 20 minutes, my Dad flagged down the manager, who immediately waited on us, but had no knowledge of the menu. When we asked how big the appetizer size was compared to the main course size, he said, "The app size is nice, and smaller than the entree." 
-We noticed a chef hat by two items on the menu, so we asked the waiter/ bus boy what that meant, and he said, "I don't know."
-once our salads came out, we had to ask for fresh pepper.
-at one point, a female seeming manager came over because clearly she could tell something was off, so my Dad told her the above, and she proceeded to do nothing about it. We didn't see her the rest of the night (pretty sure she hid).
-They brought out a 'Congratulations' dessert, which we couldn't eat because we had no silverware, even though the honoree asked for forks, but those utensils never showed. For the tenth time, we asked for our water glasses to be filled, but they weren't.
-At the end, the waiter brought the check to one of the daughters and then a male manager approached us. Instead of being apologetic, he argued that he was overseeing 190 guests and "did his best." Despite him paying the check, which he thought would make everything better (clearly he missed the point), our sister's special night will be remembered as a joke.
-the food, which was unmemorable, was overshadowed by the horrific service.

We will never recommend this to anyone, despite being Montecito residents (and believe it or not down to earth), and we will never go back.

column12:
As someone who is very nutrition conscious, this place is a gem . 
PokeCeviche offers more options than any other poke places I've been to; for example, they have kelp and zero calorie noodles as bases , which is awesome for people trying to watch their diet .
I think they are very generous with the portions of protein as well, a medium bowl had about 4-5 oz of fish. Toppings are unlimited, so if you get everything, it's a hefty amount of food!
They also have cool stuff like creatine and protein powder if you need extra boosts in your drinks.
The owner Andy is also so sweet:) always smiling and welcoming !

column12:
I was looking for a new place to get lunch and luckily I saw that there was a Luna grill here.  I was out here for work in Santa Barbara and where I live in LA I haven't seen too many of these locations but when I was out in Oxnard I did see a location out there in the menu looked really good.

I placed my order online and it was really quick and easy to do. It said that my food to be ready in about 20 minutes. Once I've gone to the store they had shelves where I could pick up my food and lo and behold there it was. The design of the interior was really nice. A lot of people were opting to eat outside since it was a nice day out.

I ordered the Gyro combo and I was able to select a side and I went with the salad. The salad was amazing tons of delicious and colorful ingredients in it. There are a lot of different components in it and it was wonderful. The gyro itself was amazing as well and it was very filling. They toast the pita so there is an extra crunch to the texture of things and it all worked very well together.  I also got a baklava. I honestly could have eaten 20 of them but I only bought 1.

The food was amazing and I definitely will be checking out more of Luna Grill locations out whenever I'm back out here for work.

column12:
Also know as the Pebble Beach of Santa Barbara, Sandpiper has some impressive views and some amazing golf holes.  If you only have time to play 9 holes, the back 9 is responsible for the 5 star reviews.

Even the middle tees are long for the intermediate golfer.  Not much water comes into play.  Rough is rough and will result in lost balls.  Largest sand trap is the beach along many of the holes on the back 9.  Greens are relatively flat with minimal breaks.

Service is top notch with attendants helping with your clubs before and after a round.  It's nice to throw them a few bucks, as they seem like a quality crew.

Clubhouse is tiny, and a small, but high quality clubhouse lounge serves golf food faire.

Pro tip:  Stay at the Bacara Resort, while booking a round at Sandpiper.  Both are quality establishments and will satisfy both the Mr and Mrs.

column12:
The good news: if you are absolutely hard up for a ball of pho and your car has broken down in Carpenteria, you have an option now.  Mind you, it's not even in the same freaking ballpark as any number of areas of Southern California where Vietnamese restaurants tend to herd... but it is an option I suppose.

If I had never eaten pho before, I probably would give us more than two stars.  After all, any idiot can enjoy a glass of wine at a wedding,  shake it off the next morning with a B vitamin, and forge ahead.  The more discriminating sommelier would likely not even order a glass.

As a self-professed omnivore, I am not pho snob... or maybe I am.  I just know that I've had better bowls of soup at lots of other places.  The basil, sprouts, and lime plate was pathetic.  It seriously looks like they brought me one that had already made it out to a table.  Why bother?

Broth wasn't balanced in my opinion, going a little heavy on the salt and not quite enough fennel/star anise flavor.  The noodles had the wrong chew, and got a little soggy too fast for my liking.  That nearly $12 for the big bowl, you're paying almost double for Carpinteria rents and beachside community ambience, I guess... Because most places in Westminster, Garden Grove, and Alhambra are half the price for a better bowl of soup.  If you live here, I suppose it comes out even by the time you're done paying for gas.

I tend not to judge a Vietnamese restaurant by its service, because most of them are drop and dash when it comes to bringing food to your table.  This one sort of brought it to a whole new level however.

Anyway, like I said... I'm not in Carpenteria with the pho bug often enough to really care.  Sometimes these little out-of-the-way places are hidden gems.

Other times, in the immortal words of Charlie Brown: "I got a rock!"

column12:
My friend called this the "JV Target" once, and it's definitely stuck. The property isn't at all big enough for a full sized Target, but Santa Barbarians were tired of driving to Ventura for reasonable home goods, so this one got built in a fancy looking mini mall who's best previous tenant was a bagel shop. Then within a year, a real Target moved in to Goleta, and we now have a JV Target. 

That said, this has been THE best place to get groceries during the pandemic - really short lines and plenty of goods. Also, it doesn't smell terrible like the Smart and Final in 5 points. They have a good selection of toys, beauty products, and booze, good prices, and an unhurried atmosphere. If you're going to a birthday party anywhere near La Cumbre, or need a couple quick items, this is your spot.

column12: Food was fair but overpriced for the quality. Server was nice but was not very attentive. Maybe spread too thin? Never got our appetizer, ended up going to another table. Still was on our bill and had to request it to come off. Our dessert went to the wrong table as well but they sent it back this time so we eventually got it. Asked for flour tortillas vs corn said no problem and it came out corn. Asked what was on the burger and she forgot to say pickles so pickle juice all over the bun, which is ok if you like pickles. They did replace the bun though after we asked. There's a reason the locals don't go there and it's just the tourists. Wouldn't go back. Not worth it. I can put up with mediocre food but service can make or break a visit. For the food- I would have rated them a 3 star. Service a 1 star so hence the 2.

column12:
This is a prime spot to have dinner here in Santa Barbara. It's on state street but the prices are a great value for its portions. I ordered the Chicken Vindaloo but have eaten the Tikka Masala and the Rogan Josh here as well. If you're a fan of spicy food, I recommend you to try the entrees here.

The Naan and Garlic Naan bread here is soft and compliments the different sauces well, the Samosas here are also hot n fresh. If you bring a friend, split yourselves between Rice and Naan bread to try between your dishes. The flavors here are really strong without rice or bread so make sure to order one of the two.

The service was expedient and took care of my friends and I. We came on a really hot day in Santa Barbara and they made sure that our water was always filled to the brim.

column12:
What a great brew house! My cousin showed me this place when I went up to Santa Barbara for a gig. 

They have great beer and food. They also have lots of tvs and big tables for large parties. This place is so ideal for a large group of friends to have beers and watch a good sports game! At the time I was there I was hungry but not starving so I decide to go with the Grilled white fish tacos! Sooooo tasty. Go here if your looking for a good sports bar with great food! Cheers!

column12:
The food was perfect but the service was so-so (hence only 4 stars).

We started with the MOZZARELLA E POMODORI which was very good.  The cheese was soft and very fresh!

For the main course, my wife ordered the Risotto with chicken and prosciutto...very creamy and very good.  I had the TAGLIATELLE VERDI ALLA BOLOGNESE...again, very good.  The meat sauce was rich yet did not overpower the Spinach tagliatelle.

As far as the service goes, I like a place they think ahead...your glass is near empty, fill it up, ask if you would like more bread...maybe I am being too picky but so be it!

All in all a very good dining experience.

column12: The food here is very good. Portion sizes are large. I recommend sharing an entree and trying more starters. My only real complaint relates to the check-in process. We booked a table for 8 PM. We arrived a few minutes early. The hostess seemed a little put-off and told us we would have to wait while she tended to other guests. We did not feel welcome. We waited outside. Another couple arrived after us. We were both waiting outside. The hostess came back and asked who had arrived first. It was clear that we had arrived first, but the other couple claimed to have a 7:45 PM reservation (they were late, as it was after 8 PM at this point). My complaint, and it's a minor one, is that the hostess should have stuck to her "first come, first served" system. She should have remembered we arrived first and and immediately seated us, and not given the other couple an opportunity to weasel in.

column12: While away on a day trip to Santa Barbara we checked out this ramen restaurant. The seating is a bit awkward outside unless you get a spot lined up against the wall to people watch. So when the waiter asked where we would like to sit I immediately went for a spot there. The server was quick to get us drinks. Since we were in a bit of a hurry due to a day filled itinerary, we ordered right away and paid. I got the spicy pork tonk kont su ramen bowl dish. It was absolutely delicious just very very hott. I enjoy spicy things, so the more spice usually the more excited I am to try it. I also felt like there was a good amount of protein in the dish as well. My husband got the spam sushi roll and he liked it. He wasn't that hungry otherwise he would have ordered more. Anyways good ambience outside, great portion sized tasting ramen and right on the downtown strip of Santa Barbara. You can't go wrong stopping here for some soup if you're in the mood for it!

column12: I am so disappointed with this place.  I walked up and there was no host.  After a wait, a server told us to seat ourselves.  After a sitting and asking for a high chair, we eventually had to get one for ourselves.  Then we waited, and waited with no menus.  After getting up and asking for service we finally ordered.  While waiting for our food we watched as three servers rushed around to handle the whole restaurant with no sections or semblance of order.  A line formed at the entrance constantly.   The servers openly argued about who was doing more and moving faster.  I watched as one server spilled water at a table and came back with a towel only to wipe the floor first then after the table with the same towel.  Ewwww.   Once we were finally served, my veggie ramen was so thick and creamy there was no liquid or broth at all.  My husband did enjoy his Spicy chicken ramen.  I ended up ordering take out at Sachi Ramen and picked it up to eat at home.

column12: Santa Barbara has seen a number of ramen places come and go; many of them were overpriced and mediocre. This is our go to Ramen joint in SB. Not only is their ramen great, they also have great poke, rice bowls and other dishes. Their prices and serving sizes are an added bonus and what keeps this place in our regular roster of places to eat at while being downtown.  If you are hungry, want great food and don't want to spend $20-40 per entree near the pier, walk a little ways down State St and eat here.

column12: Came here recently with Trevor for my birthday and wow was i impressed. We had a long wait (it was Saturday night at 8pm go figure) but i didn't mind since we had spent the day wine tasting and i had a good buzz going. This restaurant is located right on State street so there is lots of good window shopping and people watching to do while you wait. We were seated at one of the two tops that has one side booth seating and the other chair seating. Our table was a bit wide and i felt far from my man but it made for lots of room when our food came. We started with the oysters which came with chives and a delish light brothy lemony sauce. We both thought the oysters were super fresh and very tasty but small ( it's the kind of oyster not the restaurants fault). Then we got the Yellow Submarine roll ( yellow tail, Asparagus, Miso sauce and soy paper wrap) which was good but the flavor combo was just a bit different not my fave. We also had the zippy roll which is a spicy tuna roll and damn it was good. Unlike many other spicy tuna rolls this one featured the tuna and it's fresh flavor rather then the spicy mayo most sushi joints use. lastly we ordered a California roll with eel on top ( the name escapes me) it was good it had real crab which i love and the eel was not fishy. The ambiance here is not so romantic as it can get pretty loud but that didn't bother us too much. If you appreciate good sushi this is a great place to come the specialty rolls range from $8- $22 ( they have one that is $22 but most are right around $9).

column12:
I didn't think that I could possibly eat the best sushi I have ever had in California, in Santa Barbara.

I am not particularly a fan of sea urchin, but the uni was to die for. I was informed Santa Barbara is one of the biggest supplying coasts where uni is harvested. So everything was fresh from the docks and you could certainly tell the quality was unmatched to most uni I have sampled. 

They have some pretty intense shots of quail egg, salmon roe, and uni...buttery, milky, creamy goodness. The fish was incredibly fresh and the plates seemed to come out at a decent pace. 

The atmosphere was wonderfully buzzing but not in an annoying way. Lots of conversation, tight seating, but with good company and a rumbling stomach, it's the perfect spot for a small group of friends to enjoy a meal.

column12: Came here for Valentine's brunch and while we were waiting for our food my husband noticed a roach on the wall right next to us. column12: I'm really sad. Been coming to this bar for the past 3 years, I really enjoyed. We came back this year to a rude bartender who basically bur-rated me for not knowing that the menu changed 2 years ago. Well, maybe you guys should update your Yelp page. Yelp is one of the only ways out-of-towners like myself know what's popular and hopping. We chatted a bit and he said business has fallen off "because so many other places opened up." Nope, it's because of the service and food selections. Every bar on State St has over cooked burgers and deep fried chicken. Clearly these guys are interested only in hooking up their friends. Bummer. This place was great a year ago.

column12: What can I say, Pete was amazing! He was prompt, reasonable and knowledgeable.  Pete had great recommendations on wineries, where he knew we would get great service with tasty wines. He even took us to a jewelry shop we wanted to visit along the way. We went way over our time limit, but Pete was more than happy to oblige us. You can't go wrong with Pete!

column12:
(This review is for Martin in particular.)
A group of us girls came down to the area for a bachelorette weekend. We absolutely loved our tasting experience. Our driver, Martin, was not just a driver but a source of wine and winery knowledge. He knew so much and really made the experience as wonderful as it was! 

I would do it all over again if possible! This made me want to come down more often just for the tours! This is a must! 

- Affordable - Friendly - Experienced... Cannot rave enough about the great time we had! 

:)

column12: Great ambiance and a fun location, mixed with authentic Spanish tapas, make for a lovely dinner locale. We ordered a margarita and mojito, both were traditional and good. Then we went on to split the figs, fried cauliflower, grilled corn, camarones, and ahi tartar. Everything was tasty and warm, exciting flavors all around. Except the tartar, that is, which we sent back because it was dry and bland. The plate sizes are truly tapas, so if you're starving, this is probably not where you want to go. However, if you like a bit of everything and hot, fresh food, why not give it a try?

column12:
Oh em gee....my FAVORITE restaurant in Santa Barbara!!!! I used to frequent this gem when I lived in SB. Out of town guest? Took 'em here. Did they like it? Yesssss, ma'am. Great food, large portions, and reasonably priced...what else can you ask for?

The best part is the garlic knots...ate so much one day, I swear it tooks days for all of that bread to digest.

If you're feeling greedy, you can even ask them for some garlic knots to go!

Go here instead of Pascucci's.

column12:
My wife and I started going to Palazzio's in 1995 at the Monticeto location.  It was wonderful.....a 5 star restaurant!  As the years past and the owner opened the State St. location the brand has declined so much (to the one star rating that I have given it today) that I think my wife and will be looking for another place to go.

My rating is solely based on the service, or lack there of, that has become the norm at the State St. location.  The service was so bad the last time we were there I saw 2 different groups of people leave before they were seated because the staff didn't even acknowledge their presence.  My family and I waited for 10 mins. before I had to get someone's attention to get seated.  The hot rolls that we were accustomed to getting every 10 mins. we're non existent for our table, I again had to ask the busboy to bring us out some rolls as our waiter or waitress (we didn't have an assigned waitress) was nowhere to be found.  It took forever for someone to take our order, even longer to get the food, and getting the check was impossible.

If it were not for Jamie, the hostess, I am confident that my family would have gone with out food.  She seemed like she was the only one working that night.

All of my negative comments aside the food is still great, so if you do not mind waiting for service, refills, rolls, food or your bill, you will still leave Palazzio's feeling like you had a good meal.  However, I would recommend calling ahead and ordering your food to go and having a sunset picnic at the beach as opposed to dining in the restaurant.

column12: This place has an amazing atmosphere and really great drinks. They always have some vinyl playing of an awesome old jazz album. Ideally, I would give it a 5. However, they often only have one bartender. The place is rarely packed (except late on friday or saturday), so one bartender works. But here and there, it does get crowded and if it does, you may end up waiting a half hour to even order a drink (because each cocktail takes much longer than popping the top off a beer). So, DO NOT bring a big group (which will arrive at the same time). You will wait forever to get a drink.

column12: I come here regularly, and I leave satisfied every time! Their breakfast items are all delicious; my favorite is the egg bagel! So good! I usually get that with the Thai tea. The main lady is always so nice; always with a smile on her face. She sometimes gives me free donuts too if it's the end of the day. Today's service was especially exceptional because for the first time I asked for iced Thai tea with no sugar, and she usually has an already-made Thai tea with sugar so she made no-sugar ice tea for me from scratch. This is commendable because there was a long line, and she was accommodating my wishes with a smile on her face despite this fact. She's always so nice to other people too. Such a wonderful staff! Thank you! Highly recommended for breakfast items, donuts, tea, amazing boba! There's an outside place which reminds me of French cafes with little metal tables and chairs, separated from the parking lot with large flower pots. Wonderful in every way!

column12:
Man, where to start.  Came here because read it was awarded the Michelin plate.  Later read the criteria for Michelin plate and it is based solely on quality of food; no mention of ambience or good service.  Of which Bibi Ji has very little.   We felt like we had been invited to dinner by college guys in their apartment, even down to the water spotted silverware and a can of unopened beer plopped down in front of us.

We opened the door to music blasting so we asked the host if we might sit outdoors.  We were seated out front in an area of metal chairs and tables on concrete enclosed by an iron fence.   The wine list had no by the glass prices listed and the waiter said that if  we wanted it by the glass we would just have to have what was already opened.  We asked for his suggestions for what to order and he said most people just order a variety of things to share so he did not offer any suggestions.  I started wondering if I was in the wrong place so checked out the review that mentioned a verdant patio.  Since I saw no sign of verdant, I asked the waiter about that.  He said "oh, we have a patio in the back" so we asked to be seated back there.  It was a little more pleasant with some flowering vines, but the music was still so loud that we had to yell to hear one another across the table.  Fortunately, the new waiter that came with the new location was much better and gave us some helpful suggestions.  We also asked if they had beer and he said yes, it just wasn't on the menu and rattled off a few.  

As far as the food goes, we thought the butter chicken and the Nan was great, as was the wine we ended up with, so perhaps the Michelin review was right as far as the food. However, I am giving it a 3 because of the lack of ambiance and poor service,

column12:
Roy is the perfect compromise of hip and fine dining. The bread is freshly made, the salad greens come from the local farmers market, and the entrees are delicious. This is the only restaurant downtown I know of that offers a reasonable prix fixe menu of quality courses, about $25 for soup, salad and main course with a side of vegetables. I often order the duck breast or almond crusted fish, but I know that the bacon-wrapped filet mignon is very popular. If you have space for dessert (ordered a la carte), I highly recommended the flourless chocolate torte. Not to say that the mousse or creme brulee are bad, but the torte is so so good that the other desserts pale in comparison.
Roy himself is often there, and can come by the tables to chat and check up on patrons. On weekends there might be live music, like Spencer the Gardner. On other nights Spencer might even be your waiter!  And hey, Roy serves food up to midnight, that's no lie, I know this from first hand experience. 
The bar is also very popular, so much so that sometimes service gets a little gridlocked there.  Maybe I need to harden up my elbowing abilities or project myself better.

column12:
Petrini's gets four stars for the friendliness of staff, reasonable prices, small town restaurant feel and not to mention the awesome food.  The second I walked in the door, I was greeted with a warm welcome, seated right away and given the menus.  They accommodated my large family with no complaints and grabbed some munchies and crayons to keep the kids occupied.  When ordering the waitress gave useful suggestions which I always appreciate.  

When the food arrived, everything was amazing.  The portions were huge and the extra plates they gave us made it feel like we were having a true family dinner.  I tasted each entree and was amazed by each one.  Very flavorful and unique.  A big plus for me was they serve local beer.

If you're in Santa Barbara, save your money and the hassle with the crowds downtown.  Eat at Petrini's you will definitely walk out pleased AND full.

column12:
We found this service through Yelp and booked purely off of the outstanding reviews it received.  After using them (Chris specifically) we can affirm that these reviews are spot on! We've been up to Santa Barbara many times for wine tasting and have used limo companies in the past, that truly rip you off in price.  This service is much more affordable and incredibly convenient.  Chris met us at our hotel in the valet area, jumped in the drivers seat of our car and off we went.  It was so easy.  There was also something really nice about being in our car all day.

Apparently all the drivers are locals in Santa Ynez, so they know the area well.  Chris had great recommendations for which wineries to visit (based on what we were looking for) and made a really great lunch recommendation that we would never have found on our own.  He was fun and professional.  It's safe to say we'll be calling Chris and his team from now on when we're up there!

column12: Hubby & I were driving back from Santa Barbara and we hadn't had breakfast yet. So I started looking on yelp for something that caught my eye... and the food pix alone did just that! I started the directions and we headed to Rincon Beach Bar. It was very easy to get there and found parking right away. As soon as we walked in I thought it was beautiful! The garden style seating was my favorite, there was plenty of shade, greenery all around, and the best part was the sound of the ocean greeting you at your table. The hostess was very pleasant and extremely helpful with the ordering process ( contactless ordering). You order and pay from your phone.... gratuity is already included in the bill which she explained that it was equally split with all employees. I ordered the huevos rancheros which weren't as spicy as I would of liked but they were VERY delicious. Hubby got French toast casserole w/strawberries.....let me tell you I'm still thinking about how decadent it was! The crispy brown sugar on the edges was to die for!! The orange juice was on point & they don't mess around with the coffee.....tasty & strong! All the food was amazing and customer service was great. I have to say this has been one of my favorite places for brunch, this will be our go to place every time we visit Ventura or Santa Barbara. Thanks for a memorable meal Ricon;)

column12: Very disappointing. My experience started off great. I was first greeted by a very pleasant receptionist and the Hotel was beautiful. We were checked in quickly with no hassle. When we were taken to our room, however, they had booked us in the wrong room. After being switched to a room better suited to our requests, we were once again disappointed. None of the things Bacara claimed to offer with our room were there (ie. bath robes, menu, wine). When we asked our bell hop for these things, they arrived in three separate trips. When it came time for us to order from "24-hour" in room dining, no one answered despite us calling four different times. We had to order food through the front desk. When we tipped our bell hop despite the bad service, he didn't even say thank you. For a $600 night stay, I expected much more.

column12:
First off we went on a Tuesday and checkout out on Thursday so it was not crowded and so so quiet. 

The SPA Review (5 Stars):

Brown sugar scrub...OMG!!!
The spa is FANTASTIC. It is very spacious and luxurious. There are separate men and women sides, BUT the insanely beautiful rooftop sun deck is mixed. We went to the roof in our robes after our treatments and reclined on the amazing chaises and fell asleep in the sun. No one bothers you. It is quiet and again the view!  
I was told there are 47 treatment rooms.The jacuzzi, steam and sauna are located in each of the locker rooms. i guess I have been going to the Korean spas for too long. I  am so ok with not wearing a bathing suit, but everyone there had one on so I stuck to a towel and the steam sauna. The locker room is huge, plenty of showers and products.
There is pool right outside the spa as well. You can order food and drinks if you like. Supposedly if you are staying at the  hotel you cam  use the spa facilities even without an appointment. 

The RESORT Review (4 Stars):
I loved Bacara and can't wait to go back. I didn't even mind the $24 dollar valet only parking. I actually found the bellmen to be on top of things and our car was always ready for us by the time we got downstairs....we even forgot the phone in the car and they delivered to the pool. 

So why 4 stars only....We had a great room with an amazingly large balcony with a partial view of the ocean. I wish we had time to enjoy a mean out there, but next time. It was an upgrade room and on the end corner (bldg 20 - room 301). We  had to two dressing areas each with a sink so it made getting ready a snap. I LOVED the bathtub...it was deep and just the right size. The wall to the bathroom is just shutters that open. Which makes watching TV and taking a bath really easy. Plus you can talk to the person on the bed.  The downside to all this openness is that the actual toilet area is also "open" - just one open shuttered door separates you from the rest of the room. With all the stone sound travels or makes you think it is travelling. Anyway, it is a bit awkward.

The bed was comfy...Oh! we had a fireplace and they supplied some glorious big candles and matches to set the mood further. They deliver ice at night which is great. The TV got crappy reception.The business center was nice. i had to use the computer and it was lightening fast. 

We had breakfast one morning down by the pool. It was AWESOME.  They don't usually serve there until 10am, but we called at 8:30 and they said "no problem". We spent most of our time by the pool closest to the ocean and not the cabana area, but would definitely get a cabana if it was a weekend or crowded. The downside to the infinity pool is that it SLURPS all the time. You can't hear the ocean over the slurping. A regular pool would have been fine. 

It is awesome and romantic and everything you want in getting away. There are plenty of deals online from Amex, Travelocity etc. so you can stay at Bacara for a really great rate. I am told that they have specials in the winter that are crazy cheap but you have to keep checking back.

column12:
I try not to throw 5 stars around loosely. This place came pretty close though. The food was delicious. Even with a location that is not on the main thoroughfare for visitors, there was still a nice crowd. The food is well worth the short wait and the service was friendly. The decor was simple, but I am glad they put their energy into the food as opposed to having a decked out circus of a restaurant with crappy food. 

Definitely a place that I look forward to visiting anytime I come to Santa Barbara.

column12: I wish I could rate this so much higher!! The food was amazing. My Bloody Mary was perfection. The host was a super sweet, cool dude. Went in with a great first impression. It took a super long time for our waitress to check in with us or even offer us water. We finally had to ask the host if anyone knew we were seated in the corner. Our waitress wasn't apologetic at all. She moved fast but I don't know what she was doing exactly. The outside was moderately busy but there wasn't many of us in the inside dining area. It was a beautiful Saturday morning and again the food !! Every interaction with our waitress was ok but it was probably the longest meal we've ever had because there was such a gap in her timing. Service is so important.

column12: HAHA! Boy oh Boy, I was a regular here when I was a student at UCSB!  Nearly every single Saturday, I would be hungover from a night of drinking.  I would always order the same thing, the super size pho dac biet or just the large pho before the super size came in!  The broth is just so delicate and refreshing.  I usually add a buttload of the chili oil and the fresh chili to make my broth have an extra kick to wake me up.  The bean sprouts...I fu%^in pour that in as well as the jalapenos.  No basil cuz I hate it.  The meat is so delicious as well.  They do not skimp on the portions.  A double plus.  I never really had a bad service here before.  I mean, I don't expect a 5 star service.  It's a small restaurant and the owners are just trying to do their best.  The vietnamese lady owner knows my friend and I.  She would always make fun of us and stuff like that!  "ALWAYS WITH THE TO GO BOX!"  LOL!  What?! It's so good and delicious I have to take some home for Sunday morning when I need to recover cuz you guys close Sundays!  I'll always have fond memories here at Noodle City!  When I visit Santa Barbara, I'll be sure to pay a visit to my favorite pho place.  Oh, and their Chow Fun isn't that bad either.  Its deeelicious!  :)

column12: This place gets super busy, especially on the weekends! column12:
I searched Yelp for a place in Santa Barbara that had latte art, and the French Press was the first place to appear.  While in Santa Barbara, before coming for a coffee, we heard so many good things about it from locals, they even have an award winning barista that works there.  It was warm out so we ordered an vanilla ice latte, which they do make their own syrups in house.  I wish i would have gotten a hot latte, that way i could have really seen the skills of their talented staff.  The service wasn't happy, there was no hi, that was a let down, otherwise i would have given them four stars.

Overall, i enjoyed my drink, it wasn't much different from what i make at home, i would go here because of the great vibe of the place, i just wish the service were better.

column12:
I love their food. I can't tell you how many times I have eaten here, but it is a very large number. Until I moved recently, I lived just a short walk from here, and I never got tired of it. The best thing they make is the mole enchiladas, but the sad part is, they don't make them every day. Just on Tuesdays. Just telling you about them makes me want some right now. 
As others have mentioned, you have to pay for the chips, but the salsa bar is complimentary, so it balances out. The salsas are all great. Really. I can't say enough about the food here. If you are able to go here, then go here. That's about as good a review as I can write.
column14: Los Arroyos Mexican Restaurant & Take Out

column12: Driving through downtown in search of good Mexican food and we came across Los Arroyos! What immediately caught our eye was the amount of traffic going in and out of the restaurant. It is a small sit in and take out eatery so once you walk in you may seat yourself and then walk up to order once you've made a choice! I decided on the grilled chicken wet burrito! It included black beans, grilled chicken, cheese, and a side of rice! My boyfriend ordered the beef sope! The food tasted great and fresh! The wait time for food was quick! Plan ahead when coming it stays busy!

column12: Curbside seating and takeout for COVID. Grab your own table or let staff know. We had our dog so he was able to sit with us too. Order inside and they'll bring your food to you. The menus posted in the window too so you can browse in line. We ordered homemade sopes (chicken and beef), arroyo burrito (fish and shrimp), protein burrito and 1 item plate asada taco (rice and beans). The food tasted alright, lacking a little flavor/seasoning for me to give it more stars. But the ingredients were fresh. Generous with the meat which was also very tender. Complementary chips and salsa with the meal, the chips were still hot! Staff was polite and we left stuffed and happy. The nearest parking would probably be lot 4(?) behind CVS or on the street.
column14: Los Arroyos Mexican Restaurant & Take Out

column12: we had dinner there on a sunday night - fairly busy but not overwhelmingly so. The food was ok- coconut prawns and poki were excellent, halibut was ok, salads were passable but nothing special. The service was mediocre - they left dirty plates on the table the whole dinner until I stacked them up obviously indicating that they needed to be bussed. column12:
Have you ever wished that Applebee's would triple their prices? Well then, this is the restaurant for you. This food is not particularly better than most frozen entrees at the supermarket. The cauliflower misto frido was smothered in a thick flavorless breading then coated with a thick corn syrup-like sweet/sour sauce. Imagine the shitty Chinese food from your local strip mall. The 5 "bacon-wrapped large scallops" just sucked. The were tiny bay scallops totally overpowered by the size of a normal strip of bacon. They were dry and unappetizing. Didn't think it was possible to make bacon unappealing but I stand corrected.  The fish was meh. The wedge salad was the best thing we ordered. The environment is nice. The service was great. 
Basically this joint is an overpriced tourist trap lacking any love in the kitchen.

column12:
All of our dining adventures @ Fish House went swimmingly. We only intended to have cocktails in the bar each night before leaving for dinner. But each night we ended up staying for dinner- noshing on the hearty happy hour apps and taking in the fun local energy. All the servers and bussers are spot on, with food delivered efficiently even when the place is rocking. We have enjoyed every item on the hh menu, along with the reasonably priced cocktails and are always more than happy.  
Definitely a favorite go to when you want quality, quantity, and value!

Thanks Santa Barbara Fishhouse !!!

column12:
The only star off is for the super long wait for the waiter service seating area as it is quite small. There is a self service window to order from but we opted not to do that due to the live musician. He was great, it's just a personal choice for me. As a musician myself, I prefer not to have anyone singing to me as I eat as I would rather attend a concert and watch an artist and appreciate them that way. 

Once we sat, the service was good and fast, and the food, especially the Rock Crab was exceptional. Just know that they fry the calamari unbreaded. Great view when you are seated, and just be forewarned that the seabreeze can get cold. Glad I was prepared!

column12:
Bottom Line:  Average food and threatened to charge us for not finishing our plate

I was VERY excited to try this place out as I desperately miss living in Koreatown down in LA where I was for 13 years.
  The biggest problem is that most of the things that are brought to the table are not marinated in anything.  The bulgogi - which has always been my favorite - was super yummy, pre marinated and grilled up very well.  
   However things like the unmarinated pork belly, was just cooked meat at the end and not a lot of flavor despite my efforts to add things to it and even my attempt to kind of marinade it in my bowl of spicy sauce.
   Service was mediocre at best - somewhat attentive.
There are no vegetables - at all - except a bowl of salad that was periodically refilled for us.  Toward the end I was definitely starting to get the "meat sweats".

We hadnt quite finished what was left on the Bulgogi plate when the server came back and told us we would be charged $10 for not finishing all of the meat - that after we spend more than $50 for our dinner and received mediocre service.
  Not only that - this whole chargeback thing was the first that we had heard of this.  It's not on the menu and our server never mentioned it.

Having never heard about this, IMHO it was quite rude to charge us what they did for dinner, then threaten to charge us more for something we know nothing about.

This place was good but has some work to do in the customer service department

column12: A solidly good breakfast in Santa Barbara. The location on State St isn't very big and the weather on Christmas Eve morning was perfect for a patio breakfast. We snagged a table, ordered at the counter and the food was delivered to our table in a decent amount of time. My husband loved his huevos rancheros and I had a great spinach salad with berries, figs and goat cheese. We had to ask if our coffee orders were forgotten and were reassured they were coming. They were dropped off towards the end of our meal with an apology that they were backed up. We asked for to-go cups and rolled with it. Overall, the food was tasty, the drinks hot and a place we'd recommend for breakfast.

column12: Food excellent.  Was by myself, sat at the bar, not overly hungry.  Ordered the chicken scallopini served on spinach.  It was excellent, the service was not.  The bartender had friends sit down and spent her time attentive to them.  I asked for a dessert menu and wanted to order, but she never followed up to ask me.   I left and went somewhere else for dessert.  When I left, she was actually standing outside the bar by their chairs with them  Great food and maybe great service, just not at the bar.

column12:
delicious! although it gets crowded and loud (i was there on a saturday night) this is a good sign...the food & drinks are really solid as is the service. in a college town it is rare to come across such attention to detail as this staff has. kudos to the owner/manager who trains this bunch. they know their stuff.
details: love their mojitos, and their wine selection (which is completely amazing and not marked up ridiculously.) 

favorite dishes in the last few months: seared ahi, thai salmon dish, and their rib-eye...yes...better than most steak houses,

do yourself a favor a try this spot!

column12: Had no expectations walking in and was so surprised to see such a nice restaurant had such an affordable menu and a very extensive wine list and great food. People were both dressed up and casual so I didn't feel uncomfortable walking in in jeans. I cant wait to go back and try other items on the menu and invite others.

column12:
It can be a bit of a mad house here on the weekends and they don't have enough outdoor seating, but the coffees and teas are good (I suggest the dirty chai) and the setting is nice. Also, if you are biking in from Santa Barbara or Ventura it is right off the bike path.

Pros are that it is right next to a super cool mercantile store so you can browse as you sip.

Cons are that though the baristas are working hard, there are so many patrons that isn't the fastest service; also they only have one bathroom/stall (all gender, which is good), so expect to wait in line.

column12:
I was driving on the 101 and wanted to stop in SB to have healthy food.  I found Silvergreens to be quick and healthy with a wide variety of menu options.  

I wish we had a Silvergreens in LBC, its quick like a take away chicken place crossed with super healthy food.  The receipt even has the calorie, protein and health food numbers similar to labeling of store products so you know what you are eating.  

I will be back again.

column12: I really wanted to love this place, with its healthy, locally sourced food ( or so they say), chill atmosphere and low prices.  The ceviche tacos were pretty good, although I found the ahi tuna salad a little bland. The warm cookie Sunday was a huge letdown. Cold, day old cookie made it hard to eat and messy since the cookie was hard and would fly everywhere when I tried to part it with my spoon to scoop up with a bite of ice cream. Maybe I'll give it another chance ...but do I really want to be disappointed again?  On the other hand, the service was great and very attentive, better than some places I've been in this college town.

column12:
Stopped at Rosales in the middle of our road trip, and it was absolutely the right choice. The food was so fresh, service was great, and portions were excellent. 

We ordered a shrimp ceviche tostada, 2 veggie quesadillas which came with guac, and one order of fish enchiladas. They have a nice outdoor setup, so we enjoyed our food in the cool weather outside. Definitely a place we would revisit!

column12:
This place is a wonderful  restaurant the menu is creative and extremely affordable.
I was at the grand opening and I was delighted to see so many familiar faces. I really enjoyed the experience of the atmosphere that was lively and sociable. The owner John Bennet was very helpful with his recommendations . I enjoyed everything from the appetizers to the main courses. I had a wonderful nonalcoholic sparkling ginger and mint beverage. Yum! If you're visiting or local I highly recommend this restaurant for the affordable food atmosphere and location.

column12:
Was recommended by my cousin to try out this place when visitng santa barbara. The portion were decent and pretty tasty. The customer service was great. They were very attentative and was always asking if we were doing good. 

I got the halibut with citus butter which was a special because they did not have the sole. It was good and very tasty.  We also got the mixed fresh seafood penne. The flavor was good. I would definitely come back and try other food they have when im back in santa barbara.

column12:
What a gem---a delightful spot to be. We were at Jane last night for dinner with two new friends. We sat up in the balcony area and had an enchanting dinner for four. I had the Salmon and a Caesar Salad---wow. I love cozy family owned restaurants that have a distinctly California flair---and this one with a classic Santa Barbara feel. Classy, never stuffy----fresh, but creative. Service was wonderful, wine was delightful, food fantastic---and don't forget to have a bite of coconut cake before you head home. 

This is a perfect spot for a night out with friends, a dinner with clients, or your parents---perfect for any occasion. Lovely. Thank you. We will be back!

column12:
Potentially the best "value" restaurant in Santa Barbara. Great food for very reasonable prices.

If you are going for lunch, you should definitely try one of their burgers. I love the Jane burger, as the gooey cheese and perfectly caramelized onions make it for me. If you want something a little more unique the El Macho Burger is also delicious. All burgers are served on what must be a homemade bun that is incredibly moist. If you want an appetizer get the Firestone Red Rings. They are crispy red onion rings drizzled with a balsamic reduction, definitely a little different but very good.

If you are going for dinner, the chicken piccata is probably the best I have had, it is really just about perfect if you catch them on a good night. The grilled duck breast is also very good.

Every meal starts with free bread and butter, which is decent but nothing special. If you want dessert, the coconut chiffon cake is delightful. The service is always great and it's usually not too hard to get a seat.

column12:
I was very, very hesitant to come here because of all the bad reviews I've seen.  I came here on Saturday for lunch for their $9.95 all you can eat Brisket and I was pretty impressed.  The food quality is not as good as Ventura/Oxnard or even LA, so please don't base your reviews on areas with larger concentrations of Korean BBQ restaurants.  

For Santa Barbara, this was a pretty good place and my wife and I enjoyed it quite a bit.  The service was quite reasonable.  There were about 14 diners in the restaurant and one older lady taking care of food, drinks, condiments, etc...  She delivered our meat quite fast while the other items were slower than what you would expect but still reasonable.

I will certainly come back again to make sure it wasn't a fluke but so far, my first impressions were quite high and quite good for this establishment.

column12: Came here this last Sunday for brunch and had an amazing time! The food was not your average buffet food. It was amazingly delicious! They have more food than you can imagine, and all of it tasting fresh and delicious. The salads were fresh and dressing was good. They have a good variety of fatty foods and not so fatty foods, which was perfect for our party. The dessert bar is full of cake, cheese cakes, flan, creme brulee, fresh fruit, and a chocolate fountain. Bottomless mimosas are also delicious! I was thinking they were going to be more juice than champagne, but they were pretty strong so drink cautiously! And the atmosphere is great as well. I loved it all, had an amazing time. I will definitely be going back!

column12: The ambiance was a 10......open air courtyard patio seating.  Bar was 'pedestrian'....didn't go back for second margherita food was a major disappointment....albondigos soup too salty; meatballs no flavor. Fajitas served with 'authentic/homemade tortillas which had been steamed and proceeded to fall apart.  The carne asada (aka steak) was gristle heated up w/out ANY seasoning.....Needless to say there MUST be a better place to eat! MOST UNFORTUNATE BECAUSE THE AMBIANCE IS RIDICULOUS!!!.....I would go there again just for happy hour (see can't mess up chips, salsa, tacquitos) to enjoy the setting.....but pretty much would pass on the food....better Mexican food found on every food truck in town.

column12:
The El Encanto dining room is an spectacular dining setting with enchanting ambiance. 

The views of the Santa Barbara channel islands (on a clear day) only makes the food taste better. Such a dramatic setting, such good service, such good food. 

If you enjoy a velvety, chocolaty indulgence, the chocolate souffle was rich, creamy and decadent; but it is advised to order it with your entree and have the waiter/waitress bring it to you after you have finished your entree. Alternatively, you can order the souffle around 15-20 minutes before you expect to finish your main course.    

After dining, you may stroll through the grounds and make a wish at the wishing well.

column12: The Arts & Letters Cafe provides an excellent dining experience.  We went in for a brief lunch break and we were very impressed with the atmosphere of the restaurant.  It is very well known by locals as a high end eatery, and we were not disappointed.  The entrance to the restaurant goes through an art gallery with fine paintings on display, and the dining area is outside in a shaded patio area.  Everything about the environment was excellent, and the food was great.  The only thing I would be cautious about is the fact that the sandwiches are messy and the menu is limited.

column12:
we vacation regularly in Santa Barbara and wanted to try a new breakfast location
welcomed immediately on arrival, by a smiling hostess ( what a concept!)
and seated straight away at a generously sized table for 2 ( just to repeat myself ,,,what a concept!!)
Service was also with a smile, efficient and friendly......pancakes and french toast, with crispy bacon and well scrambled eggs seemed to arrive within a few minutes of placing our order.....my soda was refilled regularly and the food was prepared exactly as requested...no need to send back the bacon to make it crispy, or return the eggs etc etc
My wife and i enjoyed everything about this experience and will always return on our future visits...easy 5 star rating

column12:
My hubby and I "discovered" Silver was on our vintners visa for the harvest weekend. How lucky were we to call and find that Benjamin Silver would be open all day Monday. A very small winery...one man production is a true gem. 
Call make an appointment. Take your time. The wines were all unique and flavorful. 
I personally loved the Chardonnay  but the show stoppers were the "super Tuscan" and the the Syrah. 
The tasting room is NOT a super fabulous decorated space. It's about the wine. 
We really enjoyed spending a few hours here. Really tasting he wine. And learning the differences in the terriors and varietals 
A wonderful experience
We are looking forward to our next visit

column12: Came here for brunch one day to splurge and very much enjoyed the experience. Granted, that experience will cost you....worth it at least one time. It's a 3 course brunch with your choice of dishes from a prix fixe menu. Brunch also includes champagne, bellinis, or mimosas. The service was wonderful and the atmosphere is unparalleled in SB. The place and service are a bit stiff for my taste. I tried to self park my Camry without realizing that you must have the valet park your car. I'm sure my Camry felt a little awkward being parked next to Aston Martins, Teslas, and Mercedes. The other obvious choice for splurging on brunch in SB would be the Biltmore...for myself, I would rather dine at the Stonehouse. Someday, I hope to return.

column12:
To those looking for great food around SB,
The service I received tonight was absolutely terrible. The food.. I could have microwaved better. I have been in the industry for about 3 years and am horrified at the service. Our server said maybe 3 words to our table before being informed that my friend didn't like the way her noodles were cooked. He said they precook their pasta so there's nothing he could do, other than get her another dish. No apology, no explanation, no nothing. 

Following the meal, we then asked him to split our check. He told us he was not capable. Unless your computer system is years old and without an update, it is possible. He told us to just write out what we wanted for cash and for the cards from each of us. He put all of the tax on one bill making hers much more than her meal. He told us not to worry because it was just a few dollars... WHAT? Through her not liking her pasta, or being worried about paying for more than she should have, he NEVER apologized. Or said anything for that matter. As our beloved Jeremy walked inside, he openly mocked us. After telling us "So, the manager can't figure it out either, so you guys can wait or..." we waited at least 30 minutes for our bill receiving NO apology. Jeremy argued with one of us, and rolled his eyes at our other friend. Please inform me what kind of customer service that is. We informed the manager of our issue, and assuming we wanted something for free, proceeded to tell us Jeremy is the lead server and he couldn't do anything about it. He told us we could talk with the owner if we wanted, giving us a business card. 

The manager on duty did nothing for us, and not once did we hear an apology from him or Jeremy. With noodles cooked to order, and some server training, Pascucci's could have a shot. But for my friends and I who do live minutes from downtown, we will never be back.

column12: I love this place!  The food is excellent, and while it does cater to American "tastes" there are traditional influences throughout the menu.  My favorite is the Los Agaves Enchiladas.  The fish and shrimp is fresh and very flavorful.  You pay at the counter and then seat yourself.  Don't be afraid of the long lines... It moves fast and you'll be shocked by how fast your food comes out even when they're slammed. Excellent food. Great service.  A nice, but casual atmosphere.

column12:
I came to California looking for some good Mexican food, and I found it here! The variety of salsas at the salsa bar were delicious with just the right amount of spice, chips were plentiful, and the chicken enchiladas were to die for. 

We had a party of 9 for lunch around noon and were able to find a table without any issues, but it got pretty packed soon after. It's a place where you have to go up and order then wait for your food, but the wait isn't too long. 

I will definitely come back the next time I'm in the area.

column12:
My husband and I along with a few of our friends went to eat here last night. We have eaten here in the past but mostly the Los Agaves downtown. We were all very disappointed with the food. I don't know if there is a new owner or what but the the food is not what it used to be. 

My husband order the salmon taco, they should of called it pineapple taco because there was more pineapples in the taco then salmon 

I had the homemade chille relleno compilation plate. Now if you have ever made homemade chille relleno before the chilles are grilled, stuffed with cheese, and coated with light fluffy egg batter. Well mine chille relleno was falay open, cheese dumped on top of it then cover in what tasted like a very thick coat of masa. It was so bad that I sent it back and asked for a chicken sope instead. The sope wasn't any better; the masa was way to thick and had no flavor.
 
We all left the restaurant dissatisfied...The only good thing I can say about last nights dinner was the rice was very flavorful

Later that night my friend called me saying she was very sick to her stomach and has been vomiting- she might be a victim of food poisoning. 
Today I am not feeling to well, very sick to my stomach  

NEVER GOING BACK

Aguacate salsa is particularly good in their salsa bar.  It's too expensive for what it is, though I guess you save on not having to tip since you order at the counter.  I like that they have limes in the salsa bar & gratis stickers at the register.  Sister location on Milpas St.

column12:
First I want to thank the guy who answered when I called 30min to closing. He gave me 15min to get in. 

The food was great, although we did eat late just before closing. The staff pulled through. Didn't get to have an alcoholic beverage, but the Horchata was great. The flavor and consistency was perfect. 

We had the Carnitas plate and enchiladas. Yessenia i think was the waitress who came to the rescue....when the others had difficulty finding the Carnitas plate in the register. 

It's a must visit when in Santa Barbara, EARLY though lol.

column12:
Nice atmosphere and the booths are quiet and pleasant.  But ...Our halibut was overcooked.  A fish restaurant should know how to cook fish and not overcook it.  It was also over-salted.  It wasn't bad, but neither was it very good.
Service can be spotty.  It's hardly the best seafood spot in Santa Barbara!  Hungry Cat deserves that award and Julienne cooks a fine fish too.  Please teach your cooks to cook fish!.  NOt to keep picking, but on other visits, lobster has been slightly overcooked as well.

Their known for their cinnamon roll and sure enough, it was yummy. Definitely tasted the cinammon which was lovely.

Their shrimp &grits was a little too heavy for breakfast but I devoured it anyways! Ofcourse I had to taste their lemon pancakes and it was soo fluffy and flavorful. The egg scramble with goat cheese was a bit bland.

Service was awesome, they offered free yogurt to taste and homemade dessert at the end :)

column12:
great little brunch spot with limited indoor seating but plenty of outdoor seating in the patio.

they were able to accommodate our large party and was great about bringing our food out together.

my kale salad + chicken + poached egg was wonderful.  appeared to be heavily dressed but it was actually more on the bland side, needed a pinch of salt.

they were kind to split all of our check!  auto gratuity was included in our party, but weren't really disclosed on the menu.  kitchen closes at 2pm on saturday, a little too early in my opinion but based on the foot traffic, it's understandable.

column12:
Last time I came, I had my favorite brunch ever. I'm sorry to say that this time, it was not the best experience... After waiting for a table for a while, we were seated right next to some sort of exhaust fumes from the kitchen. I ordered some orange juice and the Scarlett Cheeseburger (well done) and after 25 minutes, the burger finally came out... medium rare. And instead of the bacon marmalade written on the menu, I found a two-inch chunk of bacon under the cheese. The waitress took it back, and I waited for another twenty minutes for my burger to come back, and another ten minutes on top of that for the orange juice. 

The servers were courteous, but honestly I did not feel cared for or respected. This, on top of the botched meal and expensive prices, just didn't make the visit worth it.

column12:
I really like this restaurant because not only did I have a smashing good brunch but I didn't pay for the delicious meal.  The girlfriend did .
I really liked their pastries like the Blueberry raspberry blackberry danish, which was semi-sweetness in a flaky crust.  The waiter said they baked the pastries in-house.  
The Endless summer scramble was awesome as was the Shrimp & grits.  
The service was top notch and although there was a wait it wasn't that long.  I guess because we got there before 10 am.  
I got to pick all the restaurants for the weekend because it was her birthday and she wanted me to show initiative.  In the end she said I did well

column12:
When researching where to eat for my trip to SB, Scarlett Begonia made it to the top of my brunch list. The food look pretty, the outdoor area look pretty, and the reviews sounded promising. 

Upon arriving my friends and I could not find the entrance to Scarlett Begonia. So many alleys and shops, confusing. We were given the option to sit either inside or outside, both looked nice but in the end we sat outdoors since it was a nice day. 

There were many things on the menu that caught my attention; I ended up ordering the Endless Summer Scramble with a side of Multigrain Toast. My friends and bf ended up ordering the other things I had in mind so it worked out! 

The Scramble was very flavorful. The potatoes were roasted nicely, the eggs were fluffy, the veggies added freshness. Tbh, the toast wasn't worth it. It was $3 for a tiny slice with butter and very liquid-y fruit preserve/compote. It was good but too expensive. 

My bf ordered the Pork Chilaquiles (special) and it was good (also expensive though). My bestie ordered the Biscuit Sampler with a Buttermilk Biscuit and a Maple Bacon Biscuit. Both were flaky and buttery. The bacon one sprinkled with sea salt. She seemed to like them. Her bf ordered the Meyer Lemon Pancakes which were my second choice. He kindly let me try them and they had a great lemon flavor! Many lemon pancakes that i've tried are lacking in lemon flavor but not Scarlett Begonia's. 

Overall, service was pretty good! The waiters were friendly and give you a sample of toffee with your check. It's definitely a pricer restaurant but if you're looking for a cute brunch spot to catch up with friends at, it's a great option! They're also dog friendly!

column12: Took the family here for a weekend dinner and man we all had a blast.  From the food to the award winning service I can't praise this place more.  It was Mother's Day weekend so we waited for around 45 minutes but it's all worth it.  All seafood appetizers we ordered are fresh.  The waiter gave excellent service and checked on us maybe more than 5 times the whole time we were there.  He made sure that if we needed something he's just an eyeball away.  Grilled oysters are excellent (very fresh), fried calamari is bomb, crab cakes made me dream about it every night.  The ceviche is not bad either.  Overall I give this place 5 stars nothing less.

column12: The best seafood restaurant in southern CA. Every time I come here the service and food do not disappoint. Today we came for happy hour and let me tell you they have the most amazing happy hour of any other seafood place in Santa Barbara. $6 for a GIANT plate of ceviche, are you kidding!? Delicious! And not to mention the drinks are cheaper, beer $1 off aka corona for $4 not bad for SB prices. My boyfriend is really into oysters and at $1.75 each during happy hour it's a steal, we ordered 15 and he was happy as a clam or should I say oyster lol. The service is always spectacular. It can get a bit busy at happy hour and tables are first come first serve in the bar area. However, it's a pretty big open space (at least 20 tables) so you should be able to walk around and find one open! This place is also amazing for dinner! Either way you will not be disappointed with the food, staff or atmosphere.

column12:
First time here & I doubt I will come back. The service was good & we were greeted immediately. But, we did get there right at 11am when then opened. The food was average at best. The cilantro ranch dressing was awful! The chicken in the taco was supposed to be shredded, instead it was chunks. I will say that they are fairly generous with the cheese on top of the enchilada & the beans were runny. It was $31 for 2 meals & we didn't even get any alcohol. That's a bit pricy to me. 
If you're looking to just refuel, then I'd say go here. If you are looking for authentic Mexican food, this isn't the place!

column12:
Stopped by for a late dinner and loved it. The staff are friendly, food came out quickly and it was filling and delicious. 

I got the Sal De Mar, cauliflower taco and the hibiscus lemongrass drink. My favorite was probably the Sal De Mar. I got the small and loved the combination of the fish and watermelon. The ceviche also had a nice kick to it--I love spicy food so this was satisfying. The cauliflower taco was also tasty but not as spicy. I had bites of the pineapple habanero in between and that added a good amount of spice. The pineapple was labelled XX Spicy, but was on the lighter end of the spicyness scale for me, though I do have a high tolerance for spicy food.

It's a bit pricey, but comparable to everything else in SB Public Market.

column12:
JUST NO.

Haven't been here in YEARS. Decided to give it a try.

First off, FYI- you can call and make a reservation, but not on the actual day you need them. You have to do it ahead of time by at least a day.

They are dog friendly on the patio, which I appreciate.

They are open at full capacity inside now, but still have outdoor dining.

Being a group of 6, with no reservation, we were sat pretty quickly outside. 

Problem started with the bathrooms. The sewer smell was so incredibly horrible, we could barely breathe, and we had masks on! It wasn't the cleanest either. I was informed by a server that they are having issues with the city about it, but it put a bad "taste" in my mouth, quite literally, upon arrival. 

Walking back to my table, I started to see what a dump the place had become. It's filthy, I got grossed out  walking back to our table. The bread and salsa station is filthy and is actually falling backwards as both the legs up front are off the ground. Food and trash all over the ground, everywhere, and it was only 6pm on a Saturday. 

The front entrance of the restaurant is where the kitchen is, but there is a table at the front for their to-go orders right when you walk in the front door, and it was just complete chaos and looked horrible, dirty, and unorganized. 

Now the food. It was gross. If you came for the stiff drink, go for it, but pass on the food. Trust me.

Steak was over cooked, I even asked the waitress how their chef was on his temps so I could plan accordingly. I was assured that if anything they are a lower temp than normal, and I could always cook it up more if need be. The baked potatoes are old, precooked and then reheated so much so that the entire first half of the potato is hard, dark, and inedible. 

My friend ordered the burnt ends sandwich and was stoked because she had never heard of that before and loves the burnt ends. But they don't serve a burnt ends sandwich. We were informed by the manager that they don't have enough to do that for every sandwich and they just chop up meat from the prime rib and tri-tip to mix in with whatever burnt ends they have. Here's a thought, how about you just only serve the burnt ends, and when you are out, you are out. Elevate your menu like you care about what goes out to your patrons. OR explain that when someone orders so they are not disappointed. When she discussed this with the manager, there wasn't an apology, he just took the plate and they went and fried up the pieces in a pan and brought it back on the same bread it was served on. It was disgusting.

Not once did anyone ask how our food was for me to correct it quickly, and we had to be somewhere, so I just doused the steak in salt and ate it. $25 for a steak, I can do better at home. 

When we told the waitress about our experience and the frustration with the food, she apologized but nothing else. You'd think they would have comp'd something. Anything. Or had the manager come back over himself.

Sliders and fries were good. 

Clam chowder has always been good. 

But nothing else was. 

It's a shame, the history and nostalgia of this place is what made me want to bring our friends and family to experience. Hell, I even was one of the very first staff to open Harry's, under the new management of John Scott. 

We won't be returning, not unless it's for a stiff drink at the bar.

column12: I went to a show here recently and I have never felt so insulted, offended and discriminated against in my life. The bouncer that was short and fat is the rudest man ever. He would raise his voice at people that were causing no harm and get in their faces unnecessarily. They split a fence down the middle of the dance floor to separate 21+ from the under agers. I thought this was silly and pointless. I paid a good amount of money to come to this place to dance and hang out with my friends...but instead I was separated from them and insulted? I also asked if I could go outside to have a breath of fresh air because it was getting rather crowded and stuffy inside and they told me this wasnt "allowed" and that if I wanted air I needed to leave permanently. At the end of the night when all the bands finished, I stayed around a few minutes to talk with the musicians and my friends that I didnt get to see the whole show and the same bouncer approached me and ordered me to leave. Then he proceeded to raise his voice at me before I could say goodbye to my friends and stood in my face until I left. I stormed out very angry! This is not a good place to go if you want your night ruined. I don't recommend going back, ever. And no coat check? Horrible service and employees. Great music though. Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros should have picked a better venue!

column12: Not sure what's going on at the SB location, but the service has gone downhill for quite some time. I just started dining here again after taking off probably almost a year because of the same issues. Problem is not getting the food I order. For example, yesterday I ordered to go the You Pick 2: tomato soup and the turkey, avocado and bacon sandwich. Open up my sandwich and it's some turkey panini. Today, I ordered the exact same thing and asked the counter person who took the order to make sure that she orders the right sandwich. She even reiterated what was in the sandwich so I thought, great I'll get it this time. Received my order, looked in the bag and noticed the croutons that come with the soup weren't there so I had to ask for it, but didn't check my sandwich. Open it up at work and the sandwich was mostly right, except the bacon is missing. Not sure why it's so hard to get it right. This store definitely needs some training and quality control. Makes me not want to go back for another year.

column12:
This place is good for a hearty meal a cut above fast food. 

To me, Paneras are a cold weather kinda place - you know, the spot you go to warm yourself up in a cozy atmosphere with a savory bowl of soup. For some reason, their Broccoli Cheddar soup always seems to put a smile on my face. There have never been exceptions to this. 

This particular location is adjacent to a popular mall with ample parking. The restaurant itself is spacious, but not always the cleanest. However, it's never felt dirty to the point of me not wanting to eat there. I'm usually able to cozy up in a comfy booth with my number as I wait for my order to be delivered. 

The service and food are on par with other Panera locations: not the greatest but enjoyable enough. I like ordering the "Pick 2" deal where I can get a half sandwich plus a bowl of soup. The food has always been satisfactory to me and really does hit the spot on a cold winter day. 

Don't expect to be blown away eating here, but do come if you are seeking a trustworthy meal in a comfy setting.

column12:
I have no idea why the reviews of this place are bad...the location is perfect, the service when I was there was stellar and super fast, the food was hearty and delicious and the prices are incredible considering you are on the water, literally!
Our gaggle of 10, I repeat 10 girls showed up here on a Sunday morning, let's say around 10:00 am...yes, prime Sunday breakfast time.  We quickly had a primo table on the gorgeous patio and get this, one of the girls asked for separate checks!!!  I was a bit mortified by that request, but it was met and with a smile!  Our orders were taken by 2 lovely ladies and delivered within minutes.  I docked a star because my eggs weren't cooked the way I asked and the inside of the restaurant is not very nice, but shoot, I sat on a patio next to the ocean and ate eggs and toast and coffee for $12 including tip!  What more can you ask for?

column12:
State & Fig is a hidden gem with the cutest little outdoor patio. I came here with some girlfriends for big birthday brunch. There was a big group of 11 of us. They were accommodating and put tables together so that we could sit in the outdoor patio area. We were a little bummed that we did not get to order everything from the original menu, as they let us know that our menu would be different because we were such a big party. A few things were not available to order. I ended up opting for lunch and got the burger which was a great choice. 
A big reason why we came here is we wanted endless mimosas. The champagne was alright, not the best, but we stayed and enjoyed many anyway. The service was great and the food was amazing. I would come here again and skip the mimosas next time.

column12:
The restaurant is located more in a corner location that is hidden away from the street. The decor is relatively modern, giving a nice feel when you sit down. Optionally, you can sit outside, where there is a nice open decor but lacking in shade. 


Now, on to the food: The food is what really
penalized itself causing it to earn only three stars. I really wanted to love the food, the colors and food was off to a good start. For starters, the soup was great. I had their clam chowder, the only wish I had would be for a thicker chowder, but not everybody shares the same opinion. The other soup that I sampled was a kale soup, which was a unique offering that many restaurants don't traditionally serve. Overall, the soup was off to a fantastic start and got me excited. 

However, things took a turn when I had their entrée. I had ordered their State Burger which has glazed onions and bacon. The taste wasn't awful, but the taste was definitely odd. But, the kicker that forced me to give it two stars was the plastic that I found in my burger! There was an entire piece of plastic that was stuck in the center of the party. That was a horrible turnoff for the restaurant. 

After informing the manager, their response was not the best. They offered no apology and quickly tried to run away with the dish. Unfortunately, I was in a hurry and had no time to wait for another one to arrive. But, their overall attitude regarding their mistake was summarily unapologetic. 

Overall, the restaurant may be a good one. But for me, their service and food caused me to give them a two star review. Maybe if I am in the area again, I can try again and see how they do. But for now, two stars is all it gets for it's food and service.

column12:
I was craving a eggs Benedict so I searched and it brought me to State & Fig. My girlfriend ordered a burger and we both shared each. The service was top notch! Everyone in the entire place did such a great job that I felt very welcomed and comfortable. 

The food used good ingredients and tasted fresh. They gave us the wrong burger though because it came with bacon and we ordered a basic one. Interesting combo to use a sweet fig sauce on the burger which wasn't the one we ordered. I doubt they make mistakes like this often though because they really do seem to care.

I am glad I came here and am also glad they stayed open until 3pm. For whatever reason so many similar restaurants in that area closed at 2pm.

column12: Killer local spot that has been in Carp for over 50 years and it's obvious why they've weathered the years. Lots of food for a fair prices and the service is always friendly. I went for Easter brunch with my girlfriend and we had the most exceptional server Kimmy take care of us. She made the experience beyond enjoyable and always had a smile when she stopped by our table! I was so sad when their spot on Chapala in Santa Barbara closed, though understandable with some of the other breakfast spots close by. Would highly recommend this spot to any of my friends and I'm sure to be back soon!
