column12:
This place is perfection. The challenge: not so easy to find, but worth it. So keep looking. Go down the the little alley behind the Lark and find this little piece of heaven. 

Beautiful industrial decor. Extremely knowledgeable bartenders. Nabil is a rockstar. They take great pride in their cocktails. Attentive wait staff and absolutely delicious food. 

We came in for a cocktail. Had a thoughtfully presented charcuterie platter and will come again and again for dinner and more delicious cocktails.

thanks but no thanks.

column12: Went with my Husband, mother in law, which is the pickiest women alive, My husband is a Manager of one of the biggest hotels in Malibu, so he knows what customer service is, and the service was excellent, thanks to a young guy named Joey, this kid was amazing, he even had my mother in law happy! he should get 10 stars just for that! She said she would go back their any time! usually we cannot take her any where with out embarrassing us, food to hot to cold etc, my husband was so impressed with this kid that he gave him his business card! and said if your ever looking for a job to give him a call, I have been married to this man a long time and he has never done that! I asked him if he was short on workers he said nope, he said the kid was street smart, young, and not from around here? he said most of his managers in their 40's are not as smart as this kid, when it came to customer service. He was a really good looking kid to. I guess he was imported like the good beer!

column12:
This is actually my second time eating at this wonderful Mexican restaurant. First, it is incredibly clean inside. They have all the classics ,tacos ,burritos, quesadillas ,tortas.... But what makes this place truly exceptional is a huge amount of different types of meats you can 
choose from. Everything from lengua to al pastor, shredded beef and the list goes on.... They have outdoor seating and four or five different types of salsa. The prices are reasonable and the servings are quite large. Personally I highly recommend the Torta Cubana.

I am giving this store Ten Stars for friendliness, cleanliness, service and amazing products.

column12:
This place deserves a solid 5 stars!! I've been around and in the food bus most of my life and TOMA HAS IT ALL! Great service, innovative delicious food, ambience, great cocktails and wine list. 
Service-We were walk-ins at 5:15 on a Monday. Found it on Yelp as we were passing through town. The host was very kind, welcoming and accommodating. Our waiter, Gabe C, was knowledgeable, not pushy, didn't rush us, he was very attentive, interactive and made us feel relaxed so we could enjoy our meal. And he used a crumbed! A lost touch of class art. The bus boys were attentive and made sure dishes were cleared and our waters were filled. Amazing staff!
Food- So crazy great! The tuna cones were the right amount of spice for the tuna wrapped in a medium sweet delicate sesame cone. The combination was perfect!
The lasagna was by far the best I ever had. Flavors of red wine soaked braised beef with ricotta spinach filling and well balanced sauce. Fabulous!
The very light pillows of gnocchi were accompanied by succulent rock shrimps, baked tomatoes and bits of truffle. Again, the best I've ever had. It's light, not like most heavy gnocchi I've experienced.
Our waiter sent us out a taste of their raspberry mousse with strawberries that can be found in their phyllo crisp...outrageously good!
The Local starts with a reduced balsamic swirl on the inner rim of the glass, then filled with muddled strawberries and basil, mixed with cucumber vodka, agave and lime...the perfect cocktail...I had two!

Do not take a second thought, make a reservation now! By 5:45 this place had almost every seat filled!

Thank you to TOMA and the amazing staff!

column12:
We dined at Toma, mid-week, with local friends who highly recommended it.  What an unexpected surprise!   Honestly, we had never associated Santa Barbara with fine dining and expect fine food even less often at an Italian restaurant.  Wrong on both counts!

Toma was great.  The location, just across from the beach, couldn't be better.  The room is warm and charming, with an elegant, high-end feeling.  Service was excellent and the staff seemed very knowledgeable about both the food and the very well done wine list.  

The food was sumptuous, with unique combinations and presentations.  We particularly liked the lasagna, which had a wonderful assembly and texture, rather than the mush that is often served.  Proteins were perfectly prepared and presented and even the customary Minestrone  and the Rigatoni were outstanding.

Toma was a great choice and we expect to be back at our next visit.

column12: Excellent meal and excellent service from Trey! Due to covid the restaurant has set up outdoor dining outside along the sidewalk. Luckily they have a beautiful view of the water right across the street. Tables were socially distanced and I felt safe eating there with my family. We kept it simple and ordered the ravioli and rigatoni. There wasn't anything leftover! We really enjoyed the fried olives as well that came out complimentary with the bread. Such a cute romantic spot in Santa Barbara. I could tell it was a favorite as there wasn't an empty table in sight!

column12: Like everyone else has mentioned, the best thing about this place is the location and the view. Besides that, it's mediocre. Not sure if it was because we were seated in the back corner and our server forgot about us or...? Anyways, my food took forever to arrive even though the place was almost empty (around 8PM on a Sunday) The clam linguine here had way too much pasta and way too little clam. I try to give this place a second chance but service is always slow and the waiting game for my food exceeds the usual amount of time (compared to other restaurants in the area).

column12:
I live up in the dorms at UCSB, and every time I come back from my hometown in LA my family and I ALWAYS stop here. Unfortunately, I'm leaving UCSB after my first year... I'm going to miss coming to this place!

Beachside is literally on the beach; it's at the base of a long pier, and the outdoor seating is only separated from the actual sandy beach by some bamboo blinds. You couldn't have better scenery than this while having a good lunch or dinner.

The seafood here is really fresh: I've tried halibut, salmon, scallops, mussels, clams, you name it. All of it is delish! Dinner comes with some (free hehe) freshly baked bread, and all entrees come with soup. My family and I always choose the clam chowder. At Beachside, the clam chowder is a lot more chow than you would normally imagine. Every bite is loaded with clams and potatoes! Yum! Prices are what you'd expect of fresh seafood... in fact, I'm surprised they don't charge more given theres no competition in the area.

column12:
Probably one of my favorite places to go with friends. Drinks or tea at the bar before dinner or even just for after dinner tea. The best place to people watch. 

Pickled veggies presented upon seating. Nice. 

Deviled eggs are yummy. Creamy and a bit different from the regular recipe other places use. 

Beet salad is light and delicious. Small so if you share like I did with 2 others, you'll only get a few bites. 


Seabass is so good. Perfectly seasoned and crispy skin on top of a bed of veggies. One of my favs. 

Service is always attentive and great. Make reservations ahead of time unless you're ok with hanging out at the bar for an hour or so for a table at dinnertime.

column12:
Stayed at the hotel and had most of our meals there. First I have to say that the service is FANTASTIC! From the moment you walk in until your seated the servers are extremely attentive and friendly. We were there with our 2 year old and she was acknowledged and was made to feel very comfortable. That's extremely important to us that she's made to feel welcomed just as the adults are which was very apparent here. The waiter also suggested plates that were spot on and delicious!
I know other reviewers already mentioned it, but I have to mention it again since the scallops are amazing! They need to have there own review! They were cooked perfectly and were paired with a horseradish vinaigrette. They only thing I wish was that there were more of these yummy little guys! 4 is great but 5 would be better. 
Pork chop was equally as delicious and were paired with a very delicious compote and a butternut squash mash.
Kids menu looked good but your better off ordering the appetizer portions instead of the kids menu. I asked the waiter if the Mac and Cheese was "real cheese" and he said it was velveta type cheese. For my foodie 2 year old that would not cut it. He did mention that if I ordered the appetizer Mac and Cheese it would be actual aged cheese. This to us sounds like the better choice and our little one agreed. 
We did also try the deviled eggs as a starter but personally for us they didn't work. This is something we wanted to try but unless you Love eggs I'm sure there is something else you can try.

Of course since they have impeccable service we were offered desert on the house since they knew we were celebrating! We chose the lavender honey Crème brûlée and it did not disappoint. 
Overall the service, food, and drinks are impeccable. If your visiting Santa Barbara I suggest you eat there for at least one meal.

column12:
So sad, as I was really looking forward to this meal.  First, it was difficult to determine where one was supposed to go to be seated.  As a guest in the Kimpton Canary, it should not be hard, but it was.  We were finally greeted by the hostess who ushered us to a very comfortable booth (imagine sitting in what feels like the material of a very nice bomber jacket - SWEET).  There was a light at the table, which was necessary, as this restaurant is dimly lit (oh, and it got even dimmer throughout our dinner).  I couldn't read the wine/cocktail menu due to the low light and small font size, and my eyes aren't that bad.
My husband helped in my wine selection, as I reviewed the menu.  I was super excited about the burrata and caramelized pears appetizer (proceeds go to charity) and the fried chicken special.  Housemade pickles were delivered to our table, as well as water and a water carafe (don't worry SB tap water tastes great!).  Our wine arrived just as some very loud women entered the restaurant.  They were seated at the other end of the restaurant, but their laughter was LOUD.  One table requested reseating immediately.  Then another.  One table actually left - not good.  
Then our burrata appetizer arrived.  It was not what I expected.  It had a lot of pesto, and not many pears.  The crostini were slightly charred toast triangles.  The burrata was fine, but there was a definite battle among the +10 ingredients.  We stopped eating it, and the gracious server removed it (yes, it was comped).
Then, the mains arrived.  This redeemed the experience to a 3 star from a single star.  The chicken and mashed potatoes and gravy and pickles were to die for!  Perfect chicken!  Probably the best fried chicken I've ever had.  I'm from the south, so that's a huge compliment. My husband's beef short rib was amazing as well, but the menu descriptor didn't quite match what he received.  But, it was really great.  
Positives - Amazing service, great wine list, very good food
Cons - Disruptive clientele, poor lighting, really dated and dirty carpets/rugs, and way too many ingredients in some dishes.
The chefs know how to cook - they just do too much.

column12: I'm always searching for the best fried chicken and Finch & Fork didn't disappoint. I would actually give them 4-1/2 stars if i could. We started with the blistered shishito peppers and the cream caramelized onion soup. If i can only make that soup! For some reason i was expecting something like french onion soup, brothy. This was creamy heaven. The onion breadcrumb topping was yummy! My friend and i shared the buttermilk fried chicken. All i can say is thank god it was Tuesday! That was the special of the day. It came with mashed potatoes and pickles. I'm not sure i'm glad this is far from my home or not. I suppose I am or I'd be there every Tuesday. Super cute place and good service. If I'm in the area I will definitely be back to try some of their other choices.

column12:
So my sister and were looking for a New Mexican restaurant to try yesterday as we usually go to Los Agaves but the only item we really like there is the ceviche. We were craving those street tacos that are delicious but not every place can make them well. We liked up Aaron Sanchez recommendations in SB and came across Monys. What a great find. We got there around 3 and there was a line and all seats were taken as seating is limited. But people are eating and leaving so up to you to wait for a table. I'm glad we took the small one inside next to the fabulous salsa bar. One was better than the other they had like 8 of them. Peanut salsa was my favorite it had a nice kick to it and went great on the tacos we ordered. Tried al pastor Asada and carnitas. Pastor was our favorite although all 3 were delicious. Loved the marination and flavors. The pineapple added a little something extra to the meat. The tortillas were fresh and had chewy texture. My kind of tortilla not the one that falls apart when you start biting into taco. Also the price was super reasonable like $1.75 each. They give you chips and salsa on the house. Staff was friendly and efficient. Can't wait to come back here. Definitely worth the drive from LA. So this place is in the Funk zone of SB but what was interesting that no local could tell us why or how it got its name but we found out how expensive the new condos are going for. Mucho mucho dinero!!!$$$$$$ 
Two thumbs up for Monys!!

column12: This is my favorite place for ice cream and I visit it each time I'm in Santa Barbara.  The original shop is on Mission Avenue, a bit farther uptown, and I like it because of the atmosphere of "old-timey ness", with photos of all the famous people, including President Reagan, who have had their ice cream.  Their outdoor patio uptown is also nice and there's a very small lot for parking.  Lots of flavors to choose from and the ice cream is very creamy and rich.

column12:
My now husband and I got married in Santa Barbara on November 5, 2016. We had a small intimate wedding of 70 guests at the Santa Barbara Courthouse with a cocktail reception that followed at Cadiz Restaurant and Lounge. 

We knew very early on that we wanted to get married at the Santa Barbara Courthouse, but really had no direction as to where to have our reception. I went to the internet, and Cadiz was mentioned a few times. I sent an e-mail through the website, and received a phone call within a hour. After speaking with Messina for 20-30 minutes, I scheduled a time where my fiance and I could meet her and check out her restaurant. Unbenounced to us, she had a full tasting prepared for us upon our arrival. The food and drinks were superb, and we loved the look and ambiance of the restaurant. It was really important to us to have our reception at a location with a lot of character because I didn't want to spend money decorating it... Cadiz is beautiful!!! It has a lot of exposed brick which I love. 

A few days later, my fiance and I made the final decision to have our reception at Cadiz. When we booked, I had to pay for the price in full. That covered a valet parking, an open bar and food for the number of guests we had planned on inviting. I was very unsure about paying in full, but it all worked out. 

Shortly after booking, we asked Messina for a DJ recommendation. She booked someone for us that she worked with a lot. We didn't meet him until the day of the wedding, but he was awesome!!! Everyone was raving about DJ Calvin Riley.

After all the plans were set in place, Messina and I didn't really talk until the week before the wedding. At that time, we reviewed the wedding details and just made sure we were on the same page for the weekend. 

Our event was flawless!!! The food and drinks were on point. Messina is very professional, and she frequently checked in with me throughout the night. If anyone is looking to do a small reception in Santa Barbara, I would highly recommend Cadiz. Messina knows how to throw a party!

column12:
The poor service and food more than obliterated the casual and nice ambiance-don't bother. 

First, the tuna sandwich, was misdescribed by our inept server, Meghan, as "sushi grade" ahi. Not so--it was a cheesy (literally) unappetizing mixture of canned tuna, cheese and celery that looked like vomit and that even Star Kist would be embarrassed be associated with. 

Second, while there were only 5 of about 30 tables occupied for lunch (hardly a server demanding crowd) Meghan, could not have been slower, more inept or more rude. It took way too long to get menus, iced tea and order our meal. Then, when asked to serve some bread along with soup, she crisply answered: " We do not have bread at lunch." Then she brought the obnoxious sandwich on its roll thatI guess was not bread. 

Oh well....

column12:
We were passing through the city and in the mood for chinese food.  I was actually surprised that Santa Barbara did not have many options for chinese.  Anyway, we made a good choice as the service and food was great.
When we were seated we were saying how there was not too many people for dinner.  Within a few minutes the place was packed with people and people were waiting.  We also noticed that they were filling a lot of phone orders. 
We had the beef with ginger and basil along with the szechuan shrimp.  Both were great.  We would obviously come here again and recommend this place to our friends.

column12: Did a short weekend trip to SB and found this place on yelp.  Service was really nice but I expected more from the food.  Started with the crawfish popcorn and that was pretty good.  The muffins were only OK.  We ordered the classic jambalaya over rice, but it was really salty and we had a hard time finding the rice.  I think there was like 4 spoonfuls maybe in there...somewhere?  The best part of the meal was definitely the bread pudding.  If you go, I would say just go for dessert and maybe drinks (they looked pretty refreshing although I didn't have one myself).

column12:
Walking up to the place and seeing a line out the door, I knew I was going to experience greatness. Luckily for my party and I, my friend made us reservations at 5:30 and we just walked past everyone in line and straight to our seats. We were greeted by a friendly waiter and explained how the place operates. Everyone works together so you can ask any waiter for anything and they bring it to you in a moments notice. 

We started off with the popcorn crawfish and it was absolutely incredible. So good that my end of the table had to get a second plate of them. You have to try these. 

After the popcorn crawfish came great assorted muffins which were really good too. I had the blackstrap molasses one and it was great paired with some butter. 

For the entree, I ordered the filet mignon stuffed with crawfish and it was perfect. You must try it. One bite and you will never want the experience to end. 

Great food mixed with a fun atmosphere and you have a real winner here. Make reservations or if you have to wait, it would be worth it.

column12:
My boyfriend surprised me by taking me here for my birthday dinner. Great choice because everything was on point.
Our server was by far the best that I have had anywhere. She was fun and happy and made sure we were having a great time. Not only was the service the best, but the food as well. 
I had the veal with crayfish and pasta with the vegetables on the side. So good, it filled me up quick.  We finished the night with bread pudding, which had a special birthday message on the plate. As long as I'm in Santa Barbara, I'll be going back.

column12:
I enjoy going to this place. One thing that stuck out the most for ne was their excellent customer service. Almost every worker came by our table and helped us out weather it was to give us water or handing us our food. This place is definitely one of a kind. 

I love it when they have that special time in the day when everyone sings together to a classic jazz song. When I was there we sang "wonderful world" by Louis Armstrong. 

Their food is good too. This place is prolly the first place I've really started liking cajun. Their pasta are all good. And their little muffins they serve as appetizers are  soooo good! I can get full off them alone. 

Overall good experience.

column12:
Boy, do I dislike Palace Grill's food. I've dined here several times at the encouragement of my family members and out of town guests and each time I have been disappointed. Palace Grill is to cajun food, what Chilli's Bar & Grill is to mexican food. Exactly, not comparable! 

Everything that I have ordered is drowned in salt. Apparently, that's all you need to call it cajun food. Perhaps I'm spoiled because I lived in Louisiana for a few months and had real cajun food on the regular. The dishes they are serving up at Palace just don't hit the mark in my humble opinion. 

I do enjoy their cocktails, on the other hand, and their bread pudding. If' you're just drinking, eating dessert or don't mind a little hypertension, Palace Grill is your place! 

The atmosphere is quite lively and colorful which is a nice treat to some of Santa Barbara's more sterile dining ambiances.

column12:
Not impressed with the cocktails...there are wayyyy more creative ways to make cocktails. But I come from a more cultured city than SB. Having pineapple and rum in almost every "tiki" drink made me feel like I was in college. Why not try pears, persimmons, mangos, passion fruits, dragon fruits, kumquats, etc that would help reinvigorate each drink. I also messaged you all as well and asked if you had food/snacks. You replied with a yes. And we get there and you only had three choices of sad soggy empanadas. If your cocktails are going to be that sweet, have a snack that contrasts this. Even fresh French fries with spices (sumac etc) or pork rinds to get people to drink more. Anything with a some salt content obviously would get more money in your pockets. We were here for an hour and for a place that does cocktails in a small town that does wine and beer you guys should Be crushing it. For those that are going to try this place during the pandemic...Oaxacan dead was decent. Purple mai tai not worth it. 

Your IG made me wanna stop by but after seeing customers only stay for one drink, made me question how "exotic/crafty" your cocktails can be. 

You deserve 1 star but I gave you two cause you're open during a pandemic.

column12: I went there randomly for a date and I couldn't have been more happy with my mistake. I cannot remember our servers name but he obviously was either the owner or head chef. He talked about his dishes with such passion and excitement which only made the experience that much better. His passion for food was translated brilliantly on to the plates. If I had to give 1 recommendation for anyone eating here, ORDER THE BONE MARROW!! This dish is for sure one of the top 3 foods I have ever indulged upon. Our server connected with us on a personal level and his energy and love for the job is translated brilliantly to not only the guests, but the food as well. Cheers!

column12: I come often due for the amazing coffee, treats for the kids and convenient parking.  Not a bad place to stop while in Carp.  Very pricey though.  The only drawback is the service.  I don't believe the employees like people or their jobs.  EVERYTIME I go in the employees are horrible.  Crack a smile once in a while.  Be nice to me while I give you $13.50 for coffee and some cupcakes!  The same young blonde at the register helps us and she for sure HATES kids.  I really want to love this place, but for now I like it.

column12: This place has it all: great eats, reasonable prices, live music, a hip yet quaint atmosphere, and perfect service. Plus parking was a breeze. They have plenty of vegetarian options as well as hearty meat items. I had the cheese and guava cubes (I am not sure what they are really called), Brussels sprouts, chipotle potatoes, the cheese plate, a salad, and some other items that I can't remember the names of. Each is is good for two people to share and we ended up ordering about 6 or 7 tapas. I recommend getting the sangria and don't miss dessert. The wait staff was really attentive and friendly. This is a good place to go if you want that upscale, chic restaurant feel for the "struggling college student" prices.

column12: Must try the potato croquettes. I was walking along state street with my husband and we were disenchanted with the number of bars that had out of control drunks or just gave us a bad vibe. column12:
My first visit here was an experience in perfection. Nothing over the top, or wildly "foodie" innovative, just good classic food and cocktails, done right.

There are two distinct dining areas, to suit your mood. The front area is the bar and bistro area, for when you're feeling casual or moody.
The back area is for more formal dining, although there's no stuffy feeling in the atmosphere. It's quieter, with brighter lighting, linens, a view of their extensive cellar, and larger tables. 

I went with four friends for a quiet weekend evening and the first thing we noticed on the menu was the cocktails, with dates next to them. The dates are the accepted years that each of those cocktails was devised. It was our first hint that this place had purist ideals.  
We sat at the bar to sample some of these cocktails where we learned:

* they make their own orgeat for mai tais,
* they make their own tonic water,
* they use real Marasca cherries in their Manhattans,
* and the Zombie really packs a punch (limit 2 per customer).

We sampled more than this, but I do not want to appear like a total lush, so I'll leave it at that. The bottom line on the cocktails is that Sly's is serious about them, making sure they're done proper. I have no doubt the other cocktails on the menu are just as good.

We stuck around for dinner, and remained at the bar. The bartender knew the menu forwards and back, including the specials, and could name the sources of all the dishes we inquired about, especially when they came from local businesses. I think it's important to note here that the more questions we asked about the food, the more pleased they were to answer them, because I feel their knowledge of ingredient sources and preparation is what makes Sly's different to other steak and seafood places. And it's really something to be proud of.

I had the mussels, Spanish style, which came with firm chorizo, caramelized onions and a tomato-based sauce that was so delicious we used our hot bread to soak up all those good juices. I even resorted to scooping it up with a spoon since there was so much. The dish was also generously portioned, about 20 mussels, and it cost $14. There are several other sauce options, and they all range in price between $12-$14. So reasonable.
I also had the streak frites. It was also a sensible price of $14, with a sensible 4 oz portion of steak, which was cooked perfectly to my request. There are sauce options as well, and I had mine with a green peppercorn cream, my absolute favorite sauce for steak. The french fries are also perfect, and the meal reminded me so much of simple dining in France and Belgium, I had to ask for a little mayonnaise for my fries and was rewarded with a dish of delicious housemade mayo. Everyone in the group dug into those fries with mayonnaise, we never even removed the cap of the nearby ketchup bottle.

Nothing could top a meal that brought back those European memories like a round of profiteroles for dessert could. I swear I had no idea what was on the menu and when I was offered the dessert menu I flat out said I could not be tempted, unless there was profiteroles.  And guess what was there, prominently displayed on the menu. YES!  A handful of choux pastries filled with vanilla ice cream, topped with chocolate sauce and a warm pot of housemade dark caramel sauce on the side.  The price on this varies, depending on the number of profiteroles requested. I selected 5, and that was $13.

There are many other items on the menu, different cuts of steak, bigger cuts, lots of fish and shellfish. The prices are generally on the upper end, as these are sourced from reputable specialty companies, not mysterious agri-beef businesses or large scale produce corporations. But still, the items we happened to order were very affordable, especially given the attention to detail and the quality of everything. 

I took photos of the food we got and some of the cocktails. Hope that's helpful!

column12:
Prices are excellent.   The combo for less than $9 comes with a good size fries, double cheeseburger, and a drink.   Very simple menu, which I liked!

It's a hole in the wall location with several outdoor seating areas.  Nothing fancy at all.  Didn't look like it's changed in 30 years.

The food is sort of like a non-branded In-N-Out.  

If you wanted melted American cheese on a double beef burger for a good price, this is your place.  It's not a fancy burger, but they stay in their lane!

Was recommended by a local, for locals, during my stay in the area.

column12: Amazing sushi - perfect to take home in the midst of COVID-19 or any time!  The taste and quality of every roll was fantastic.  The Rainbow Roll was especially delicious.  The Salmon Skin Roll was the best I have ever had, including in Japan.  This was my first time here since social distancing, so I called to see what precautions the restaurant was taking.  They are doing everything right:  masks, hand washing, gloves and sanitizing.  They care about all the right things, especially the quality of the food and service.

column12:
There is something special about going to a restaurant when the owner is charge. 
You feel taken care of and you never doubt or question the integrity of the food or the service. This is after all their investment, their livelihood on the line. 

Ive been here several times and overall I love the owner's service and I love their food. I wish the owner the best of luck in making it, here in IV, the area is saturated with restaurants and its very competitive. 

Im not sure how long the owner will be running the show, but for now, I think this is the best time to go eat at Sorriso's. 

Make sure to get the Nutella dessert, it is just amazing!

column12:
REAL Indian cuisine with GREAT service.

The food itself was very much how indian food tastes...intense flavors. The flavors were super strong and very different from the Americanized Indian food that I am usually used to. 

1.) Appetizer Sampler: Samosa was good and was JAMMED to the top with all the filling. The onion ring-ish things were good but a tad salty. The lamb sausage thing was very very flavorful and soft. The tandoori chicken was good too.

2.) Lamb Vindaloo/Chicken Tikka Masala Combo Plate: The raita was very tangy and very different from what I used to have, but was good! The rice was of course good. The Lamb vindaloo and chicken tikka masala was more focused on the meats then the sauce. I hafta say I'm more of a thick sauce girl who like to dips her naan in it. But these curries were more focused on the meat with a thinner sauce. But they were extremely flavorful and tender. The paneer matar that came with it was awesome. The paneer was VERY soft and light.

3.) Naan: YUMMY! Very fresh and doughy/soft but very good taste to it.

I liked this place's service and the food, but I prefer more saucier sauces. But it was great and they're SO nice here! AWESOME service.

column12: When I have any reason to be near Santa Barbara, I make sure to save time for a meal at Stella Mare's.  Lunch or dinner, it's become a favorite.  I like everything about the experience.  Starting with the way it's decorated.  Everywhere your eye travels, there's something else interesting.  The staff offers exactly the right amount of attention - not hovering, but then you'll never want for anything either.  Did I mention the food?  While this part of California offers many great places to eat, the food at Stella Mare's is so good, and the decor and service both exceptional, so I keep postponing trying other nearby places. Sounds like I'm on the payroll.  I'm not, but I do believe in praise where praise is due.  If you want a memorable meal, lunch or dinner, alone or with a group, you'll find it at Stella Mare's.  If I didn't live hours away, I'd be there for lunch today.

column12:
Came into the Nook wednesday night with my boyfriend and our dog! The patio is dog friendly so that's awesome! 
We ordered the Rockfish tacos, Topa Topa burger with truffle fries and the german pretzel!
The girl at the counter was super friendly and recommended gluten free options for me! the fish tacos come on corn tortillas and are super flavorful and tasty! My boyfriends Topa Topa burger was cooked a perfect medium rare, the bacon jam is amazing!! The burger "house sauce" is so good, like thousand islands on crack :) truffle fries were cheesy and they also had pesto on them with the perfect amount of truffle!
the pretzel is served warm with cheese and mustard and it was so soft! 
we are so happy that SB has such a unique place, that's dog friendly with amazing food!! we can't wait to come back!

column12: Okay, if you don't go to Book Ends Cafe for one their amazing sandwiches and/or salads, then you are missing out.  The space is great, the people are warm and engaging, and the food....I had 1/2 sandwich/salad combo.  Brisket Banh Mi sandwich -- tender, juicy meat with pickled carrots and radish, cilantro, and jalapeno vinaigrette. So happy with that choice!  The salad was a kale and tabouleh mixture that was light and wonderful.  All the meat is sustainably raised, the vegetables are farmers market fare, the pickling is done by the cooks.  The pickles on the side were awesome!  When I complimented the owner on his pickles, he brought me more on the house.  Do yourself a favor and take a midday vacation to Book Ends!  You will not be sorry.

column12:
First visit was about a month after High Sierra opened. Chalked up the paltry food and bad service to opening jitters. Second visit months later and not much better. Recommended this morning to order the brunch by waitress because, "it's better than anything we have on our regular menu." Asked at the omelette station where I could order a couple of simple eggs. Guy at the omelette station couldn't even speak English. Asked another staff member and was told omelettes were included but two simple eggs would cost me extra. ???? Tried instead to order eggs Benedict which is on the menu and was told that they stopped serving those and that I could get chicken sliders instead. Why have a menu listing all the items served from 9:00 to 2:30 and then not serve them. Total bait and switch. This third time was the worst and I've learned my lesson.

Gave it one star 'cause zero stars wasn't an option.

column12:
I am so happy to have found this place! The happy hour cannot be beat and it's right by my office. The food is modestly priced and the service was very attentive when we went for lunch on a Friday around noon. This place is huge and I can definitely see returning here with a big group. My favorite part is how dog friendly they are. We sat inside and they brought my pup his own little doggie menu. 
All around great experience and I look forward to trying more things on the menu. The burger was so good though, I might order it again. I asked for my burger rare and it came out perfect :)

column12: We thought we would enjoy trying out the new restaurant and weren't disappointed.  The tri tip sandwich was excellent.  We also really enjoyed the steak and blue bite appetizers...tender cuts of steak with crumbled blue cheese.  Additionally, the dinner salads that came with our meals were the best I have ever had.  Overall all of the food was awesome.  Yes, the service was a little challenging, but as a newly opened restaurant that is to be expected.  The new owners have done great things with the decor and the patio is amazing!  I can see great things happening at this place.  We will definitely be back!

column12:
We fly a lot and never expect too much from restaurants in an airport.  But, this little place hit the spot.  They have nice big tall draft beers, I think $8.  Not terrible for airport beer. Same price as the beer you buy on the plane but twice as big.
We had the beef tacos which were very flavorful and nice and hot.  Our waitress was friendly and did a great job.  
We were not in a rush, so we can't comment on how speedy the service could be if you were in a hurry.
We will eat here again.

column12:
I'm giving the restaurant a 3.5 & the lounge a 4. I actually did not eat in the restaurant. I was staying at the Best Western adjacent to the restaurant & they do the room service for them. On day one we ordered room service for breakfast. It was your standard scrambled eggs, bacon, toast & fruit. I had no complaints with breakfast, but my wife didn't like the scrambled eggs. Bacon, well, it's hard to mess that up and the fruit & toast were fine. 

The following night I went into the restaurant and ordered a Cobb salad, burger & fries to go. Again, not difficult to prepare and even more difficult to screw up. My wife & I were both pleased with our meals. Their service was fantastic. The manager and waitstaff was very friendly. 

I visited the lounge a few times over the weekend for a quick drink with my family members, since we were in Santa Barbara for a wedding. The drinks were good and the bar tenders were great. I don't remember the woman bar tender's name, but she stayed after the restaurant staff had gone home, so we could keep enjoying our cocktails and spending some QT with family members. My family's spread all across the country & we don't see each other that often, so it was really appreciated that she did this.

column12:
Y'all. The ideal local coffee shop is Old Town Coffee! Close parking, plenty of seating, fair prices, tons of accessible outlets, dog-friendly patio, and AMAZING coffee!

My husband and I were excited about having another local coffee shop nearby, and we love that this place is located on Hollister in Old Town. There is street parking available and a public parking lot about one block away, which is quite convenient.

The vibe here is welcoming and it's suitable for families, study groups, coffee dates, and all types of people. There are seriously plenty of areas to sit in, too, depending on the purpose of your drop in! I enjoy bringing my dog and sitting on the back patio near the corn hole set-up. The patio tables and umbrellas make it really comfortable to enjoy my Brulée Mint tea.

And for you grad students out there: OUTLETS. There are plenty of outlets stationed throughout the space, so you can settle in, order several drinks, and finally work on that paper you've been putting off without your computer dying.

One of my favorite things is that Old Town uses Rise Coffee Roasters and these beans are *the best* I've had in Santa Barbara/Goleta. They're not too dark, not harshly acidic, and each blend has a distinct flavor. In other words, these beans make good coffee and espresso in every application! Bags of beans are a great price, and the drinks themselves are a great price, too. And the Old Town Coffee baristas have also been pretty consistent in their beverage execution. Or if it's not perfect, let them know! They'll happily help you get the best beverage possible.

The owners, Tim & Rachel, are kind souls. Tell them hi, become a regular, and support their hard work!

No bike racks out front, but I'm sure you'd be able to wheel your bike to the back to rest on the back patio!

column12:
ABSOLUTELY AMAZING!! My friend and I decided to give this NEW place a try, and I'm glad we did. Everything here is perfect: the open-to-the-street design, the food, wines. 

I ordered the ORO PURO pizza which is the one with black caviar and 24k gold flakes. I've never had gold on my gourmet before so I had to try, and besides, the caviar was amazing so that's what was giving the pizza the rich flavor. The dough is black unique dough which makes it feel like fresher than white dough. My friend got the AVOCADO SALMON in a jar--so very fresh! The plating/utensils/the cork menu are unique: the jars, the bottle-plates (you'll understand what I'm saying when you go here). 

The OWNER is a wonderful man from Pravia, Italy, and he has so many amazing stories (and recommendations for travel). I loved listening to him! And he quotes the beginning of Dante's Inferno by heart. How can you not love this place after all this?! Go here please!! I want them to be successful and stay open. Oh yeah. Try the sweet wine he recommends with your dessert: out of this world!! HIGHLY RECOMMENDED

column12:
Took my beautiful wife out to Oppi'z for date night and it was really a great experience! The outdoor seating was so comfortable and with Italian music in the background we felt like we were back in Florence. 
Our server, Sara, was so sweet. She guided us through the menu and catered to our every need. She was calm, professional and really made our first time there very enjoyable. 
As far as the food.... It was fantastic! 
Delicious "salad in a jar" ( check it out, it's a thing), we tried the Ceci jar and the flavors were so good. 
For mains we split both the  Tagliatelle pasta with bolognese sauce as well as the Black Parma Pizza with black dough.
The pasta was sublime! Obviously house made and cooked to perfection. The sauce had so many delicious layers, really good.
The pizza was also off the charts! Cheese that just made you happy inside right when you bite into it. 
 First time trying Oppi'z, we will be back! Thank you to Sara for making our evening a romantic one! Highly recommend!

Yes, it's on the pricier side for some noodle or soup, but it's fresh food, quick, and yummy. The Bangkok noodle or hangover noodle are my usual go to. column12: Hands down the best bakery in Santa Barbara, everything is made fresh each and every morning and everyone working there are the most friendly and welcoming people ever. They offer fresh bread, sandwiches, breakfast burritos, and soups daily. They honestly make THE best sandwiches, and all your requests will be fulfilled. Want extra onions? not a problem. anything you want done to your sandy, just ask. There's plenty of parking, so you never have to worry about meters or anything. A couple of chairs and tables are outside so you can enjoy your breakfast and lunch outdoors. Definitely a go to place if you want good food fast.

column12:
This is the 2nd time that I've just joined friends outside on the Terrace to look at the ocean (this time near sunset).  Food is good, drinks rock and the view is unparalleled.  Pure Mediterranean meets Mission luxury.  It was cold though.  I can' wait to actually stay at the hotel, but if you are in town it's definitely worth stopping by for a stroll, the view and some nibble and drinks.

TIP:  You can't actually see the sunset from there.  A couple of minutes drive  South to the Golf Course will give you a gorgeous sunset view though.  We were lucky to have it pretty much to ourselves.

column12:
Great view but that's where it ends.

Patio seating on the edge of the surf can't be beat but the very limited selection let me wanting more. 
Scrambled eggs
Bacon & Sausage
Waffles
Breads
Omelet bar
Smoked salmon
And that's about it.

With most people self serving form the buffet, the wait staff has little to do. I guess they were too busy to come by and check on drinks. We had one round of mimosa and never offered a second round. The next time we saw our guy, we asked for the bill. 

Sure this could be a romantic evening or family filled Sunday brunch and if the service was better, I could justify the cost. The Bistro is just too much for too little.

column12:
BREAKFAST BUFFET 

We ate breakfast here everyday for the week we stayed at this lovely resort. The service is good but we had the buffet daily so there really wasn't much service needed. We where sat right away daily, mainly sat outside on the patio where there was outdoors heaters to keep us cozy. 

The omelette bar was marvelous, hubby was all about it. The freshest ingredients and lovely presentation of each omelette. There was a fruit bar, cheese and cold cuts, yogurt station, breads/bagels and some random hot foods including breakfast tacos, grilled veggies etc. 

The view though takes the cake at this little spot. We will definitely dine with them again.

column12:
The Shop Kitchen is a casual eatery near Santa Barbara High, where my husband Matt B. went to school. It's on the same street as La Super-Rica, and appears to be one of the newer, trendier places in the area, open since late 2012. We went for brunch on Easter Sunday, during an overnight visit to town.

It's essentially a fast food restaurant with fancier food and a beer and wine license. You order and pay at a window, then find your seat on either the patio or the somewhat gloomy indoor dining area. There was a line when we walked up around noon, but it moved pretty briskly. Service was quick and perfunctory. I ordered a drink and only asked after it when it didn't come with our food. It turned out it had been sitting out at a different window, where I was supposed to pick it up. If I was given that instruction at any point, I missed it entirely.

The Sriracha Bloody was okay, a little bit spicy and not very strong, as it must've been made with soju or some other 14% liquor. $7 was a fine price for it, though, and it came with some tasty pickled green beans.

My food was also okay. I got the General Sanders, a buttermilk fried chicken sandwich with apple slaw, sweet and sour carrots, and spicy mayo on a soft bun. The chicken was good, but there wasn't much to the other ingredients. More slaw, more carrots, more spice would've been great. I tasted a tiny bit of apple in like one bite, and the sandwich needed more texture and flavor overall. I did like the housemade potato chips, though not all of them were crispy. Matt's food was better. He got the Frenchie, a grilled french toast with real maple syrup, and it was solid.

This was a totally serviceable meal, and if we lived nearby, we might visit again. The Shop Kitchen strikes me as a useful neighborhood restaurant, an unfussy brunch stop where you can get in and out in well under an hour. There just wasn't so much to it that I'd go back again during a short getaway to Santa Barbara.

column12:
We were in Santa Barbara for the day and needed. A bit of sustenance to get us to the beach. We drove Down a quaint street with Mediterranean style buildings and parked around the corner on a residential street. The amount of noise from the construction going on directly in front of the restaurant gave us pause. However as soon as we sat down at a picnic table to sip on our mimosas the construction crew took a break. Yay!
     The food was exceptional, hot, fresh, and delivered with a smile. We especially Liked the Caesar salad and the french fries. We felt quite safe as the tables were spread apart nicely.

column12: We put our name on the wait list and were told the wait would be about 30-45 minutes. We made sure we got to the restaurant before then and checked in, but we ended up not being seated for over an hour and a half. When we finally got in, it took about 15 minutes for us to get water because they ran out of glasses. When we finally got our food, the chicken sandwiches were ridiculously spicy and the cheese steak had way too much horse radish on it. All in all, the food was subpar and not worth the wait at all.

column12: I have been coming here for over 20 years. I enjoy the good service, and inside the environment is open and airy. No recent remodel, it's dated, but clean, and I really appreciate the off street parking. The food is good ( food wise this is one of our better Thai restaurants ) and incredibly consistent. A few years ago, the owner's son decided to start expanding the homemade ice cream... he calls it "Creaminal Minds". What a success!  Be sure to try the fusion flavors, they're excellent. Thai basil with mint and chocolate, Thai coffee mixture, a marvelous list... even some vegan choices. You can get pints of ice cream to go, so be sure to share!

column12:
The service was a bit lacking, especially for the re-opening.  The girl that helped us looked like she didn't want to be there and was annoyed.  The atmosphere was not friendly - lighten up people, you work at an ice cream shop, not a morgue!  There is hardly any parking if someone parks their boat in the small lot.  There was no line when we got there.  The chocolate almond has a thin, cheap texture and is overrated.  The Brazilian coffee was pretty good, but half scoop was just about right.  

I like how you can have two flavors in one generous scoop.  Those two points = two stars.

column12:
Surprisingly, I was very underwhelmed with the Hyatt in Santa Barbara.  My husband and I traveled to SB for our anniversary and given the room rates, I suppose I had pretty high expectations.  The rooms were very dated, small, and oddly laid out.  Overall, things were clean, but not spotless and you could tell that the furnishings and carpet were old.  Our tub also flooded a bit if you stayed in the shower too long (fortunately, the front desk was able to have this repaired slightly mid-stay).

Highlights included the pool area and beach access.  The staff were also very friendly and helpful.  The hotel is located on the west end of town next to the zoo so does require having a car to get downtown (valet parking is $26/night).

While there wasn't anything terribly wrong with our experience, I don't think this Hyatt is worth the cost and was hoping for a bit more luxury.  I would probably explore other options next time...

column12:
If you have ever strolled down State Street in Santa Barbara, then you are aware that it is the home of a plethora of both local and chain restaurants and cafes. It can be overwhelming to choose the "right" one for your eating/drinking/socializing needs. La Arcada is one of the many options to choose from. How does it stack up?

La Arcada is a cute bistro located on a corner real estate offering indoor and outdoor seating in an Irish meets Spanish- ambiance (which makes sense as the owner is Irish while his wife is Mexican). During the early afternoon, it is calm and inviting but apparently can get rowdy on weekends when there is live Irish music reverberating the air. Think: Irish bar meets cafe with rustic wood trim but stuccoed walls. 

Although La Arcada didn't have too many customers at the time of our patronage (between 2 and 3pm); I didn't feel quite that welcome. It isn't that the server and staff were rude per se; they just weren't that inviting. Not to mention: slow. Very, very slow. Despite this, we browsed the menu having not yet eaten lunch seeking some light fare. My boyfriend and I decided to share plates and went with the House Salad (Grilled chicken, fire-roasted red peppers, red onion, blue cheese, toasted pine nuts,red delicious apples and mixed greens tossed with balsamic vinaigrette-- $16.00) and the Irish Soda Bread (with Kerry Gold butter and Dubliner Cheese -- $6.00). Due to it being Happy Hour, we also shared a Bellini ($5.00). 

The key to La Arcada is presentation. The salad and bread arrived at the same time and had an elegant but approachable feel. The salad was absolutely delicious with just the right amount of vinaigrette, tender chicken, and veggies. Although it was enough for my boyfriend and I to share; I still think it was much overpriced though for the quantity. Not necessarily satisfying if you are very hungry. The Irish Soda bread was a good deal with plenty of bread and large slices of cheese. I found the bread to be a little dry (and I love Irish Soda bread so I've had it plenty of times). It wasn't awful but I wasn't blown away. The Bellini was a highlight though. It was tasty and strong which is great being that it was a happy hour price and sometimes restaurants water down drinks during those times. 

A minor note but still worth mentioning is that the bathroom is a single-stall meaning that you have to wait quite a long time if someone is inside. Plus, it is an awkward back of the house area next to run down soda machines. Not good if you really have to use the bathroom!

There honestly isn't much more to be said about La Arcada. The experience wasn't bad but also not memorable on the positive side; making it simply an okay medium-choice on State Street but not life-changing. If nothing else though, the outdoor seating is quaint with great views of State Street. I would say this is a hit or miss option in lovely Santa Barbara.

column12: I'm in love! Such a great experience at Bouchon. I came here to celebrate my birthday with my husband. I was lucky enough to get a reservation just the day before and they decorated the table with rose petals and a personalized card for my birthday. We recently went to Paris over the summer and so it was nostalgic for us to be able to enjoy French cuisine done so well outside of France. I started with the savory foie gras that just melted in my mouth. Husband had trio of scallops- best scallops I've ever had! I ordered the Duck entree which the waiter said has been on their menu for 18 years. I can see why because this dish is definitely in the top 10 of dishes I've ever had. I wouldn't call myself a foodie or snotty when it comes to food. I just enjoy good food and good company. Husband got the rib eye, which was also amazing but he kept eyeing my duck so of course I shared. Ended the meal with the blueberry lemon upside down cake. Yum yum yum! I can't wait to make an excuse to come back to SB to have this meal again. Thank you Bouchon for a memorable dinner!

column12:
Great happy hour food/drink specials. 

I usually order chimichangas. Weird incident in which first 2 times i came here i had no cheese in them (which was fine, i didnt notice and they were delicious). Then came the third time and suddenly it was oooooozing w cheese (which is an oddly common trend in SB that i find unappetizing). The waiter gave me a hard time about this since the menu apparently states it has cheese, ignoring my comments that id ordered it several times before and it never been like that.....but usually Ive had good service. 

Another great dish is the garlic shrimp. The sauce is sooo good i mop it up with my garlic bread-which is also great.

They have 2 outdoor seating sections which are nice. Indoors theres a more restaurant-like section, and a larger section which is more sports bar like so it's a great place to catch a game too.

column12: There was an insect in my food. A legit big insect with wings. They claimed that it was a "shrimp tail" but I didn't order anything with shrimp. Just the fact that there was a bug in my food was disgusting enough for me to never go there and to tell my loved ones to never go there.

column12:
I have been eating here for two decades, primarily because of its pleasant atmosphere and convenient location.  The quality of the food has gone steadily down hill, to the point at which it is simply terrible.  

This evening we had the Seafood Platter and Pork Satay w/ peanut sauce, both were touted as "House Specialties".  Both were terrible, and we felt ill all night after eating them.  The Seafood Platter somehow tasted like reheated seafood that was several days old.  The peanut sauce tasted canned, and also seemed several days old.

We will never eat here again.  This has happened to us too many times here over the last few years.

column12: Having not eaten at this restaurant for over two years, my girlfriend and I thought it would be good to pay Your Place a visit. We were greeted quickly and politely, and our drinks were brought to us speedily as well. The real star quality of this restaurant comes from the menu. There are so many great dishes, it will probably take a while to pick your meal. While we decided on what to get, we had the waiter bring us some fried wantons. The appetizer came out very quickly, and we had finally chosen our entrees. Being a curry fan myself, I went with the panag curry house special and substituted tofu for meat. My girlfriend got the beef and bellpeppers. The food must have arrived a mere 7-8 minutes after we ordered. We were delighted with the food and the service from the evening. The only thing I would recommend to the staff would be to provide water after seating customers.

column12: Well this was a pleasant surprise...I expected a mediocre meal and both of us actually liked our food. I took the advice of a fellow yelper and ordered the fried artichokes and as a southerner, I actually thought they were good. The Coq au Vin was very good and the cobb salad was yummy but a bit too much dressing. The service and prices(!) were very good too but the wine list is terrible. I would go again, bring my own vino, and think "finally....a decent restaurant in this vicinity for spontaneous dining in my sweats"

column12: Used to be so good, even just a short time ago. Just got home with the most paltry burritos of anywhere in town. That used to not be the case. This was one of my sons favorite places to get a BRC burrito and usually they were delicious and very filling. Tonight for some reason it was the thinnest layer of beans, rice and cheese and a lot of tortilla. The $11 veggie burrito was shamefully also the slimmest layers  of beans, rice, cheese and some old, mushy  tomato inside a tortilla. Potato taquitos were good so that's worth the two stars. I'm hoping it was an off night as I've never had this experience before, but to be honest not sure I want to spend 30 bucks to go back and find out. There are really too many great places in town to risk going back for the same disappointment.

column12:
This place was empty at about 6pm when we rolled in.  And it's actually nicer that way.  Around 7pm is when it starts getting busy and loud...at least on a Saturday.

The prices worked well for us on a budget.  Special rolls were between 6-10 dollars-ish.  And they had regular rolls for less.  The serving sizes were smaller than I was used to, but it's probably more of the average (the sushi places in my town serve large rolls).  If anything, the portions were just right.  With an appetizer, three special rolls, and a tempura ice cream, the bill came out to about $35 for two people.

Oh yea, and they have quite an extensive appetizer list.  Pretty good portions for the price.  Would totally come back again.  Cute little venue.  Good service.  Great food.

column12:
When I first moved to Santa Barbara a year ago loved Edomasa amd went almost 1-2x week. Around 2-3 months ago things went downhill and fast. The last time I went in December my order was not written down by the small Asian lady who does not speak English well. After apologizing they brought out my Katsu which was so over fried I couldn't bite through it. The older man stationed at the cashier didn't care that I was a regular or that my order wasn't taken down or that my food was inedible. 

I went last night to give it one last chance and because my girl wanted to go. She ordered a tempura udon, I ordered a tempura donburi and we shared a hamachi roll. Except my order was never taken and again I had to ask what was going on. Same small Asian lady waitress who doesn't speak english well. Same reaction from older cashier, doesn't care about patrons. sad.

column12:
I was told presto pasta was a good place to go for cheap Italian and that was right it was cheap but not good. It wasn't the best place I have ever been too but it wasn't the worse. We ordered the chicken piccata, fettuccine alfredo, fried artichoke, and meatballs for to go. We didn't have too long to wait for our food it actually came out really quick. It wasn't that hot which was unfortunate because when we got home it was already kind of cold. 

The fried artichoke was not good at all. It was soggy and not crispy at all. The sauce that came with the artichoke was really good but the artichoke wasn't at all. 

The chicken piccata was good but not very warm. There wasn't much sauce on it either. 

The meatballs were really good and had alot of sauce. I think they were the best things we got. 

The fettuccine alfredo was not good at all. It was all clumping together and the sauce was not good at all. 

Overall I probably will not go here again or if I end up going there I will not get it to go.

column12: Steph and his team catered my wedding in august 2021. His crew did an amazing job. We got the tri tip and smoked turkey, garlic mashed potatoes, asparagus, salad with bread, and people won't stop telling me how good the food was. He also served appetizers during cocktail hour. He was super easy going, service was great from beginning to end, made sure everything clicked and was taken care of and looked great. He and his staff were so friendly. He was so organized, professional and completely reliable. Steph will make sure you get exactly what you want. His prices are fair and if you like bbq I totally recommend him in a heart beat. He makes bbq look like fine dining. He's the bbq man!

column12:
My friend and I experienced the rudest service of our lives at M. Special. On the night of April 21st, my friend and I visited to watch the Washington Capitals/Toronto Maple Leafs hockey game. During the first two periods of the game, we both drank two beers each. In the third period, one of the bartenders was nice enough to give us a couple samples out of the blue, which was much appreciated. Finally, with five minutes left in the game another bartender noticed our sample glasses, and came over to ask us if we wanted some 'big boy beers.' This  already seemed strangely antagonistic, and we declined as we were both driving after the game. Immediately, he went to the television and changed the channel away from the hockey game. We thought it might be a mistake, and asked that it be changed back, and he refused, saying it was 'kind of weird' that we weren't drinking any beers. 

We were both shocked and furious that he was being so petty and mean-spirited. We left the bar and missed the end of Game Five of a tied game in a tied series. This kind of service is just unfathomably rude and completely outside of our experience. Needless to say, neither of us will be returning and we're encouraging all of our friends to patronage other, more friendly establishments.

There was a food truck there in case you get the munchies.

The staff was nice and attentive and there was a huge variety of beer.  If you like beer, there will be something here for you.

There is plenty of free parking available.

I will certainly come back the next time I'm in the area.

Give them a call for current prices and to see what they are pouring.

column12:
I was underwhelmed. 
I've been there three times now.  Once was a weekend lunch, once was a weekday work group lunch and recently was after work drinks with a couple people.

Burgers are above average, salads are generous. The onion rings, which  were rumored to be good, were good, but pricey at $5.95. 
The hummus is also pricey at $5.95, but plated nicely.

The macaroni and cheese, though, bleah. Another $5.95 item, and as the ultimate comfort food, it's not unreasonable to expect comfort food. What we got was discomfort food. Actually, the worst I think I've ever had. Worse than boxed mac and cheese. Everyone in the group tried it and said, "wow. that's seriously bad."
The pasta was undercooked, like crunchy. The sauce tasted just like Taco Bell nacho cheese sauce mixed 1:1 with water.  More like crunchy pasta cheese-flavored soup.  There must have been some bad mojo going on in the kitchen to produce a dish like this.

Thank goodness we had the onion rings to tide us over.

column12:
A hidden gem in SB Funk Zone!

Lafond is cozy, clean and sleek tasting room with indoor seating and a cute selection of wino merchandise including home decor and foodstuff.  Tastings are $12 for 5 pours, and I like that the servers are knowledgeable about the product and offer descriptions without being asked.  The atmosphere is intimate, quiet and low-key, which is in contrast to other rowdy neighboring establishments.  Members and guests of the Lafond/Santa Barbara wine club receive free tastings!  Woot!

I love that they offer breadsticks to clean the palate!  Extra star for that.

column12:
We were looking for a place to eat in Santa Barbara that would satisfy my hunger and sisters who were looking for good salad. We had a couple places in mind thanks to Yelp and we ended up going to The Middle Child. We are so glad that we did. Both my sisters enjoyed their salads and the rest of us our personnel pizzas. We loved this place so much we decided to come back here the next day before we had back to the Bay Area. Their menu doesn't have a lot of items, but It's simple food that taste really good. My sister wanted a Caesar salad and had them top it with their fried chicken. They were both great (I ordered the same thing when we came back the 2 time), my other sister had their arugula salad and she loved that. I had the avocado pizza, and that was good too and my nieces shared the farmers market pizza which changes each time, depending what they decide to get at the market that day. It was a potato pizza and they both loved it. If you come here, GET their fried chicken. It is soooooo good.

You order your food and pay at the counter. They have an upstairs for more seating and also a cute outdoor seating area in the back. Staff is really friendly too.

column12:
For a new restaurant, this place totally hits the mark.  For a well established restaurant, this place still hits the mark.  The decor is vintage funk cool hip, unlike anything in Santa Barbara.  
The place is full of locals, and I mean full. It is getting rave reviews in all the local newspapers and deservedly so.  
The owners have created  tasteful, superb, friendly restaurant that has me in awe of a first time restarauntier.  
I am impressed, and have been there 2 times with excellent experiences, and will be continuing to go and make this my new go-to place and recommendation.

Still excellent. And the service is impeccable. They explain EVERY dish they bring to the table with a smile.

column12:
Awful experience, awful staff, awful food.

Went for dinner on a recent Wednesday night -- the place was half full.  Ok, great!  We have the pick of tables.   Not.

The greeter placed us at worst table in the house, and provided some half-baked explanation that they were understaffed, and certain sections were closed off.  We asked to be moved.  Not -- again.

Then "Patrick" -- the manager came out.  He was completely officious, demeaning, and not interested in accommodating the customer.  He then tried to immediately take our order, in particular the wine, after which I said "we'll order wine with rest of our meal."  This did not sit well with Patrick, who insisted that the wine be ordered at that time.  I refused and he left.  

On to the cuisine.  I don't even know where to begin with this.  There were SO many ingredients on each of the plates, that our heads were spinning.  And in the end, completely unmemorable, other than the outrageous tab.

The wine list was short, expensive, and unimaginative -- considering the proximity to SB wine country.

I don't know what the hype is of this place.  

Avoid.

column12:
i have nothing but good to say about the lark and the wine bistro behind.... we arrived a little early for our dinner reservation so we sat at the bar at les marchands for a delightful, refreshing glass of wine. wonderful environment! we moved over to the lark where we sat a a booth where we could see all that was going on. we had such great service. the food kept coming, and it amazed me;  each dish served at the table got better and better (and it wasn't because of the moscow mules consumed). our party decided to share all the dishes we ordered. we started with the charcuterie plate, pork belly sliders, little gem wedge, the beet salad along with the fried olives. we moved onto the marys roasted chicken - so moist and simple yet flavorful. each dish came out at the perfect time, and each dish was more and more exceptional.  i just might have to go back for the desserts!!!  the milk chocolate pot de creme (an absolute, even if you are not a dessert person),  the cheesecake, black sesame dacquoise, and ice cream sandwich - we did share all of those with coffee. a great ending!
i can't get back soon enough. time to make another reservation!! thank you for such a wonderful evening!
ps...i had to go back the next morning to the lucky penny for a warm scone and latte! perfection!

column12: Been to this place twice now, and it is absolutely amazing.  I've had a LOT of Mexican food, and this is hands down the best I've ever had.  Flavors are absolutely unbelievable.  Only issue is that requesting extra rice or beans costs an extra $3, which is pretty ridiculous.  But I'll keep the 5-star review, seeing as they have a massive unlimited salsa bar of some of the best salsas you will ever taste.  Prices are very reasonable as well, with most non-special meals being under $12 (including chips and the salsa bar).  100% recommend.

column12: Stopped in on a trip through Santa Barbra based solely on the Yelp rating. This place did not disappoint at all! column12:
Meh. 

Not bad. The place is clean and well maintained. The staff is polite and efficient. The food is fresh and the service is quick but the food is just really bland. It is just uninteresting to eat but if you are just hungry and not in the mood for an experience then this place will suffice. 

It is just a shame this place is so highly rated because there is much better Mexican food in the area and I feel like this place kind of gets in the way and almost gives it a bad name. It was too much a fast food place. On the one had, consistency is good but not when quality suffers. 

So not bad, but I have better things to do

column12:
Omg, this place is amazing!!! We came up from LA to visit and saw the rave reviews on yelp. IMO, the hype is worth it.

I ordered the Enchiladas Guadalajara with shredded beef and salsa roja. Some of the best enchiladas I've had, honestly. My boo ordered the shrimp molcajete and he thought it was fantastic. 

I also wanted to highlight their salsa bar - so good!!! All of them, we tried like four and they were all bomb.

The food here is so flavorful. And the price point is so reasonable. Casual vibe too, good for families or a casual date. I highly recommend!

column12:
This place came highly recommended by my friends in SB. 

All I can say is you better come hungry. The steak burrito is HUGE. Now I'm latino, more specifically I'm a mexican and I can tell you that when I say HUGE it doesn't mean "wow that's a lot of food" I mean "GOD DAMN is that a COW in your tortilla???"

I can't imagine people actually finishing these things. I mean unless you have four stomachs or such a fast metabolism that you get rid of half before eating the other half. 

The food wasn't half bad, it was definately a college place. Much like buck fidies in Westwood however much bigger servings and more sitting space. The location is right in the middle of IV and has a cool atmosphere. 

If I were back in IV I'd eat there again after a looong day of hiking, biking, surfing, running, and any other activity to make me so hungry I could eat a cow. Then and only then I would actually be able to eat their "cow in a blanket" which they call burritos.

column12:
I will never go back to this place and I hope no one else will either. For me service is paramount especially when you're going to provide average food for above average prices. 

I was in here one time with a friend, it wasn't too busy and we had ordered some food to go to take to the beach. After 25 minutes, we asked them what the hold up was and they said it's almost done. After another 15 minutes we asked them again, this time they told us that they forgot to put our order in. THEY DIDN'T EVEN APOLOGIZE! I was livid, the whole experience took an hour. I'm writing this about a year later and I'm still getting fired up. This was one of the worst restaurant experiences of my life. I understand things go wrong, mistakes happen, but to have the gall to not apologize for it happening makes me wish the worst upon this business. 

I'm going to have to write a good review now to put my mind back in a good spot.

column12:
Service was good. Food was not.  Coffee drink was burnt.  

I have high standards coming from the Portland restaurant scene.  So, I thought that maybe the burnt latte was just a fluke.  The homemade vanilla syrup had nice flavor, but unfortunately the latte espresso was quite burnt.  It had a cute little face as latte art, though!

Next, my husband could not eat the french toast, it was so hard.  I get that challah bread is hard, but when he couldn't saw through, that's saying something.  

My omelette was super greasy.  I mean grease oozing out.  I don't think it was cooked that well either as the cheese wasn't melted.  And, I'm not sure, but I think they forgot the cheddar cheese - even though they said it was white like the gruyere. 

The home potatoes were pretty hard and seemed old.  They didn't have much flavor either.  Definitely not worth the price for anything we ordered.  

Their homemade toast was pretty good - not amazing, but good with their jam.  

Because we both couldn't eat our food, they ultimately brought out our dishes a second time.  They were a bit better - the French toast could be eaten easier (at least with a steak knife which was provided with it on Take 2), and the omelette cheese was more melted.  Instead of pure grease on the omelette, it was mostly mushroom juices oozing out - still a no-no for omelettes.  My toast on my second plate was only toasted on one side - and not at all toasted on the underside.  The potatoes still tasted old and chewy.  Bleh.  

We were told the chef was brand new and having a rough adjustment.  I hope they get that ironed out as the restaurant has a lot of promise - great location, friendly staff, and a nice owner (at least, we think our primary server was the owner as she waived the cost of our meal, went back to help the chef at one point, and gave us some free pastries for the road - which were tasty).

I would give it another try, but I would inquire about the chef and his experience first.  I would also request that an experienced barista brew my espresso.  The best part of the meal was the fresh squeezed orange juice - expensive, but AMAZING!  I love fresh squeezed OJ.  But, they really do need to get the food quality way up - especially with such high prices.  

Overall, nice service, bad food (except the pastries and jam), and burnt espresso.  But, they are nice to their customers and try and make things right to make up for the bad food.

column12:
Let's say 3.5 stars.

Went here after a long day in Solvang and visiting wineries.  Nice service and comfort food (we had dinner). That said, we enjoyed the food and it was a good place to just relax after a long day up and about.  I'd go back, that's the bottom line.

column12:
Another place I can't believe I haven't reviewed yet!

The husband & I have been going for YEARS now to this place and it all started when we saw a sign with two arrows, one pointing to parking and one pointing to BEER.  We pretty much hit this place up 99% of the time we go to Carp, whether we're camping, staying in a hotel, and/or just passing through to Santa Barbara.  We were part of the Island Nation for a while 

LOCATION/AMBIANCE:  The brewery is where they actually brew, and used to be more of a warehouse.  They've since renovated and its even cooler.  It is next to the train tracks and on the other side is the grass and campsite area, so the ocean is viewable, though somewhat in the distance.  Bummer part is that there's now a park in the grassy area that blocks the awesome view they used to have.  Great for the kids, but sucky for those sitting here.  The crowd is all casual and there are often kids and dogs joining their parents and owners, respectively.  There are locals (some of whom we've met over the years) and there are out-of-towners passing through or who, like us, have this is as a regular destination.  Very laid back and not at all a bar-type feel (except for, of course, the beer).  What I mean by that is that I've never seen a fight, loud drunks, people getting kicked out, etc.  It's a very pleasant experience.

BEER (& OTHER DRINKS/FOOD):  So, it's a brewery and they only have beer, with some bar munchies.  My fave is the hef and the husband's fav is the IPA.   Since they don't serve other drinks or food, they allow for food to be brought in or delivered.  I've also seen women with wine while their husbands come in for beer.

STAFF/SERVICE:  We absolutely adore their staff.  Some of them we don't see any more b/c they moved shifts (and we only come on weekends since we're not locals) and the newer ones are still very nice also.

Bottom Line - Go for a pleasant & relaxing time, but don't get rowdy.  This is not the place for that.

column12:
Professional Staff, Small Portions, and Unusual Menu

First, the staff, from the greeter, to the waiter, to the bus staff were professional and first rate.  That really can make or break a dining experience.

Second, the portions are quite small, so if you order a salad and a main course, you may walk away hungry.  

I had the roasted quail, which is a really tiny bird, in and of itself (a grown man could easily eat two), and the restaurant served up a drum stick and thigh, about 3 tablespoons of meat total.  Granted, it was served with delicious barley and persimmon, but is really more like a small appetizer.  

I also had the roasted vegis, which really should have named, burned vegetables.  Roasted to me means oven roasted so they are slightly tender.  These came out thoroughly blackened and tasted burnt.  No thanks.  

The brownie desert is excellent.

Finally, if you're in the mood for a standard lettuce salad or something really simple, don't come here.  You won't find typical beef  or chicken cuts.  Indeed, the only beef cuts this night was a beef cheek, e.g., a couple tablespoons of meat from the outside of the cow's mouth.  

The food is tasty but the menu is a little weird and it has very small dishes.  I think it is trying to be too upscale and loses sight of what a restaurant should offer in the way of a menu.
