column12:
Started going here recently, and originally loved the vibe and atmosphere of the place. However my several occasions of terrible service here has made me start to avoid it. Twice now I have showed up over an hour after the posted opening time to a closed shop, with no explanation sign or anything. I have to assume that the employees just show up to work late or didn't at all.  There was also an incident where I ordered a chai tea, and received one with espresso in it. I politely told the guy that was working there that I didn't want espresso in it. The guy went off about how they always but espresso in their chai and that he didn't know what I wanted him to do about it. I had gotten several chai's there before and not had espresso put in them, but l I said ok and that in the future I would specify "without espresso" and asked if i could please just get a new one. He literally rolled his eyes, put chai powder in some hot water, and handed it to me. It was absolutely disgusting and pretty shocking behavior.  Besides that particularly bad experience, about 1/2 of the employees have been rude and 1/2 nice. 
Coffee colab could be a wonderful place if the would just get their employees together,

column12:
My boyfriend and I recently moved to Santa Barbara, and so of course we're on the lookout for Mexican food that is good, cheap and authentic. I really can't say if Romanti-Ezer is authentic, but it meets the other two criteria hands down.

This place is not an indoor restaurant. It is a walk-up window and an adjoining patio with seating. You place your order, take your drink and free chips (topped with crumbly cheese and delicious mole, free of charge) and head to the table to wait.

We ordered the loco nachos ($8.50), which are loaded with sour cream, pico de gallo, multiple meats, cheese and beans and could easily feed two people. We also did the asada and chicken tacos, $2.75 each I believe, both of which came on what seemed like a fresh corn tortilla topped with pico de gallo. Yum. They also give you your choice of spicy red salsa and salsa verde at the table. Overall for around $17 we were stuffed and couldn't finish it all.

This is definitely a great place to grab a quick lunch or dinner outdoors off the main State Street drag. Not to mention these guys are open until 3am Thursday-Saturday, so I bet this is a great spot for the after-bar crowd.

column12:
My girlfriend and I decided this was worth a try on our the last night of our central coast road trip. I was, at first, reluctant because I thought the table fires were totally hokey. But, I was wrong.  Very cool ambience. 

And, the food was all really delicious. Lamb shanks were super tender...fall of the shanky tender. And, the shawarma was large and delicious too. Yummy, creamy hummus to boot. The desserts looked great. But,  we were too stuffed!

column12:
I love the atmosphere. My hubby and i have been to luckys before and enjoyed our dinner/evening. Today was mothers day brunch. The restaurant was surprisingly empty. Most everyone at the restaurant smiled and was helpful. But our server fell short. He just didn't project the image of fine dining. My husband and I frequent many upscale restaurants in Santa Monica where we live and lucky's just didn't measure up. Our server couldn't describe a particular dish on the menu and he himself said he should know. Yes, you should. We had to track him down when we needed him. The two other people i was with asked for coffee about 30 minutes after i did. when they received their coffee, mine was almost empty and i wasn't offered a refresher. The crumbs on our table were never wiped off. Little things that an upscale customer comes to expect/notice. The busboys and everyone else was cool, thus the 3 star rating. However at such an upscale establishment, there should be no missing links. On to the food: 
Bloody mary's-the best
Burger-very good
Open face steak sandwich-tender but SALTY
Eggs Benedict-such a disappointment. Sadly. Two very small poached eggs on top of sliced Canadian bacon over soggy English muffins that had been drizzled with butter. The proportions were so off, too much bacon, too small of a muffin and  ridiculously tiny eggs. I had to ask for a third egg. I was too embarrassed to return my dish cuz the muffin was soggy. Side fruit just ok, cut into TOO tiny of pieces, reminding me of canned fruit.
No fancy, unique presentations. 
Coffee is great. Go there if you want. I'm indifferent. Maybe, maybe not?

column12:
I'm from Chicago, and I used to work at a Chicago style pizza restaurant. I have high standards, and this place exceeds my highest expectations. 

The pizza was just the way I remember it in Chicago. The service was excellent too. I used to have to drive all the way up to Zachary's in Berkeley to get legit Chicago style pizza. I am thrilled to now have this place in my own backyard. I'm surprised it took me so long to find out about it.

Concerning the negative reviews, most Californians don't know the first thing about Chicago style pizza, so they have a negative experience when it doesn't meet their expectations of what a pizza is supposed to taste like. Chicago style pizza is more like pie than it is like pizza.  It is very dense, and you normally can't eat more than two slices. So while a large pizza comes out to 40 bucks, each piece is the equivalent to three slices of a normal pizza. Working at a Chicago style pizza place I know it is not uncommon for the large pizzas with a lot of toppings to come out cold in the middle. I read some reviews that said this. This did not happen to my pizza, however, it does happen from time to time because it's such a thick pizza. It's no big deal, you just send it back and the manager will probably give you a discount.

column12:
My group of 6 came here over the Fourth of July weekend for dinner. We lucked out and were able to snag one of the picnic tables outside. We were all pretty hungry, and ended up splitting four pizzas and the burrata & prosciutto appetizer. It was just the right amount of food, though we probably could have eaten more if we had ordered it. 

The highlight for me was definitely the burrata and prosciutto appetizer; it was super fresh & really tasty. The pizzas were also good (loved the crunchy crust), just nothing incredibly unique. There was something on the menu for everybody.

Great ambiance and very fast service (under 15 minutes). Would recommend this place for any group that wants a quick yet nice meal.

column12:
The wood-fired pizzas here are amazing! Tried the lucky margherita and green & black. You should also try their housemade chips. They're flavored with a delicious spice mix. We also tried the chicken salad sandwich which was also super flavorful. 

Try to get here early if you can. There is limited seating outside and it fills up quickly. The best part of this place is the fact that it is fully covered in pennies, literally. It's a place you definitely need to check out!

column12: There are not many food options in the Funk Zone so it was nice to have this area that's right next-door to The Lark which is closed for lunch. I got the pizza that had chorizo and an egg and it was good. The person I came with ordered a salad that you can also get in a sandwich form. You basically order at the counter and then there's outdoor seating for you where you get your own silverware.

column12:
"Solamente una botanita para matar el hambre..." 
We woke up hungry and wanted some really good tacos. Yelp directed to El Sitio, and we were very pleased. Cute little place with little need for atmosphere or seating capacity. Apparently it is named after a little town in Zacatecas which is where my suegros are from - small world. Anyway I got the veggie burrito, my traveling companion had the breakfast burrito. The food came up right away, served with chips and rosted chiles on the side. Although the price was a little more than we were used to, we figured Santa Barbara is more expensive, so we didn't mind. The burritos turned out to be delicious and more than enought to satisfy our hunger. We finishd our road trip all the way to SF without even getting hungry. Would eat there again.

column12:
After a surf session at Hendry's my oldest son and I decided to have breakfast at the Beachbreak. I have fond memories of this place when it was called The Come Back cafe. It became the Beach Break a few years ago. The restaurant itself has indoor booth and table seating (a few flat screens hanging about, muted). They also offer outdoor seating under a large alcove. 

It's a nice, casual, dog friendly location with fairly easy parking located across the street in the city lot. The menu offers the basics (pancakes, french toast, eggs, bacon) as well as the attempted reinvented. Such as Beachbreak Benedict. A lunch menu is also offered in standard fair and flair. All menu items are offered anytime until close. The food is common variety american diner. 

The location is nice and bright with a lot of large windows without direct sun. About 25 tables inside and out. However, based on my latest experience, if more than 7 or 8 tables are occupied I would suggest another restaurant. Simply put, the staff needs a lead waitress or waiter. They seem to have enough personnel,  just very poor communication, with almost comical floor disorganization. 

When we arrived there was no wait for tables, though nor were there any clean tables. Not to worry, we were in no hurry, but after being told to sit anywhere (remember there were no - none - zero clean tables) we waited a good 5 minutes at our chosen table for it to be cleaned. Which, It doesn't sound like a long time, but it is when you're face to face with someones waded paper napkin soaking up whatever is left of their egg and hash combo plate along with their food impacted  fork pointing at you -  mocking your every move. Relief appeared in the form of a busser and as he tidied our table he assured us someone would come by for our drink order ... drink order ? ... it's just juice and coffee, black simple, The cups and pot so close they would cast a shadow upon our heads if direct sunlight was available. Another 5 minutes or more pass and several muted tragic CNN stories later we are greeted by a server and asked our drink order, which as you already know if you got this far, it's coffee black and O.J.  We add to that poached eggs on rye, with bacon. My son requests the Pancakes and eggs. We settle in to another wait another 5 minutes (a pattern) for the cup of Joe to appear, and then correctly assume the food order will take at least 5 times as long.  

While waiting we're asked by two other servers and the original bus boy if we would like something to drink. Clearly being an equal opportunity restaurant in regards to service, other not so patient diners get up and leave, with one asking to see the manager. Suddenly my attention is diverted from my wrist watch and/or attempts to lip-read CNN. "There is no manager" we over hear someone in the kitchen say. The customer leaves to join his departed group on the sidewalk, and as if on cue a waitress brings their food order to their table, now empty, though leaving the food to remain. Our order comes but not before seeing another table vs waitress order confusion, the show continues in that fashion. Our meal arrives edible. Though the toast cold, as were the poached eggs. It seems like a server issue, not a kitchen problem. I did feel bad for the waitresses, they were busy but the place wasn't stormed with customers. The floor staff appeared seemingly very unsure how to handle a workable number of tables. They indeed remained friendly to us, it just didn't seem like they knew what to do. 2 stars.

column12:
Going through a hit and miss phase, but still good. 

Frankly, I used to love this place. It was a 4-5 star yelp review, consistently in my book. In fact, I would have given it five stars today were it not for the past year of weird service and declining food quality.

I'm not sure what's going on but the food used to be pretty vibrant and fresh. It now often tastes bland or re-heated. It used to be amazing service. Prompt, friendly and accurate. Now, it's the definition of hit and miss with both the service and the food quality. 

For example, a recent visit saw being served cold burritos. And not the exaggerated cold, which some people say when it's really just not piping hot. I mean cold to the touch, as if it were made 10 minutes before we even sat down. 

They also messed up our orders twice on recent visits which meant we had to wait nearly an hour for our actual food. They apologized and they gave us some free drinks, so at least there was some kind of recognition of the problem. 

We also order takeout often from this location and they have been on a streak in terms of getting our order wrong despite reading it back perfectly at the time we place it. 

I'm willing to give this place the benefit of the doubt and I'm really hoping that they clean up their act. They have a captive audience in terms of locals traffic in Montecito wanting Mexican food. It just seems like either they are going through some growing pains or they have become lazy and a bit complacent.

column12: This is regarding their catering, which is amazing.  Areli and Pauline are superstars to work with.  Areli is beyond knowledgeable and will actually come and stay onsite for the duration of your event.  I recently worked with them on a 150 upscale event at the SB Historical Society and the whole staff was gracious and kind.  Service was fast and there was TONS of food.  A little grease was spilled on the ground by accident and they immediately mopped it up in order to avoid having the client lose any of their deposit.  All in all, they were polite, put together, tidy, hard working and quick to smile.  They made it all look fun and easy, which is saying something!  I'd strongly recommend them to anyone looking to cater a large event!

column12:
Food was amazing! We got brussle sprouts and pork belly, which were both simply irresistible. We ended up ordering about five other items which were all so delicious, with perfect portions. The alcohol options are also classy and unique and the mule we ordered was amazing.

The atmosphere is so classic and unique, it's a perfect dining experience. The tables have brown paper with crayons in a small cup to draw/write. My boyfriend and I had a ball playing games and writing jokes. 

The only reason I took a star away was because our actual waiter seemed a little disinterested and wasn't very helpful with our I inquiries. But everyone else was amazing and very friendly.

column12: If you are looking to eat outside in Santa Barbara then this is your place. The patio is very spacious with a relaxing atmosphere. My boyfriend and I both enjoyed our meals but unfortunately the service is very slow. While our food arrived promptly, it took some time for someone to take our order. We would have loved to have had a second glass of wine with our meals, but unfortunately we were never waited on again until our check was delivered.

column12:
Great Margarita's Good Atmosphere. 

Came here on a Sunday afternoon.  The restaurant is on a quiet block two blocks East of State Street.  It's right next to an historic adobe, so you get that real Spanish Colonial vibe. 

Sat out on the patio. Ordered margaritas and the carne asada with cheese enchilada. Order came out quickly and was tasty.  

Margarita's definitely had a kick.  I could only have one and a half! 

Overall good place for Mexican food in Downtown.

column12:

Tip: Pay with cash to get a big discount

column12:
I stayed here for about two weeks. So too did two of our guests.

This is one of the nicer properties in the area. it's situated about 15 minutes outside of Santa Barbara proper. Their rates for what they offer were better than those of similar properties within Santa Barbara.

They offer morning breakfast and an afternoon dessert with your room price. 

Breakfasts were delicious...but more so if you're someone who considers 'butter" to be it's own food group. Very un-heart healthy fare.

We switched rooms a couple of times so we tried several during our stay. All of our rooms were worth it for the price they asked. All were kept reasonably clean and in good repair.

Now...with this much of a nice experience with this place you may wonder why I award them only 3 stars. So here's the truth...they're a nice property...but none of the members of our party were ever "wowed" in any manner by either the property or the service. And we spent a good two weeks here.

They offer a private lot for your car...but it can be a cramped pullout...so beware. I inflicted a substantial amount of body damage here to my own car. There's not too much within walking distance but Santa Barbara is a close drive up the freeway.

column12: We both grew up in Santa Barbara, and this is one of our favorite go to restaurants for a comfortable evening out to dinner with friends, by ourselves, or just for happy hour by ourselves at the bar.  Tonight we opted for Happy Hour after attending a really cool free walking tour of the waterfront area of Santa Barbara.  When we come for happy hour we sit at the bar.  The bartender is always super friendly, and makes really great drinks!  Tonight I had Cosmopolitans, and hubby had a beer on tap.  They have a great wine selection too!  We always start with Jill's potato skins (they are the best!).  But all other appetizers on the menu are awesome too!  Tonight we both had the Tuesday evening special, Tri Tip Sandwiches served with salad and fries.  We've tried just about everything on Jill's menu.  The steaks are fantastic!  Nonna's Spaghetti Bolognese is one of my favorite.  Love that when you order a main entrée dinner it comes with soup, salad, & bread (no need to order sides unless you want something extra).  The food is fantastic, prices are fair, and the service is great.  A local's favorite!

column12:
Thank you, Yelp! I can't go anywhere without checking the rating and recommendations first, and because of that, we found this delicious meal in SB!

My BFF and I started with some draft beers, and their homemade sausage and potato skins for appetizers, which were both great. They also served a few pieces of delicious garlic bread. Ooh, I almost forgot their yummy split pea soup and salad!

We shared the NY cut, and it was really yummy. Their meat was exceptionally flavorful, I think because they get it from a local supplier. It came with a potato choice and veggies.

We were here for at least two hours, and had so much good food! The service was great, and after everything we ordered, the bill was ~$70, which is not bad at all for the quality! I highly recommend Shalhoob's.

column12: I am so thrilled to find Uncorked during the pandemic. We have ordered gourmet takeout dinners twice and they are phenomenal: perfectly tender salmon, abundant, smoky brisket, incredible ahi salad, chocolaty desserts. The amazing thing is the price, which is about the same as pizza takeout for a five-star meal. I received excellent advice at the wine counter about a local Pinot noir to go with scallops. The service is wonderful. These are creative local businesspeople working tremendously hard during a challenging time. Let's support them enthusiastically.

column12: This restaurant has AMAZING food!!  We were riding bikes in SB on a vacation there, when we decided to Yelp a good lunch place. We were blown away by the absolutely delicious vegan food!  We had the BLT flatbread, the pulled smoked mushroom sandwich and the polenta fries. All were FANTASTIC. We loved the food so much that we returned to this place for dinner the same night. All the staff were wonderful as well, and the owner even brought us a complimentary dessert of the best baklava and soy ice cream we'd ever tasted. Only wish we lived closer. Even the dedicated carnivores in our group loved the food. It's THAT GOOD. We will certainly be back the next time we are in Santa Barbara.

column12:
This is quite possibly the best restaurant ever.  It has aroused a feeling in me I have never experienced before.  I actually have severe anxiety that it won't last.  NOT because they are doing anything wrong, in fact they do everything right; its just that it feels too good to be true. It keeps me up at night.  

Mesa Verde represents everything a restaurant should be. It has incredible, local and healthy food, served in beautiful, artful ways, by some of the most pleasant people you can imagine.  Of the many times I have visited, I have been greeted personally by the owner EACH time. He always checks in and makes sure every person is having a great experience and if he can't accommodate someones wishes, he goes out of his way to make it right.  In fact, one time there were no seats available so he told my group to come back in half an hour and he would make sure there was space.  When we came back he acted sincerely grateful and ended up not charging us for one of our deserts.  It was honestly embarrassing because there is no way I would ever not come back to this place....

As if things couldn't get any better, I recently learned from a reliable source, unaffiliated with the restaurant, that Mesa Verde is the Santa Barbara Farmers Market's best customer. Proof of the quality of their food, and of their support for the local community.  

The only thing I will caution is that the Macro Bowl, under the entree list, is really more of a salad.  If you are looking for a super healthy, lighter meal, I highly suggest it; but if you want something super flavorful and filling, I would try ANY of their other entrees. 

The last thing I should mention is that you cannot die without trying their deserts.  I am not a desert person at all, but I get it every time I come here.  They are all super unique and delicious.  Enjoy!

column12: This is my new favorite restaurant in the world. We tried the soup,  which was a delicious puree of mushrooms with vegetables. The flat bread has a seasoning called satar. It is a mix of herbs,  sesame seeds and salt. It is TO DIE FOR. The street tacos are made with home made tortillas! The Caesar salad had huge caper berries and a delicious cashew dressing. We ate so much!  Including the empanadas, pumpkin cheesecake, chocolate cake,  chai tea and prosecco. By the way,  the Pumkin cheesecake had a tiny sprinkling of thyme on one corner,  served over marigold flower petals and a coconut cream canelle. Did I spell that right? It doesn't matter!  The food was beyond delicious. It was such a wonderful experience! !!!!!!! Thank you thank you thank you. And one final thank you to Rami, for guiding us through it.

column12:
Bottom line, this place is delicious. it would be worth going to even for folks who are all a hour meat-everything is flavorful and delicious. But-bonus for me- I am a meat eater and my partner is veg, so it's great to go somewhere she can eat everything. 
In particular, the Brussels sprouts were AMAZING, the hummus and baklava were maybe the best I've ever had, and the cashew cheese was fabulous. This isn't a place that tries to imitate meat and cheese, but does its own thing. We will definitely be back. Also great service, and the owner was very welcoming.

By far one of my favorite restaurants in the area, no wait, the planet.

Each meal Mesa Verde offers is bursting with flavor and so beautifully presented and delicately thought through. Even though I'm not a vegetarian/vegan, I honestly prefer it 9 times out of 10 to "real" meat or cheese. 

I have consistently gotten the pizzas and never been disappointed. Left feeling satiated and like my taste buds went to culinary heaven and back. 

The service is somewhat slow, however. Everyone is super nice though, especially the manager who gave my friends and I a free cheesecake for no reason! The prices may be hefty, but so worth it.

column12:
We booked a Sunday brunch reservation with Boathouse for a Bach weekend I was throwing a good friend of mine. I called and let them know it was a special occasion and that I wanted to make the meal very special for the bride. 

After being told this place doesn't take reservations on the weekends I was disappointed but willing to still make it to Boathouse and wait for such a great place. Checked their site and left an email on their inquiry page requesting for the reservation for our large group and hoped that they would make an exception. Sure enough they emailed me and called me back. They let me know they were going to be able to set the reservation but not only that, they also offered us a table VIP bottle service at their local club spot Indocine for the night before our reservation. This was such a great surprise and delight! Of course we took them up on their offer and changed our night plans to make sure to stop in for the table service. I loved that they offered such a special just because we were dining with them and celebrating such an occasion. Goes to show... you should always tell people if youre celebrating a special occasion. 

The club was locally known as a not so upscale place and definitely didn't have the reputation my friend would want to go to - solely because she's a more wholesome gal.... and yet Boathouse exceeded our expectations again! The club played a great mix of hip hop and old 90 classic songs that made us feel very young again and overall had a great time. 

When we arrived the next day for our Brunch reservation... the one thing we didn't plan for was parking. I'd recommend you drop your party off before parking as the overfill lots were a very far walk. Prepare for not a huge lot but know they have two lots and looked like there was more parking when we left at 1:30PM. Our table was already ready by the time we arrived at 11:30AM and the hostess was able to walk us back immediately. Our table was the best table in the whole restaurant :) Front corner table on their patio facing the water shore. Couldn't have asked for a better ending to our great weekend in SB. This was definitely the cherry on the top. Evan was our server - who was amazing!!! So attentive, helpful, suggestive, and we never had empty water glasses which is huge for me. I drink a lot of water and love it when the staff can be on top of their game with the refills. 

Food was awesome. We had all the specials... lobster mac and cheese, chowder fries, and special lobster salad. No one left that place hungry or unsatisfied. Couldn't believe how fresh the seafood was. I ordered the poke and was thoroughly impressed. I'd definitely order the Calamari, Burger, Cornbeef Hash, and Crab Cakes.. which the other girls ordered and loved. 

If you're looking for a friendly staff, a great view, and delicious lunch and brunch options in SB - you MUST stop at Boathouse. I'll be back and will be bringing friends and family so they too can see what this place has to offer....which is more than just their food.

column12:
The Boathouse is a great restaurant tucked into a cove in Santa Barbara. I was there back in October 2020 with my girlfriend and originally went for breakfast, but due to the long wait (1.5-2 hours on a Sunday for a table for two) ended up having lunch. You'll want to keep that in mind and go early otherwise the menu will change and you'll be forced to pick from other options that you didn't originally plan for. 

The beach is beautiful, but busy with families and dogs (only half of the beach was dog-friendly). After putting down your name on the waiting list, definitely grab some drinks at the bar and relax on some benches looking out at the ocean. 

There was a good mix of indoor and outdoor dining, given the circumstances of 2020, and the service was great. They were attentive and helped move an umbrella once the sun started burning my neck haha! We ordered the Angus Burger ($14.95) and the Pulled Pork Grilled Cheese ($15.95). They were both big portions, but nothing to revel about. The burger was huge and can be easily split with someone or taken home for leftovers. The grilled cheese was misleading since it wasn't very cheesy and felt like a regular meaty sandwich with one slice of cheese. While the food was okay, I don't think it justified the price and it's clear that you're definitely paying a price for the location and the view.

column12:
Having heard me speak fondly of my days spent in Santa Barbara almost a decade ago my gf surprised me recently with a last minute trip to The Four Seasons Resort Biltmore for a couple days and it really was the perfect getaway for two.  
       For those unfamiliar with the area the Biltmore is near Montecito(a few miles East of SB) right on Butterfly Beach which may be one of my fav beaches in CA.  It's clean (meaning no dodging balls of tar that you have to deal with at some beaches in the area), the sand is white and soft between the toes, with the channel islands just offshore and  the east-west orientation of the coastline here, you get both breath-taking sunsets AND sunrises.  So the location couldn't be better.  Literally every time you turn a corner on the grounds of the resort it's like you just stepped into a postcard.  And with the sprawling mix of lush but immaculately kept gardens and the early twentieth century architecture cottages throughout, I half expect to stumble into a party thrown by Mr. J. Gatsby himself.  Maybe I've just been living in SF for too long and miss the beach and lush greenery but yes, this place is that grand.    
       Of course being the Four Seasons you expect top notch service but they really outdo themselves here.  It's not the generic blank faced but smiling friendliness you get at most large hotels but actual greet you by name type of service.  Incredibly soft robes and bedding, quality toiletries, fresh flowers everywhere, and the pool at a constant, perfect 80+ degrees....I could go on all day.  Be sure to check out the Beach & Cabana Club nearby which is private but open to guests at the Four Seasons.  The Santa Barbara/Montecito area really does have a glut of great dining options so be sure to venture out for a meal or two but I'd be remiss to not mention the excellent meal had at Bella Vista.  You can socialize at the lounge, wander the beach or find a secret spot for two to lounge privately in the gardens.
       While, beyond the occasional mani-pedi or massage I've never been much of a "spa" guy, but being the good sport that I am we signed up for a couple of the in-house spa treatments.  The couples aromapothecary (that is totally a word I swear) and stone therapy treatments were mind-blowing.  Take my advice and splurge for the 80 vs. 50 min treatment.  If memory serves it was about $450 per couple for the 80 min treatment and was worth EVERY penny.  Wow I had no idea that hot/cold rocks could be so insanely therapeutic but in the right hands they work wonders.  I left there feeling like a new man and the gf was barely able to speak with a trancelike smile on her face as we walked(well I walked and she got carried) back to the room.  PS She had also gotten what I believe was an Avocado-Citrus(?) wrap the previous day which she could not stop raving about for 2 days so I promised I'd get her recommendation in here for any of you ladies out there.   
        OK so that's about it.  This is the perfect place to take the significant other and spend a few days sweeping them off their feet in absolute shangri-la.  I cant say enough about it(though I have certainly tried!).
column14: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column12:
Commonly known to the locals as The Biltmore, this is the definition of luxury at it's best! The grounds are amazing, and service is top notch! From the moment you walk onto the property, you are greeted and are welcomed. When they say you get what you pay for, with The Biltmore, you really do. The Biltmore was recently renovated within the past few years, and from what I understand the new owner is the founder of Beanie Babies (Ty Warner). The rooms are elegant, with modern amenities, while keeping to the integrity of the Spanish architecture. I was fortunate enough to stay in one of the suites, which included a fireplace, and even an ocean view! I was celebrating my anniversary, and upon return to my room after dinner, I was greeted with champagne and a strawberry chocolate tower. Now that is service!
With that being said, this place is not cheap by means, it is probably one of the most expensive resorts in the Santa Barbara area. However if you can afford to splurge just once, The Biltmore is definitely worth it!
column14: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column12:
I have to preface this review by saying most of my negative experiences here I think have to do with the fact that this is a very old property, but several of the problems I noticed are easy fixes that should not fly under the radar at a Four Seasons hotel that charges around $700/night for a normal guest room.  The staff was absolutely fantastic pretty much across the board from the front desk to the breakfast buffet and pool staff, the food was great and the place is absolutely beautiful.  

However, some aspects of this property in my opinion fell below what I believe would be par for the course for a Four Seasons property, such as thin, course bath towels and somewhat chintzy bedding that you'd more likely find at a Best Western.  I was also shocked to find a tub shower with shower curtains in the first room they put us in.  I'm not sure I've ever stayed at a Four Seasons, let alone any 5 Star hotel, that had a darn shower curtain.  I was also pretty surprised that one of our sinks had a very slow drain, which eventually completely clogged by the end of our stay, which was gross.  We had a few other friends staying there that said they noticed similar plumbing issues.  These items should be easy fixes and IMO are inexcusable, especially at a property charging $700/night for normal rooms.  

What was very unpleasant was the fact that this building is old and there is virtually zero acoustical engineering done, and I mean it quite literally that when you are in the guest rooms you can hear people outside your room as if they are inside your room.  We were first placed in a lower level room, and the first morning we were woken up at 6am to the people above us walking around.  They were not being unreasonably boisterous, the sound just traveled right down to our room.  Then construction began at 7am, which I think was directly next to the hotel (not on the hotel property), which kept us up.  Not the fault of the hotel at all, but if the acoustical properties was better, I don't think it would have been so horrible to deal with.  We asked to be moved to an upper level room, and our request was immediately granted, so we stayed our next two nights in an upper level room.  The only problem then was the fact that this room was directly above some kind of meeting room, and our next morning we were unfortunately woken up by a door constantly slamming shut.  I went down to see what the commotion was, to learn it was the door, which did not make much noise when you're using it, but the sound of it slamming shut resonated directly up to our room and was horrible.  The staff member who was going in and out of that room immediately and pleasantly granted my request to simply keep the door open as they went in and out, so the problem was solved, but not after we had our second night of sleep cut short.  The door was not used the morning after our last stay, so our last night of sleep was not cut short and it was a quiet morning, thank goodness. 

Both of the rooms I stayed in had a musty odor, sort of like an old library, although it was much worst in the first room we were in.  The second room was somewhat tolerable.  It was bad enough in the first room that the smell permeated into the bedding. 

Although not a big deal, when we returned to our room after the wedding we attended (at the hotel), neither of our room keys worked, so we had to go all the way to the front desk to get new ones.  They were, of course very apologetic, but it was not what I wanted to be doing late at night. 

My only other unpleasant experience was on our first night at the Tyde's restaurant.  The food was amazing, but the service sucked, and I would have to imagine it was due to the fact that they included gratuity, so their servers weren't working for a tip.  And we only had a 3 person party, and they slapped us with an included 18% gratuity, which I find to be totally tacky, especially at a Four Seasons hotel.  I wouldn't mind it for a large party, but we were three people.  

In sum, if you are looking for a getaway to a very beautiful property and don't care too much about peace and quiet and being able to unwind, this is a great spot.  Between the gardens, tile work and architecture, the property is honestly a piece of artwork.  But, the flip side to that coin coin is the fact that you really don't have peace and quiet in the guest rooms,a and many other problems existed that I felt fell way short of Four Seasons properties.  The sound issue is likely tough to fix without an 8 digit renovation; however, the stupid things we encountered such as crappy towels and bedding, clogged sink, included gratuity on a dinner with bad service, shower curtains, etc, are easy fixes.  I picked this hotel because I had thought paying extra for a Four Seasons experience would guarantee that things like this won't be present, but I was apparently wrong and will be more scrutinizing towards their properties in the future.
column14: Four Seasons Resort The Biltmore Santa Barbara

column12:
We went to see a matinee show of the Santa Barbara Symphony at the Granada Theater on State Street yesterday and went to Tupelo Junction, which is next door, for lunch. 
The service was good and quick. There were three of us and we ordered a burger, pulled pork sandwich and mac n cheese. All the items were just OK, nothing special. With tax and tip, the bill came to $75 for the three of us. No need to spend that kind of money for something that isn't really that special. 
Santa Barbara has a lot of restaurants. Go elsewhere.

column12:
I came in for an early dinner on a Monday and was their only customer. I was highly confused if I was supposed to wait to be seated, seat myself or order at the counter. After approaching the counter, they said I could take a seat if I wanted (still confused- is that what I'm supposed to do?!) Anyway, I took a seat and they DO have table service for dinner. 

It is a cute café style restaurant with a deli counter (some bakes goods and salads) and a mini-accoutrement shop off to the side with wine, jellies, some small gifts, etc. It is a pretty casual but modern atmosphere with not so casual prices. I gathered the theme was healthy food with a Moroccan twist. They don't have a large menu for dinner items, but I actually like that as I frequently have difficulty making decisions. I opted for the Kale Caesar and added Grilled Salmon. It was honestly just okayyyyyy- could've used some sea salt or more flavor in the dressing. Staff was friendly and I enjoyed my experience (after the awkward seating sitch) so I'd give this place another go.

column12: We were in the mood for pizza. Since this was our first trip to Santa Barbara, I relied on Yelp for suggestions. This restaurant got good reviews and was close to the art institute so we gave it a try. First, we loved the ambience. It has a European feel and a comfortable atmosphere. Our waiter was excellent. The food was delicious. We started out with the cauliflower, which was very tasty. We also ordered a pizza and a side of rapini. Both were outstanding. We like thin crust pizza and this one was delicious. I highly recommend this restaurant.

Beautiful scenery looking out to the ocean. The food was not good  ordered the Salmon Vera Cruz no flavor at all, I was very disappointed when I noticed my meal had canned veg-all in it. The Salmon was too tough to chew  also had calamari which was not bad. Unfortunately I will not return.

column12:
We received great service here!  They were dog friendly on the patio, which made the experience even that much better.  We had the Rincon Brewery Haole Boy Lager​,
(American Lager,​ 4.6% ABV​, 10 IBU​) which was a perfect light beer if you like a like lager.  We had the Hummus as an appetizer which comes with small warm pretzel bites and dipping veggies... deliciousness!!!!  Price was fair and the environment was warm and friendly.  Highly recommend for couples or families.

column12: Like some reviewers have mentioned this is fancy Mexican. The food can be hit and miss. Some of my favorites are the Cazuela con Chorizo Rojo and Pork Belly Quesadilla. The ceviche, guacamole, and salsa selections are all good choices. The cocktails are some of the best in SB. I mainly come here when I am in the mood just to hang, have a few drinks, and enjoy the lovely location. The atmosphere both inside and out are awesome. I don't love the food enough to come here regularly, but it's more the style that I don't prefer rather than the execution.

column12: There's a parking lot directly across the street that's FREE for the first hour and 15 minutes... more than enough time to get in and out. Silverware and napkins are kept on the table so you don't have to worry about grabbing any, just carrying your food. They have many food and drink options( gluten free, vegan). The employees aren't overly friendly and most likely won't reach out if you look like you're needing assistance. Once you start asking the questions they will assist. It was on the pricey side for deli like food. $36 for 2 waters, and 2 entrees each with 2 sides.

column12: My mom and I went for our first wine tasting and were beyond satisfied with our experience with captain jacks tours. We had Amir as our personal chauffeur AND photographer and he was more than we could have wished for. So pleasant, funny, and interesting to talk to as well. Was a little nervous since we were the only two doing a tour that day (woohoo for midweek if you're looking for an absence of crowds!!) but he made us feel like queens and was happy to accommodate all of our wishes. He had a lot to offer in knowledge about the wineries and the general area as well. Will definitely be requesting him if we decided to do another, which very well may be in the future.

column12: I highly recommend The Creekside for private events. We rented the whole restaurant for my Mothers rustic wedding and we were completely satisfied. The renovation at this venue is beautiful and it truly provided a stunning setting! Dave was great to work with leading up to the wedding. Behnom was incredible with the day-of operations. He was like my personal assistant ensuring that I was happy and enjoying my family and friends. To be honest, all of the staff were very attentive and easy to work with. Our guests enjoyed all of the delicious options the buffet offered. I was a bit concerned about the parking but that went smoother than predicted as we encouraged guests to carpool. Again, I HIGHLY recommend this venue for a private event and for a causal bite to eat!

column12:

column12: The food was fine, but I'm giving them 2 stars because of the experience. I flew in to see my sister who had just been released from the hospital. We were also both sick with the flu and wanted a nice dinner. We thought we would be walking in to a nice restaurant, but little did we know, we walked in to A HIGH SCHOOL CAFETERIA. A group of 30+ brought a speaker, were screaming, chanting, banging on the tables etc. I understand that it isn't the restaurant's fault if people are inconsiderate and rambunctious, but the management didn't bother to say anything even though the entire restaurant was clearly irritated. I didn't think it was fair to ruin the experience of several parties for fear of putting a small damper on one.

column12:
Ordered:
1- margarita pizza (tomato, mozzarella, and basil)
Large size- enough to share 2-4 people. 
However, it tasted like a childhood microwaveable boxed pizza from the freezer section of a grocery store. Very disappointed given the hype. Score- 1/5. Rather have digiorno pizza. 

2 - mixed green salad 
Average. Very small sized salad. About 2/3 cup of a salad or less 

Service - mediocre. 
Had reservations & restaurant half full. Still waited 15 mins for table set up. Food took 30 - 40 mins to come out. 

Would not come back. 
Overpriced for size and service.

column12:
After reading the reviews of local restaurants while visiting the area for the weekend my wife and I were excited to try the food at Trattoria Mollie however we weren't even able to make it that far...

We were in the area about an hour before they opened for dinner service and (based on the reviews about the food) decided to wait for a table. After waiting outside for half an hour a couple walked up and a staff member unlocked/opened the door for them, sat them, and took their drink orders (all of this 30 minutes prior to their official open time).  When I walked up to her to see if we could be seated as well, my wife and I were told that the other couple was "an exception to their rules" and that if we wanted a table we would have to wait outside the additional half hour as there was no one ready to take care of us.  Before we could even ask why would couldn't just sit down with a glass of water and wait for the kitchen to open, she turned around and walked away. She didn't try to accommodate us at all let alone apologize for the inconvenience.

At that point we felt completely disregarded. It was as if we didn't even matter to them. When we go out to dinner we love to have the full experience; a nice staff, a good bottle of wine, appetizers, deserts, ports, etc. We both have experience in the food service industry and were shocked that this sort of discrimination had happened to us.

Such a pity, we would have loved to taste the food but unfortunately we will not be coming back.

column12:
Great location. Lovely atmosphere. The positives end there. I don't know any other way to say it: the food is just plain bad. Lamb meatballs needed something. Salt? Pepper? I don't even know. They were so bland. My husband ordered the sea bass. Not edible. I'm not kidding, it was horrible. I got the bucatini which was actually decent, which was a good thing since my husband had to share it so he wouldn't go hungry. We told the manager that the sea bass was bad (they asked if we wanted it boxed when they saw it was barely touched - answer, no) and they gave us a free desert. I got a coffee which was neither hot nor fresh, and we tried the caramel hazelnut chocolate bar. The gelato was pretty good, the bar was not worth a second bite. It was like a giant piece of really mediocre candy. 

I usually do not complain at restaurants and leaving this sort of review makes me uncomfortable but I am really hoping this place gets it act together. We have needed a nice restaurant in the east beach area and I am rooting for them. Here's hoping they can shake up this menu and get some food worthy of the location.

column12:
Located inside the Santa Barbara Inn, Convivo Restaurant was a Incredible dining experience!

We made reservations for outside but it was too chilly, even with heaters. We asked to sit inside and they accommodated us within minutes.

The restaurant has a wonderful view of the beach due to the large glass patio doors and  entry way next to the bar.

The table service was quick and the food was delicious. We had the seafood pasta, breaded pork chop and  margherita  pizzas.

Next time we're in SB, we'll definitely be returning!

column12: This place is average. I came for happy hour, but had a couple of lunch entrees as well. The happy hour foods were not worth anything, but the onion tart was pretty good. If the quality of food served at dinner is equivilent to the tart it should be good. However, if it has the quality of the happy hour foods stay away. Had 5 of their happy hour items and none were any good, in fact they were pretty bad.

column12: I'll be honest: their donuts are amazing. Second only to maybe Anna's. But, Their service is awful. AWFUL. We ordered three drinks and after a 20-minute wait, put came two. We waited for the third, but the woman walked out of our view and after we patiently explained that we ordered three drinks (and showed her our receipt) she groaned loudly and slowly began to make our third drink. She stopped in the middle and after waiting even longer we walked out. Not an SB native but I've been to Anna's a few times and compared with them, God was this a bad experience. Worst I've had here. Wish I could say that the donut quality outweighs the service, but it just doesn't. I wouldn't come here again. Go somewhere else

column12:
Good food, weird service, overly priced. The decor is charming, good for dates but not for business meetings nor kids.

The food was well prepared and full of flavor. Try the swordfish or the mushroom ravioli, and drink the lemon/blueberry virgin drink. Get dessert somewhere else.

column12: So this place get one star and not because of service. Yes I know! The food was just terrible. Maybe because I'm from the bay area and have tried various Chinese places, but I couldn't even eat the food. Everything was extremely salty. Fried rice tasted like it was soaked in soy sauce. The other fried rice dish, the curry one, was even worse. They charged extra $1 to make the curry fried rice vegetarian using tofu. They said the fried rice had veggies which is why they charge $1 more for the tofu. If you view the picture, it came with hardly any veggies to even count it as a veggie fried rice. It seriously is a joke. It was a waste of money for sodium overload that just gives you high blood pressure and puts terrible strain your on your body. Not worth it.

column12: Great casual date night spot! I recommend sitting on the patio in the back, very quaint. I got the shrimp specialty - it was delicious but you must love garlic. It has a ton! Margaritas were decent flavor wise but pour seemed short. The chips and salsa were delicious. You're given three different types of salsa. Service was good and employees were friendly.

column12:
Drinks are okay.  They use milk powder and syrup to flavor and sweeten their teas.  The vibe and decor is cute.  Targeted for college students with way too much $ and willing to spend big bucks for mediocrity on drinks and snacks.  
Ordered the popcorn chicken...small size for the price...fried pork chop...literally a box of pork chop cut into strips...on the dry side....but comes without anything else, no sauce, not rice/noodles...fish balls with curry...was cold...they didn't microwave it enough or something...they was cold...yikes!

All things considering...I knew what I was walking into and was prepped to pay for over priced bobas and snacks...however, what annoys me the most are the unapologetic dismissive attitude and rudeness  of the girl working there!  So rude, go to order, never greeted me or made eye contact.  Her body posture told me that I was bothering her for ordering or asking questions about a drink.  Snatched my credit card, ran thru the system...no thank you, here is your receipt...nothing.  Handed me the curled up receipt with her 2 fingers.  Seriously?  Bad service, I understand but bitch face service is a whole new level. Felt like I was dealing with my teenage daughter the whole time after I grounded her.

column12:
I was ecstatic when this place opened, SB has needed a cider spot for my fellow non-beer drinking  friends. Their 4-play tasting flights are a must try for your first time. The flavors are always rotating and the staff get really creative with suggesting great combinations and rim toppings. 

The indoor and outdoor seating is cozy and there's a ping pong table! There are also numerous board games and party games to play. This is a great place to bring out of town guests to get a taste of SB vibes or just enjoy happy hour. 

If you follow them on Instagram, you'll get sneak peeks into upcoming flavors, food vendors, and trivia nights!

column12: This is our 2nd year at the festival. If you are a seafood lover,this is the place for you. Lobster,  paella, uni, oysters and so much more. All fresh and waiting for you to buy and devour. Parking can be tough just get there early and have a great time listening to live music and awesome food. Beautiful weather to top it off.

column12:
Tamara and her crew were so amazing. I really wanted a family style meal for our wedding reception and all other caterers were going to charge us an insane amount just because of that. Tamara was so willing to work with me and make sure we got everything we wanted. We did family style tacos, a chips and salsa bar, and passed ceviche. She provided a bartender and also managed the rentals (tables, chairs, glassware, etc.). Because of her and her team, my husband and I had nothing to worry about at the wedding and were so pleased with the result. The food tasted amazing! 
We can't thank Tamara enough!

column12:
If it has to be fast-food Americanized Chinese, I won't even consider Panda Express. But Pick up Stix is the best you can get in under 5 minutes. While their portion sizes tend to be under-whelming, their ingredients and general tastiness is a good compromise to the pig slop served elsewhere. This particular location is usually pretty clean and generally has friendly staff.

If you are in a hurry, stop by Pick Up Stix for some decent food.

column12:
The pulled pork was good but service wasn't. After standing at the counter in a nearly empty restaurant,  someone clearly with a cold finally waited on us. And it seemed more like we were an inconvenience rather than customers. If a food server is sick, I don't think they should be waiting on customers or handling food. 

Then there's the proselytizing. I don't care what religion people are but I don't want religious messages hanging on the wall staring me in the face while I eat.

column12:
Francisco and his associates waiting on our table were attentive and wonderful. Unfortunately the appetizer flat bread came out cold and looked lovely but when I tasted it. It tasted burned even though it wasnt. hmmm 
the amuse bouche was melon that tasted of salmon. odd
the the pastas were fair not exceptional. 
the yellowtail sashimi appetzer was amazing. Get it!
Tiramisu and berries desserts were lovely. 
The Food should match its environment. 
I must say they have a long way to go to match the food to the amazing environment. 
Best of success to you Caruso's. I really want to return to an amazing meal
